****PETronus Rescue endeavors to include all pertinent information for each of the dogs within our organization with regard to approximate age, potty training status, kennel training status, temperament, activity level, dog/cat friendliness, etc in an effort to give those considering adopting as much information as we have.  Inquiries requesting additional information will not be returned, due to limited volunteers. Thank you for your understanding **** 

Meet Ginger.

Ginger was adopted from a local high kill shelter and returned because she is not good with small dogs and they had a small dog. NO small dogs or cats for this girl, however, she gets along great with male and female dogs her size with proper introductions.

Ginger is working on her leash manners and socialization outside of the home but does great in a crate, has great house manners, and loves to play outside with older kids and doggy friends! She loves people, and will cuddle up on the couch after an afternoon of playing in the yard. Ginger is very nervous outside of the home, obviously hasn’t had much experience out in public. She would do best in a home as a house dog and not so much an out and about dog. 


Her adoption fee is $200, which includes her vaccinations, spay surgery, and microchip. We are located in Houston, TX, but she can also be transported to an approved adopter in WA for an additional  transport fee of $250.

If you would like to add Ginger to your family, you can fill out our adoption application here http://bit.ly/PRAdoption and we will be in touch soon!

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Luca!  If you have a quiet home and the time and patience to win over a wary dog, then I have a match for you.  I was born in November of 2019 and was brought back to the shelter because I'm a fearful dog and not a good fit for a family with kids.  Once I came back to the shelter, it took a long time for me to allow the staff to leash me and take me outside. I just do not know how to trust.  I now love to romp and play with the people I know. I've made some huge strides!  It is everyone's hope that I am given a chance to be comfortable in a home.  Please note that if you'd like to add me to your home, you'll need to make a couple of visits to the shelter to spend extra time with me prior to adoption.  Apply for me today!

My adoption fee is $60. Adoption applications can be filled out at CCHS or online through our website, www.cchs-petshelter.org. Applications are not first come, first served. All applications will be reviewed by the adoption committee and the home chosen will be the one considered to be the best match. All dogs and puppies have been vaccinated for Distemper and Bordetella, dewormed and microchipped. If old enough, they will be vaccinated for Rabies and blood tested for Heartworm, Lymes, Anaplasmosis and Erlichiosis. Dogs and puppies will be spayed or neutered before adoption.

CCHS is proud to be a No-Kill Humane Society. As a private, non-profit charity, our work depends on donations and volunteers to keep going. We are committed to helping the animals that enter our doors and finding each the best possible forever home. CCHS has been inspected and licensed by the Department of Animal Health - DATCP. Our license is #268235-DS

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

YES, WE'RE STILL ACCEPTING APPLICATIONS FOR ALDER.

**
Alder will be placed in the Phoenix metro area, for proximity to our rescue (home checks, follow up visits, visit to finalize adoption) and for access to our veterinarian. Sorry, no exceptions.

**

Alder's adoption begins with a Foster-To-Adopt arrangement that continues until he has completed Basic and Intermediate Obedience Training.

**

Meet Alder, who was found protecting his tiny siblings (or maybe daughters?) Maple and Juniper where they were all been dumped in rural Arizona! He's SO FRIENDLY and funny, soft as silk (maybe part Pei?), and takes treats gently.

Alder will thrive in a family with an adult who is home most of the time. He is young, yearns to please, and is very quick to learn! Dog-savvy children older than eight years, please, as he is small but runs fast and plays hearty!

Alder loves people and his face lights up when he sees new humans and friendly dogs. He would love an active family that appreciates his sense of humor and fun. He is such a happy and delightful dog and absolutely craves companionship! Alder requires a fenced yard for frequent play and also because he is sometimes vocal when his humans are out of sight and he's feeling lonely!

If you believe you're a possible match for Alder, please complete an adoption application! Please include information about your experience with raising and training a puppy.

"Companion animal" means, needs at least one other friendly, playful dog that lives full-time in the same household.
"Fenced yard" means, a backyard that is adjacent to and connected with your residence. (It does not mean a nearby fenced area/dog park.)
Gates must have padlocks and thresholds (cement or buried pavers to prevent digging.)
Yard and patio must be free of debris and have room for dogs to run and play *on a lawn and/or in a very shaded area.* Please do not invite us to your home if you have not yet landscaped your yard!
"Swimming pool" means a private, in-ground, year-round pool that is available to the dog daily or multiple times per week.
We do not place dogs in situations where there are "drained" or empty swimming pools, which are a fall hazard and contribute to the propogation of mosquitos.
Last and not least, we DO NOT adopt to students as we have found that they often do not know or anticipate where life will take them.

Discussion about a dog - including scheduling of a home check or other dialogue - cannot occur until we have received your completed adoption application. NO EXCEPTIONS. Thank you!

animal.description:
Hi
I'm Granny Big Lots and I'm looking for a comfortable, loving home to spend my golden years in
I'm around 11 years old and I was diagnosed with Hypo Thyroidism so I take meds (they are not expensive) and I've already lost 6 lbs! 
Walking was very hard for me when I first came to my foster home but I've improved so much and now I can go for strolls!

animal.description:
Meet Harlequin, or Quinn as he likes to be called. He is a 4 year old catahoula. Looking for a dog that would LOVE to go on a hike with you? Well then Quinn is your guy!

Quinn's perfect match would be a family who lives in a house, since apartment living would not suit this large fella - he needs room to romp and play- it's his favorite pastime! A good sized 6ft privacy fence for his safety would be ideal.

Due to Quinn's size (70lbs) and his playful demeanor he would be better matched to a home with older children 10 and up. While we are unsure of Quinn's feelings towards feline friends, we do know Quinn would be able to live with another doggie friend who is submissive and enjoys to play. Quinn has done fabulous with other dogs with slow and proper intros. He would love someone active as he loves to romp outdoors and to go for walks. He is great on a leash and wants to learn! He loves to cuddle but he is not a couch potato by any means.

Quinn needs someone with large breed experienced who can be a confident and solid pack leader willing to work with him so he can be his very best. We promise you if you take a chance on Quinn he will pay you back tenfold. He truly is an amazing dog.

Please be sure you have the time, commitment and experience to dedicate to our sweet boy prior to filling out our adoption application. 

The Catahoula is a breed of dog like no other. Extremely loyal and protective, a true diligent worker, and will be the best friend one could ask for. Exercise is a must or they will get unruly. 

Dog ownership is a very serious commitment and it is one that should be for a lifetime. It is not something to dive into without a lot of thought and research.

Adopt Quinn pawzabilitiespa.org/adopt

Foster Quinn pawzabilitiespa.org/foster

Our veterinary partner estimates that Sarah is 2 years old at the time of intake in August 2020. Sarah is good with people of all ages and other dogs. We pulled this sweet girl from a kill shelter where she was languishing most likely just days away from euthanasia due to a medical condition. Though only 2 years old, Sarah is suffering from heart failure which caused her belly to fill up with fluid. So even though she was completely emaciated, her belly was huge. Our veterinary partner drained the fluid from her belly and she is now on the medications she will require. Sarah is a happy couch potato/lap dog who is easily trainable as she is motivated by food and treats. Sarah deserves a chance to live a normal, happy life and we know we will find that special someone to be Sarah's "person." If you are that amazing person willing to give Sarah the happy life she deserves, please apply online to adopt Sarah (GA) at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

My weight is: 70lbs

I love play dates with my friends, doggie parks, road trips, warm baths, ears cleaned and massages. I am looking for a loving home with maybe another pup or cat. I am so sweet, pretty and we behaved that once you meet me, you'll love me.

Sebastian came to our shelter by way of our friends at Baldwin County Animal Control in Georgia. He ended up at the shelter when his owner passed away suddenly. Sebastian is about 2-3 years old and weighs about 50 lbs. 

Sebastian was frightened by new people when he first arrived at our shelter. We have been working with him and he has made vast improvements. Sebby is the type of dog that will “pick his people,” so we require approved adopters to visit multiple times to build trust with him. 

Sebastian MUST be adopted to a home with Chow (or akita/shar pei, shiba) experience.  There will be no exceptions.  He needs a quiet, adult home WITHOUT cats.  Once you win him over, he will be your best friend for life. Sebby gets along wonderfully with other dogs.  

Sebastian is neutered and vaccinated for Rabies, Distemper, and Bordetella. He tested negative for heartworm and is current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention too. Sebastian is also microchipped with a lifetime registration.

animal.description:
Sanctuary Notes on Savanna: Savanna was nicknamed Smiley, as when she first came to us she would watch us with interest and a big smile on her face. She came in with a group of seven other pyrs from the neglectful situation described below. I thought for sure that she would be the first to warm up to us as she seemed to have the most confidence and did not seem as fearful as the others, but she would always keep her distance, playfully smiling at me from behind a tree. We now have them in an area with access to indoors and outdoors in our main building, where they are getting used to seeing us all throughout the day. We have found that although Savanna seems to be adventurous and inquisitive, she is still unwilling to let us actually pet her and will skip away last minute. Because of this we are going to switch gears and give her and Leo more undivided one on one attention to help her past this hurdle. She will happily stand at arms length from me, smiling and eat treats, but gets confused when we reach out to make physical contact as this was not likely the norm in her last "home" We have high hopes that we will have the needed breakthrough with Savanna, and would love a specific patient foster home to help her get there!

Group notes: Milo took in seven beautiful yet under-socialized Pyrenees that had been seized from a hoarding situation, but were then set for euthanasia due to lack of space at the shelter. We have been working with them to gain their trust as they were not raised as family members, and some are making great strides. Because of this, they are looking for very patient, understanding and rural homes that will continue to work with them to help them to realize their full potential. 

None of these dogs have ever bitten anyone and even the most fearful will run and bark when scared or unsure of a situation rather than show outward aggression. They had not been raised walking on a leash and were living in a large fenced area together which they had never left and were used for breeding, cared for by a man with mental illness until seized by animal control for neglect. Because they were not raised with livestock ( and do show a prey drive towards cats) they would not be a good choice for someone looking to have them guard animals on a farm, and because they were not raised in a home, they do not understand commands etc, but they do prefer to go potty outside and are loving sleeping on cozy beds. They will follow direction when a routine is established and will go inside or out as a group when asked. They do love each other and will bound around and play, but we do not know how they would do with other dogs given that Pyrenees imprint with the animals that they are raised with and these guys can get worked up as a group when there is a dog unknown to them outside the fence, for this reason if there is another dog in the home their interactions would have to be closely monitored in order to make sure that they are a safe fit together. From what we have seen, they are open and excepting of puppies even if outside the family group, but again supervision would be key! If you are willing and able to help one of these gorgeous dogs, please send applications to foster or adopt to sanctuary@milofoundation.org

Thank you for considering adoption of a Milo Foundation Sanctuary dog.

Our Sanctuary is where our rescued dogs who have had difficulty in a home in the past, have behavioural issues, or too much energy, or for some, aggression issues with other dogs, or intense stranger danger that make them more difficult to safely and happily live in urban environments.
These are not beginner dogs or for the most part nor are they for families with children. IF you are looking for an easy dog to add to your family, we suggest looking at the dogs at our Adoption Center, Milo Pt Richmond. 
BUT, if you can offer a safe and nurturing home to a dog with some behavioural "quirks" please do send an application today. Thank you.

animal.description:
Athena

Age: ~ 6 yo
Sex: SF
HW Status: Negative
Weight: 70lbs
Natural Tail and Ears

Available: NOW

I would like to tell you a story and introduce myself. My name is Athena and I am a 6 year old Boxer and once had a family of my own. Suddenly my family abandoned me and I have been alone ever since. I have been lucky to have been rescued by Rockin P Rescue where I have now lived for almost a year. I am so thankful for Angie and her team but I am really sad not to have my own family anymore. I ask myself if I did something wrong that I needed to live at a rescue for so long, but I can’t find and answer.
A few things about me that I would like you to know. I love to play a LOT when I am able to get out of the kennel. If you stomp your feet at me I will get so excited and want to catch you. I love to run and jump around with the people that take time with me and play. I have gone on a lot of field trips to Encore Enrichment Center for Shelter Dogs to learn how to listen to commands. They say I do really well and listen to them like a champ! It makes me happy to know I can make humans happy so I try hard to learn as much as possible. They have told me that if someone adopts me they can bring me to Encore for two more free lessons so my human family can see how good I am and let me show off my listening skills.
I do not like other dogs and some of the humans that have met me don’t understand why. I am not sure either but we all have our own personalities and this one is mine. I would love to find a forever home with a family that only wants me in their life. I promise to love you so much and show you all the time. I want a human family so badly and wish someone would choose me to take home. I have seen so many other dogs come and go to new homes, but not me. I think it’s because when they see me in my kennel there are other dogs around me so I bark at them and get a little nervous. Like I said earlier, when I am out of my kennel and just around humans I am relaxed and like to play with them and just have fun being a Boxer.
If you are thinking about adopting an “only” dog please remember me and imagine how happy you could make me. I super paw promise to give you love in return and will never let you forget what a great thing you did by rescuing me.

This dog is being fostered near Jacksonville, AL. You must be willing to drive part if not all of the way to pick up this dog for adoption unless transportation to another state has been arranged.  Please contact us with any questions. 

Please visit Rockin' P Rescue, Inc. to submit an online adoption application. 


Adoption contributions are as follows: 
* $300.00 for a dog 6 months and under
* $250.00 for a dog aged 7 months to 1 year 
* $225.00 for a dog over one year

animal.description: Kavik is an Alaskan Husky mix and is a very loving dog who found himself at the Wichita Animal Shelter. He's a bit nervous meeting new people but warms up quickly and has no problem cuddling with you if you if you can keep his attention. He has tons of energy, so an active family is a must for him. IHe is great with the kids ages 6&10 in his current foster home, but needs to work on social skills. He wants to say hello to every animal but comes off as a little too eager/intrusive when given the chance to say hi. He wants to be an alpha so he can be persistent about shows of dominance with other dogs. He has little interest in playing fetch. He is a great running companion but needs some work to slow down on walks (gentle leader works ok but it bugs him). He is mostly house trained. He has been kenneled when he can't be watched and shows signs of separation anxiety when he's left alone. He has only had a couple of accidents inside the house. He has a scar on his right cheek and left front leg for reasons unknown. He does know some common commands like sit and come and is very food driven. He is a fast eater but hasn't shown too much protective actions towards people getting close while he's eating. He does not like being pulled by his collar by your hand (maybe a trigger from past human aggression?) but is ok when its done with a leash. Overall he is a great dog that just needs a little training and a family who will love him and love to be active with him.

animal.description:
Calliope aka Cat

Located in Sidney NE
1 year old approximately 
Shar Pei and Bulldog Fusion 
VERY Dog friendly 
NOT cat friendly 
NOT good with small kids (conflicting reports on this) but I think she would be just fine with older kids 
Slow to warm up to new ppl especially men
House trained
Crate trained and knows a couple basic commands
Was the more shy of her and her sister but she's a super outgoing, playful and silly girl now
Fully vetted
50lbs (she's very solid, kinda like a bulldog)

Cat aka Callope was found with her sister Tullulah when they were babies. These 2 girls were found by a private citizen rescuer dumped on the Mexico/TX border. The finder kept them and eventually listed them for rescues or adoption however no one was interested. She had them a YEAR when we happened to see their posting. The rescuer actually got Covid and almost died, she is still fighting and has a lot of residual medical issues from it. This sweet woman and these girls needed help. They are not in any way "aggressive" just scared, when joining new households, which is pretty expected. Cat LOVES to play with other dogs, she has excellent recall and she loves to cuddle! Cat was attacked by other dogs as a puppy so her left jowls are shorter than her right, but she is seriously the sweetest girl! This little bowling ball and Pei combo is so truly unique and so crazy sweet we are certain her people are out there waiting for her! 

If you think those "people" may be you please contact us!!

To Contact Us

Message us through our website http://www.highplainspaw.org

Message the Facebook Page at https://www.facebook.com/HighPlainsPAW

Fill out our Adoption Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/adoption-application

Fill out our Foster Application at https://www.highplainspaw.org/foster-application

Email us at highplainspaw@gmail.com

Call our voicemail at (402)957-1578

 $200.00 Adoption Fee Each (however our main concern is finding a home(s) that fit for these girls
(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

WE DO NOT HAVE A FACILITY ALL OUR DOGS ARE LOCATED IN FOSTER HOMES. This means there is no place for you to go in person to view our dogs. We ask that an application be filled out and we will go from there!

animal.description:
Meet Cookie!  Her name should be bubbles because that is her favorite game. Cookie will chase bubbles all day. Cookie is about 3 years old. She is a lovable mix breed female. All her shots are up to date and she is spayed. She is looking for a forever home ready to accept all the love she has to give. She loves to cuddle on the couch with you and will not wake you up at 5am to eat. Cookie likes to sleep in. She is house broken but is very talented at getting out of a crate. She would be best in a house without cats. She does ok with other dogs but likes attention so an only animal house would be ideal. She does well with kids and would do well in a house with school age kids and older. Cookie gets very excited when kids are playing and wants to get in the middle of the action.  She walks well on a leash and does well on car rides. She is a very easy going dog. She is not a jumper unless you let her, but we encourage her not to jump up on people when greeting them. She loves a tennis ball but not the best at giving them back. She has mastered sit and shake. Do you have room on your couch and your lap for Cookie who is so full of love?

Are you interested in adopting Cookie or another JCAPL pet you have seen? You'll need to start by completing an adoption application, available online at our website: www.jcapl.org. There is no obligation to adopt by completing an application, however, we do recommend submitting an application as soon as you find an animal you are interested in. We review applications in the order they are received.

Completed applications can be sent via email to adopt@jcapl.org , faxed to 919-300-5524 or delivered in person by visiting us at one of our adoption events on Saturdays at PetSmart in Garner (White Oak Shopping Center). 

We will contact you as soon as possible once we receive your application.

Thanks for thinking adoption!

ATTENTION: All of our dogs are in private foster homes. We do NOT have a kennel with multiple dogs. If you find a dog you want to meet in person, please go to www.secondchancedogrescue.org and complete an application. We will make every attempt to process all applications within 3 business days of receipt.

// //

Meet Elvis! This sweet little man is looking for someone to "Love me Tender". Elvis is a 12 year old, five pound Chihuahua that is deaf and has visual impairments- so if you snore or have a bad hair day, Elvis won't mind a bit! He learns his way around his new surroundings and is nervous at first but gets more comfortable over time. Elvis loves the sunshine! Although he is still getting used to walking on a leash, Elvis loves to cruise around and bask in the sun on the patio at his foster home and explore on the grass. Elvis is working on his house training. This "Hunk of Burning Love" is a good eater, much like the King himself, and often comes into the kitchen to see if it's meal time. Elvis sleeps well and doesn't seem to mind dogs or cats. Little Elvis is easy going and although he will need a little extra support to help him adjust we are sure that you "Can't Help Falling in Love" with him. Elvis is neutered, microchipped and current on his vaccines. His adoption fee is $200.

All Second Chance Dog Rescue dogs are spayed/neutered, are up to date on vaccines and have microchips prior to adoption.

Adoption fees vary depending on age of dog. Fees help Second Chance Dog Rescue cover spay/neuter costs,

vaccinations, medical treatments,

food and supplies. Please go to

www.secondchancedogrescue.org

and complete an application today!

All dogs live in private foster homes until they are adopted.

animal.description: This sweet girl was probably hit by a car, but that was long ago.  She was not walking well when she was impounded in Los Angeles but those days are over and she is getting around well now.  Some slippery surfaces set her back but she takes everything in stride and holds her own.  So glad we took got her to safety.  Dottie is the perfect example of a MCR dog.  She would not have been adopted, would have died in a dog pound.  And what a shame.  Dottie has made major strides, walking,  and now even her fur looks beautiful now.  She had some skin issues now healed and she has become quite the little lady with confidence she never showed and a tail wag now and then and part of the gang.  With the right person Dottie should blossom, loved to the very end no matter the time she has. What a joy it will be to know her.

animal.description: Sweet girl, Lil Mama is fitting right in at the rescue and has been adopted and returned twice due to seizures. She stays to herself and remains a shy dog who would rather not be the center of attention. This tiny gal of only 5years old came to us as an owner surrender turned into an LA dog pound. Why? We are guessing it is because she had some mammary masses and wasnt spayed and needed her teeth cleaned so basically it might have been because her owner could not afford what care was needed or saw seizures etc. A quiet home would be best. A loving home is a must. She is a good dog who listens well and has a long life ahead. And her photos do not do her justice. She is under 6 pounds so a home without children would be best as she is shy.  She also should only be with dogs who are non aggressive because she can sometimes guard food.

animal.description: Meet Lilly, an adorable 22 lb 2-year-old whippet mix in need of a committed adopter willing to come to DAWS several times to get to know her before she goes home. Lilly is often reactive to new people and animals and will bark on first meeting. When meeting Lilly, it is best to be quiet and just walk with her.  Eventually she will get curious and sniff you.  She does well on hikes and loves toys. She will entertain herself with her toys. She has no signs of resource guarding. She likes to play in the yard with other dogs and we think she would do well as a second dog with a nice, confident dog. Lilly is very smart and in tune with her person. We think she could be a terrific student at agility training. Lilly needs an experienced dog owner who will give consistency to her routine so she can enjoy home life. We recommend an adult-only home for Lilly and no apartment/condo living and no cats. If you are willing to get to know this girl who is so deserving of a second chance in life, please email dogs@daws.org to discuss further. Some dogs need a little more work to settle into their forever home and Lilly is one of those dogs. She will be a great companion to someone willing to put the time in to win her heart.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.OUR REQUIREMENTS FOR PUPPY ADOPTION:
1) PUPPIES WILL ONLY BE PLACED IN HOMES WITH YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL, DOGS. This helps integrate the dog into your household easier by giving the pup a mentor.
2) In addition to the youthful playful dog, someone MUST also be home at least part of the day. Please do not apply for a puppy if you are gone 8-10 hours a day. It is not a good situation for you or the puppy.
3) You must have plans in place to socialize your puppy properly.
4) Our puppies are not livestock dogs. They must be family pets that are allowed inside the home.

Please watch this short video which demonstrates how puppies learn polite behavior from their adult dog mentors. https://youtu.be/R6N8STRl2aI

Meet Indiana! He's a bouncy flouncy goofball! Born around April 2020, he is innately a very happy, playful boy. He weighs around 55 pounds, and his coat is becoming longer and thicker.

Indy, or Happy as we also call him, recently had a DNA test that gave a lot of insight into his active silly personality. He is 12% Great Pyrenees, with 38% Staffordshire Terrier, 13% Australian Cattle Dog, and 18% Chow. The test was able to detect a total of 11 breeds in this little guy!

Another test he had, and passed with flying colors in his foster home, is the "good dog" test!

Indiana is a sweet natured, extremely loving, loyal pup. He loves attention and cuddles. His favorite place to spend the night is up in bed snuggled with his people.

This pup has never met a stranger! He can be a little overwhelming in his excitement to meet new people, but he settles quickly into being a solid lovebug.

Indy gets along wonderfully with all the other dogs he's met during his foster stay. He must have a big, playful dog buddy in his forever home. He had a young Weimaraner visit for a week and befriended him instantly. They played non-stop! He is much more active than his 12% Pyr heritage!

He loves playing in water! He enjoys playing in the pool as well as out in the rain.

He does well on walks, is crate trained, housebroken, gentle receiving treats, and knows basic commands.

Indiana would love to live in an active home where children play with him and the family keeps him engaged in their lives.

SPIN Pyrs are all in foster homes in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. Potential adopters are asked to make travel arrangements if they live elsewhere. All SPIN dogs are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and on heartworm prevention. Please go to our website www.SpinRescue.org and fill out an application for this great Great Pyrenees!

animal.description:
RayRay being fostered in Chicago.

Update August 2020: RayRay is doing fantastic! His neuter and dental went very well (though he did end up losing 13 teeth). He is the happiest, and most easy going dog in my house right now. He has so much love to give and is really taking to being an indoor dog now. He loves to be near his people and is starting to get the hang of snuggling, which he has started asking for pets and affection in the cutest ways! He was heartworm positive, but has begun his treatment and is so far tolerating everything extremely well. He has a couple more months to go in his protocol but let me tell you he is worth the wait! 

What RayRay's foster mom has to say about him:RayRay is such an amazing guy! He was previously an outdoor-only dog who spent all his time chained up. He is initially a little shy but with a few treats and time to get his bearings he quickly warms up! He loves to play with squeaky toys and loves rolling around the grass and exploring outside. He especially loves to be near his people, and is now hooked on pets and ear massages, but he is also completely content to just be at your feet while working. His heart is so big, and he's hoping there might be a little room in yours for him too!

He is not officially potty trained, but so far we have had almost no accidents. He loves having a schedule and is very good at going to the bathroom outside when let out.

He is not very comfortable walking on a leash, which we are working on, but he will likely do best in a home with access to a yard.

He is overall healthy, though he did have some dental disease. RayRay will be getting neutered and a dental cleaning on 8/11/20!

He currently lives with 2 other dogs and 2 cats and is very easy going.
BDRA has voted against the use of electrical fencing effective immediately.

animal.description:
We are looking for a medical foster for this precious girl!
Lilly needs to have surgery to repair her ACL. Recovery is estimated at eight-weeks (possibly longer). Lilly is very sweet and affectionate.
All of Lilly’s medical expenses will be paid for by BAHS. This includes pre/post-surgical care and medications. We will also help with getting Lilly to and from appointments if necessary. Lilly’s activities will be restricted, so a low-key environment where she is not alone during the day is ideal. She is okay with kids but is selective about other dogs and may do well with a canine sibling. We will have dates for surgery once we find a foster. 
If you are interested in becoming Lilly’s medical foster, please email bahshelter@yahoo.com. If there are other dogs in your home, we require a meet and greet, which you can schedule via email at bahshelter@yahoo.com.

Lilly is as sweet as she is pretty! Her favorite past times are running, exploring, and cuddling. She is learning how to walk properly on a leash and will sit pretty for a treat. Lilly is selective about other dogs and may do well with a canine sibling but should be in a cat-free house. This gorgeous girl is a terrier mix and weighs 50 pounds. Her birthday is June 2, 2019.
Lilly is spayed, microchipped, and current on all vaccinations, and she takes preventative flea/tick/heartworm medicine.
As with all our dogs, Lilly must be an indoor dog.
If you are interested in adopting Lilly, please email bahshelter@yahoo.com. If there are other dogs in your home, we require a meet and greet, which you can schedule via email at bahshelter@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Meet Dasha!

Hi, Dasha here. I’m 10 years old and 48 pounds. I was so graciously saved by Albert’s Dog Lounge and I’m getting a second chance at life. My life didn’t start off too great as I appear to have been abused. I am on the mend and getting better each day, however, I do have some medical needs. I do walk with a little limp, sometimes I walk on my tippy toes, and sometimes I hop like a bunny. But that doesn’t slow me down. My foster mom calls me bun bun. The skin on my hind leg has been slow to mend. We’ve had some great progress, and some setbacks along the way. We are currently trying different techniques to help mend my injuries from my prior life. I may require some vet check ups, to continue to help my injuries heal, as well as keep my allergies at bay. I'm okay with other dogs, but do best with calm, older dogs who aren't so 'in your face', and respectful of space. I could also live with no other dogs and be happy with it. I am a sweet girl who loves to cuddle, and I absolutely adore attention. I am potty trained and very food motivated. I'm not a fan of crates, but I haven't been destructive or shown any signs of having anxiety when my foster mom leaves the house. 

I love going on walks, and roaming around in the backyard, but I don’t like being left alone outside too long... maybe just 10 minutes for a quick potty break, but I would love to be outside with you for longer if we are just hanging out in the yard. I am a happy girl and I love being around my people. I deserve a loving family who knows how to treat me right and make me a part of their family. I have been around men and women and have done great. I have not been around any children. Oh, and whenever I see a cat on our walks, I have the urge to chase it. What dog doesn’t, right? I have medium energy, but I can just be a couch potato, too. I love taking car rides, and I love hanging out in the car. I will snuggle with you all day if you’ll let me. Will you be a part of my forever?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Hi everyone, I’m Roxy…I’m all white pit mix with cute little black dots on my belly….I weigh about 55 lbs I’m in excellent shape, I’m very energetic and in great health!
I’m very, very soft and are you aware polka dots are making a comeback?!  I’m 8 years young, and all of that time except since mid-January of 2020 I had a family.  I lived with a cat and two small human siblings.  My world changed drastically on that day in January, and to tell you the truth I can’t really  remember what happened….all I know is that the next day I no longer had a home, I was left in a loud very confusing place.  Up until that day I thought they loved me, I learned all the tricks and always performed perfectly on cue, I can sit, sit pretty which means sitting only on my hind legs and reaching for you with my front arms, I know dance,  down, no, come, stay, belly ….everyone says I am a smart girl!!   I still know my housetraining and I keep an exceptionally clean kennel here.  I love to play ball I’m a first class fetch player!!  The nice lady who came to interview me thought I could do well with agility…always good to keep both your mind and body in shape you know!!  I take treats super gently and I promise to show you my love every day in so many little ways…gosh how I love my humans!

I do like to be the only girl in the house, but I used to get along fine with male dogs and small dogs and I lived with a furry feline.  The shelter thinks a home without felines might be best, since I am very curious about them.  Sometimes it’s difficult to be myself here, there are so many animals it’s loud, I’m just  not used to it all….I had my family since I was just a wee pup it’s all I knew and I try to put on a happy face and make the most of my time here, but truth be told I long to have a family to call my own again.   I hope and pray, paws crossed that someone will read this and give me a second chance at a loving home….please come for me soon…please!   Roxy
animal.name: Roxy

animal.description:
Shuka (formerly Fairuza) is a very active and playful girl. She was found as a stray so needs basic obedience and socialization to teach her boundaries and how to play nice with others. Shuka would do best as an only dog in the home. Her high energy level dictates she live in a household with no children under 15 years old. She is fascinated by cats to the point of chasing and should live in a home free of small furry critters. Sounds can be very upsetting so she needs a quiet home with room to run and play. Shuka needs a strong leader who has the patience, calmness and love to help her gain self-control and focus on learning good behaviors. She is very smart and a problem solver, so she needs an adopter at least as smart as she is.


Thank you for considering adoption of a Milo Foundation Sanctuary dog. Our Sanctuary is where our rescued dogs who have had difficulty in a home in the past, have behavioral issues, or too much energy, or for some, aggression issues with other dogs, or intense stranger danger that make them more difficult to safely and happily live in urban environments. These are not beginner dogs or for the most part nor are they for families with children. IF you are looking for an easy dog to add to your family, we suggest looking at the dogs at our Adoption Center, Milo Pt Richmond. BUT, if you can offer a safe and nurturing home to a dog with some behavioral "quirks" please do send an application today. Thank you.

animal.description:
Java is a BIG boy 80 pounds. Java is 3 years old and a very sweet boy. He came to us when the college kids he lived with moved back to their home state. Java is well behaved in a home. He is housetrained, not destructive at all and is all about snoozing in the sun. He loves to go for early morning walks and rides great in the car.
Like all our dogs Java is neutered,fully vaccinated and had blood work checked. He had entropion surgery, that is a surgery to correct a Sharpei problem where the eye lid is folded inward and causes irritation on the eye. It is well heeled now and Java's eyes are perfect. Java would do best as an only dog or with a mellow little dog. 
Java's adoption fee is $350. If you are interested in meeting him, please fill out an application on our homepage. www.luckydogrescue.org

animal.description:
Date of birth:  6/27/2019

1/7/2021:  Jack is an adorable B&W American Staffordshire Terrier mix!  He’s a year old and currently weighs 48 lbs, but he’s thin and needs to put on some weight.

• Jack is very affectionate!  He can be timid at first when meeting new people.  It may take him a little while to settle into his new home and feel comfortable, so he’ll need his person or family to be patient with him.   He’s very food motivated, so treats will definitely help him trust more quickly!

• He’d do best with a pet parent who has dog experience.  We think he’d be fine with older kids who are 10 years or older, with dog savvy parents.

• We’d like to place Jack in a home with a fenced yard.  He is playful and energetic.

• Jack is a bit dog choosy, but has made doggie friends here and plays nicely with his friends.  If you have a dog we’d ask you to bring your dog to meet Jack to see if they could be buddies. 

• He does need a home without cats.

• Jack’s a fast learner and knows Sit and Shake. He loves rope toys and doesn’t shred them to bits.  

• He was house trained in his former home, but may have accidents while adjusting to a new home. We were told that he needs to go outside to poop immediately after eating. 

• He’s been neutered, vaccinated, microchipped and tested for heartworms.  Jack had parvo virus when we took him in.  He’s fully recovered and healthy now, and ready for a new home! 

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Dog Adoption Contact Info:
Email: christine@hsgkc.org
Phone: 913.521.2339
http://hsgkc.org

animal.description:
Howdy! My name is Providence but my friends call me "Provi"

I'm a beautiful senior Labrador and everyone constantly tells me what a sweet good girl I am. I got a bad deal when my people left me for dead in a cold cruel place. No explanation but I suspect it's because I had this bump on my leg.

Fortunately some awesome volunteers found me and got me the surgery I needed. I feel sooo much better now. I spend my days hanging in the sunshine, getting belly rubs, and playing with my foster siblings.

All I want is a loving place to live out my life. Someone who will come home to me, take me to walks, brings me cookies, and tell me I'm a good girl.

if that's you come see me!

animal.description:
MEET DENVER!!

Look at my beautiful eyes!!

Denver is a sweet, excitable pup who is excellent with other dogs and absolutely loves the people who loves him. Denver loves to play. In fact, it seems that he would never stop playing if that was an option. Tough toys are a must--those soft, squishy toys don't have a chance with this boy.

Denver is smart and super motivated by treats. He will sit, shake, lay down and wait for you if you have the goods. Ok, so he is still working on "drop it," but hey, he's still young. He loves to get outdoors, so he makes sure to behave on a leash. Feel like going further than the neighborhood? Great! Denver loves car rides too. When this pup is all tuckered out, he likes to be up on furniture because he wants to cuddle up with his people all the time.

Denver is still young, so he needs an active family. He is a pup that will not do well with a doggy door, as he will have a desire to climb the fence to go find you. So he'll need to be in a home without that option.

Denver would do best with another dog to play with, so he doesn't have a lot of idle time. If you have the time to give this pup your home and your heart, meet Denver today!

NOTE: Unfortunately, he is very wary with strangers, so he will need a calmer home, with just his owners in residence, and no strangers coming and going into the home.

If you are interested in meeting this dog, please visit our website for our online application www.underdogaz.com

animal.description:
MARLIN is a spunky, 6-year-old, 60-pound Black Labrador Retriever mix.

He's an outgoing and confident fellow who would make an outstanding friend and companion!

WHAT'S NEXT?

If you would like to meet, foster or adopt this pet, please fill out our online FOSTER/ADOPTION APPLICATION which can be found in the main menu of our website or at the bottom of this page - simply copy and paste the link into your browser. EASY PEASY!

Once we've reviewed your application, arrangements can be made for you guys to meet! It'll be kind of like a blind date!

***

This pet is spayed or neutered in accordance with our strict policy wherein all animals are altered prior to adoption. This pet is dewormed, current on vaccines, and started on monthly flea/tick and preventatives.

Animal Alliance's policy is that we will adopt dogs younger than 1 year old to families with children under 9 years old. We do not adopt dogs 1 year or older to families with children under 9 years old due to the unknown history of adult dogs. 

BY APPOINTMENT ONLY:  Meetings at our Adoption Center are by appointment only (no walk-ins).  An online adoption application is required and must be approved prior to meeting any animals.  Adoption appointments are set up by email by our Adoption Coordinator (no phone calls, please).  This process ensures our dedicated time to the animals in our care, as well as full attention to adopters at scheduled times.  

Prior to submitting an application, please see the Animal Alliance Adoption Process for adoption details.

To fill out an adoption application, go to:
https://www.animalalliancenj.org/fosteradoption-application/

He is super playful and loves long walks around the neighborhood, super social with everyone he meets! He doesn't like to be pet or held too much, but once he gets comfortable with you he loves to hang out and will give the most adorable little kisses and nibbles. 
He needs an experienced and patient adopter who can work with him on learning to trust people and help him with some bad habits like resource guarding and some barking. He has anxiety and may need to be on medication, we are still working through that. He is also scared of loud noises and will bark when he hears unexplained and very loud noises, like vaccuums, blenders, and people walking in and out of an apartment. He would do best in a larger apartment or a house where he is not able to hear every noise! He is 4 years old and 11 pounds.

Do you have room in your heart and home for little Macho? Apply today!

animal.description:
Friends to the Forlorn
Adopt-a-BullBreed: Pit Bull Terrier Gender: Male Estimated Date of Birth: April 26, 2019 Size: 45 lbs Location: Marietta, GA
RESCUING AUGIE
A good friend of ours was alerted to a bad situation in Rockmart regarding 3 puppies living outside with their mother on a chain. The neighbors were caring for the pups, but the condition of the pups was declining and being outside in the blazing Georgia heat at such a young age was not helping. Augie wasn't using his back legs and his back foot was very badly injured.
ABOUT AUGIE
Augie presented as a 'swimmer' pup at first, but as the weeks passed, our vet determined he had neurological issues in his hind legs and severe hip dysplasia. Additionally, at 7 weeks of age, prior to being rescued, he had a severe injury to his right, hind paw. It took several weeks to heal and caused a deformity in that paw. On September 26, 2019, Augie had an FHO surgery to correct the hip dysplasia on his left, hind leg. His front legs have always been very strong and he hasn't had any trouble getting around.
Since September 2019, Augie received regular electro-acupuncture, hind leg strength training, and physical therapy. In the house, he walks on his own and he can go up and down stairs. During walks in the neighborhood or parks, Augie uses his 'mini wheels' (walker). It is so funny to watch him; he spins, runs, and has fun just like every other dog - he LOVES his wheels! Compact-sized, Augie in his little walker is a cuteness overload and he makes people smile.
Even though Augie had to go through all the pain and physical limitations, he is just the happiest guy you could imagine. He has a zest for life and he wakes up smiling. He doesn't think that anything is wrong with his legs and he knows how to have fun.
Augie loves to play with dogs and he also loves to snuggle on the couch. He feels comfortable in his crate and he is extremely food driven. Augie is also housetrained and holds his business just like every other healthy dog. If you want a dog that inspires you to make the best out of life, Augie is your guy!
Augie would likely do best in a home with another playful dog. It is also preferred that the home has very few stairs so that he is not restricted once he gets older, otherwise his human would have to be committed to assisting his back end during the stair climb. When adopted, Augie's 'mini wheels' will go with him.
See Augie in action!: https://youtu.be/-jEMqEZP_9I
Photo Album of Augie: https://www.facebook.com/pg/FriendsToTheForlornPitbullRescue/photos/?tab=album&album_id=2631879653536851&__tn__=-UC-y.g
Our adoption fee is $300. All dogs are current on vaccinations, spayed or neutered, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and are fed top of the line grain-free food.www.savingpitbulls.org

animal.description:
Ben is a 5 year old, 60 lb terrier mix. He's a total velcro dog. He absolutely loves his person and will stay close by. He is a very smart and playful boy. He is currently living with a female dog (Holly, also available for adoption) who is his BFF. Ben can be jumpy when he gets excited so he would do best in a home with older kids. Ben is a bit cautious with new people but warms up. No cats for Ben.

Please email us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com to find out if Ben is the right one for you! (Local adoptions preferred - Philadelphia and tri-state area [South Jersey and northern Delaware] only.)

PLEASE READ BEFORE CONTACTING US!
We are NOT a shelter: All of our dogs live in private homes with foster families. Come and meet the Almost Home dogs and their fosters at our Meet & Greet events, where you can learn more about our wonderful dogs from the people who live with them, find out which dogs are on their way and when they'll arrive, and fill out an application to adopt or foster.

We cannot adopt to homes where electric-shock fencing systems or training collars are used. For more information on the dangers of electric-shock collars, please visit banshockcollars.ca/studies.php and http://www.hollysden.com/say_no_to_shock.htm (scroll down and click on the "Invisible Fencing Systems" link).

We do not have an online adoption application; to request an application, e-mail us at AlmostHome4Dogs@yahoo.com. To speed e-mail processing time, be sure to note the name of the dog you are inquiring about in the Subject line. For Meet & Greet times and locations, visit our home page, where you also will find information on our adoption process and fees.

FOSTER FAMILIES ARE LIFESAVERS!! Can you open your heart and home for a few weeks to homeless shelter dog? Remember, by fostering a dog, you save TWO lives - that of your foster dog, and that of the dog who takes his place in the shelter! Come to a Meet & Greet and find out if fostering is for you - there's no reward quite like the feeling that you've saved a life ... or two!

Personality:  Meet Lizzy! She's a super sweet, fun-loving, snuggly girl! Lizzy's perfect day is chewing on a Kong, going for a walk and snuggling up after a long day.  Lizzy is one smart girl and passed her basic training class with a gold star!  As outgoing as this fun girl is, she can be a bit shy meeting new people and likes to get to know people at her own pace.  She's already house-trained and crate-trained and ready to meet the family she will lavish with all the love and joy she has to give.

Forever home:  Due to her energy level and boundless big puppy excitement, Lizzy would do best in an adult household or with older, active children.  She would do best in a home without other animals. She loves chewing on bully sticks and Kongs – peanut butter is her favorite!  Lizzy would do best with a patient and involved family who will continue her training and socialization.  She'd love a fenced yard to zoom around in and get her sniffs on. Our adoption process includes an application and in-home meet-n-greet with the dog.

animal.description:
Who could resist this happy face?!  This special lady is Star.  She arrived in Wisconsin a couple weeks ago after a long trip from our friends at Pet Tribe in Texas. She is 7 years old, 63 pounds and her breed is a best guess. This poor girl was chained up in a back yard with the chain also wrapped around her paw. She started chewing her paw to get loose and a concerned neighbor convinced the owner to surrender her to a rescue.  Thankfully they did!

Although she had a rough start, Star is still a loving dog and will make an amazing companion. She is said to love every human she meets! Star is super playful, loyal, smart, a good listener, and enjoys a good snuggle session.  She is selective about dogs so may require multiple meets with a dog companion and would need to be closely monitored in the home.  Star is a happy-go-lucky gal with lots of great personality quirks and is very playful but can get possessive over special treats/toys and has some food aggression issues but her foster mom has been working very hard to help her with this!  Because of this, we would recommend her go to a home with older children that would be able to understand those boundaries. She does not like her crate but has been doing well in the tall kennel run at her foster home.

It is not hard to fall in love with Star once you meet her, so we hope her perfect family is out there for her.  She has come such a long way and can’t wait to have a home of her own ???

If you are interested in adopting Star, please fill out an application at http://misfitmuttsdogrescue.com/adoption/

If you are already an approved applicant and would like to meet Star or have any questions, please email our adoptions team at misfitmuttsdogrescue@gmail.com.

animal.description: HOLD ON TO YOUR HATS!!!!!!  Yesiree, hold on tight cause you just are not going to believe this wonderful little twelve pound, Sheltie/Chihuahua mix!! What a fantastic fella we have here!!!   Is he ever so gorgeous! He's definitely a head turner.  But wait, there's more!  He's not only a looker, he is the "perfect pet!"  He is completely housebroken and totally trustworthy to be left home alone. A bit shy at first, but give him a minute and is your BFF!  He's such a happy, fun, playful, lovable, hugable little buckaroo. He folks, he is the total package, the bee's knees, the top 'o the ritz, the real deal, yesiree, he has got it all!  He's very easy going, sweet as sugar, and more lovable than you can imagine. His birthday is March 19, 2019, he's just a youngster with lots 'n lots of gooood years ahead of him. As soon as you sit down in your chair, or on the couch, he is right there at your feet, asking "Can I come up? Huh, huh? Can I, can I? Plleeeez!!"  He's a quite a sports buff too.  Whoa Nellie, he has been SOOOOO happy college football season is just around the corner.  Unfortunately, he is now sooo disappointed because with Covid 19, there hasn't been much of a college football season. He is sooo distraught, so sad, really sooo upset!! Does not look like there will be much of a college basketball season either. Normally folks, he'll plum run over you to get to that TV when there's a college football or basketball game on.  Whew, this little buckaroo means business!  Ha ha ha!!  He would normally be right by your side, the whole time the game is on, pulling for his favorite team!  When the TV is turned off and it is time to turn in for the night, don't be a bit surprised to find him sitting there on the bed looking at you as if to say, "what took you so long??" He's ready to snuggle in right next to you !!!  You can rest assured you will NEVER in your life find a more devoted companion than this little sugar baby.   He WILL be your bestest bud forever and ever!!  He'll follow you wherever you go and will never be more than one step behind you! He also gets along well with other doggies and kitty kats! You know what is sad though??  This little peach did have a home once.  Due to unfortunate circumstances, his owner was unable to keep him any longer and that  meant he was OUT the door!  Right now he has no idea what's going on!  Poor little baby!  But he will be absolutely fine because his foster mom and dad are giving him ALL the love, hugs and kisses he can stand.  They are totally thrilled with him and they have very quickly determined he is one fabulous little chap!!  They are sooo happy to have him. We do have a couple of requirements for Max's new home. He loooves his canine cronies, he loooves to play. We have promised Max we will make sure the home he gets WILL have another dog, roughly his size and age to play with! NO EXCEPTIONS!!  We have also promised Max his new home will have a very safe, secure fenced yard so he and his new BFF will have lots of room to run around and play, play, play! NO EXCEPTIONS!! Please, please, please, DO NOT leave a message if you do not meet his requirements, which are, a fenced in yard, a playmate roughly his size and roughly his age! NO, NO, NO EXCEPTIONS! We have also promised Max that his new home will be his home for the rest of his life!!  Just so you know, we DO keep our promises.  He loves to go on walks and loves car rides!  You will NEVER find a more wonderful, handsome, sweeter pet than this fine, exceptional little gent!!  For you interested folks out there, please call 352-438-8283.  Hurry, hurry---he's ready and waiting to go home with you!!!  He won't be available for long, he's just waaaay too sensational!!  Adoption donation $350.00.

animal.description:
It’s impossible not to fall in with that face and those ridiculous ears! This is Kendra, she’s between 7-8 years old and was rescued from Miami-Dade. She’s living in a wonderful foster home but really needs a permanent home and family so she can finally start the next chapter of her life. She’s very sweet and will wiggle over to greet you! Kendra can be a bit fearful of men if approached suddenly when in her little sleeping nook but is otherwise great with the men she’s met. We aren’t sure how she is with kids so for now think a more quiet adult home may be best. Kendra has played with other dogs her size and has done well, just plays a bit exuberantly at times so needs a doggy friend who can handle her play style.

animal.description:
ALL adoptions require a completed application, vet check, home check and final contract.  The application to adopt can be found at www.camorescue.com.

Adoption Fee:  $300 plus 8.25% sales tax

(Baby MUST go to a home with another dog.  Please do not apply if you do not currently have one - thank you.)

 This little girl is in need of a quiet home with kind, loving, patient, humans and a friendly dog to help her learn to be a dog again. She is very sweet, but VERY timid - we cannot stress this enough, she is VERY timid,  She does come around pretty quickly if you have the patience to help her - be aware that this could take several weeks or even months. Please do not apply for her if you do not have the time and patience to work with her. 

She is happy in her foster home because she has doggie friends and a kind foster mom who has given her the time and space needed to learn that she is safe and has nothing to worry about. Baby, was rescued from a hoarding situation along with 14 other small dogs.  She’s only about 4 years old and deserves to spend the rest of her life in a loving home knowing she’s loved and wanted. She weighs a whopping 22 lbs. is spayed, up to date on shots, hw negative and microchipped.  Please contact us if you think you can help her become the happy little dog she deserves to be. 

Adoption fees are variable. Up to date vaccines, microchip, spay/neuter are included in the fee.

Once your application has been approved, we will put you in touch with the foster to set up a  meet and greet. We are a foster based RESCUE, not a shelter. All of our dogs are in individual foster homes. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We select the best applicant for each dog, based on the dog's needs. 
For the safety of our small breed dogs and based on our past experiences, we will not place our dogs in homes with large breed dogs.    

CAMO rescue is a 501c3 whose primary focus is rescuing small dogs from the euthanasia list from high kill TX shelters.   
EIN # is 46-5486022
We rescue 800+ animals a year.

Follow us on Facebook at www.facebook.com/camorescue

Our donation link is http://www.paypalme/camorescue 

We are strictly volunteer based, no salaries are paid and 100% of donations go towards rescuing dogs.

animal.description:
In Memory of Papa Ouderkirk

'I have always had a huge heart for all animals, but especially cats. We even adopted two cats from Joyful Rescues: Leia and Lucy. Lucy is actually one of the cats that came from a transport, and when I saw how small and weak, she was, as well how she always scarfed down every meal as if it would be her last, I felt terrible for her. I would like to name this transport "The Papa Ouderkirk Memorial Transport" in memory of my grandfather, who passed away in 2019 due to lung cancer he was a lover of cats as well'. - Christianna Reynolds

Freebie was born around August 04, 2019 and weighs about 20 pounds. It seems Freebie came from a puppy mill or backyard breeding situation. She ADORES other dogs and is happy and playful with them. Freebie wants to love us humans and will walk up to us but runs in fear when we try to touch her. Freebie has never been aggressive to human touch just extremely fearful. Freebie must have a secure fenced in yard and another playful well socialized dog in her next home. It is going to take some work and patience to show Freebie that humans are wonderful but the outcome will be well worth it for you and for Freebie . Please do some reading on working with mill dogs before applying to adopt Freebie. Update: Still no human has touched this girl, but she will come within a few feet of the human she sees the most. When she gets near I smile, wave, and say her name and she wags her tail, but will run immediately if I move toward her. I'll keep working on it. She does use the dog door freely and does come into the TV room with the other dogs and two humans in the evening, but she looks around, plays with another dog and then she is off doing more dog things. Freebie does shed.
The Adoption Fee for this dog is $450.00
Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general our fees include spay/neuter, all age appropriate vaccines, Home Again micro-chipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY.

Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES

We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption.

Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME
Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

Hey there! I'm Berto! My (3) brothers and I were found in a ditch as puppies; the kind people at ARFhouse took us in and gave us a place to live while we look for our forever homes! I've been at the sanctuary for almost 2 years now and I am very anxious for a family of my own. I am 2.5 years old, 65 lbs. and they say I am some sort of Beagle/Hound mix. I am good with other dogs and I love to run and play! I will need a fenced yard for exercise and play time and I would love a home with a four-legged companion. It might take me a little bit to adjust to my new home as I've been at the rescue for almost 2 years, but I promise once I'm used to being part of a family, I will make a wonderful family member!

animal.description:
Star is a two (2) year old, 30 pound lab mix that was picked up by the shelter. While she was seemingly in good shape with a shiny coat and good weight, her eyes were both severely damaged and she was terrified not be able to see the barking dogs around her or know that she was safe from them. The whole time she was there she stayed curled in a ball pressed against the chain link. She dared not move from that spot because she didn't know what was around her. Once we got her to the vet, she did the same thing, curling up in a corner and not moving to even eat or go to the bathroom.

We were very lucky to find a foster and get her into a quiet home. Unfortunately, as soon as she was starting to relax and trust, it was time for her to go to the vet to be spayed. An exam on her eyes proved that she was blind and her eyes were likely causing her great pain, so they were both removed. She is clearly not comfortable with her blindness and we are not sure what happened but its obvious that she has not lived her life this way. Although scared, there is no aggression towards people or other dogs and we think that another friendly dog to mentor her would be great. For now, she spends her days on her bed, which is her safe space, and only moves to eat or potty, which she dutifully does on the "pee pads" in her room.

Star has a challenging road ahead of her, but she is coming along well and with some patience and time, she has so much potential to have a full and happy life. If you would like to nurture this girl along this new road in her life, ALR will stand beside you and give you all the support needed. If you are interested in learning more and think that you can give her a home, please email us at info@atlantalabrescue.com

I am a very quirky boy as my foster mom likes to call it. It took me months for me to relax around her and the family. I get worried that someone is going to hurt me and it takes a while to let my guard down. They have a lot of patience with me and gave me my space to decompress. Now I love to lay with them and get lots of kisses and belly rubs.

Before coming into CBR I was underweight and scared of being left outside. Every time I would go on walks I would pull as hard as I could to go back inside. I still pull hard on the leash when I get scared. Foster mom is working on my leash manners but thinks that I will never be a dog that likes to be out in public. I love the backyard here. It seems like I can run forever and they keep throwing the ball for me. My fur sister keeps me very busy here and is always up for play time. I do get a little vocal when I play but I don't mean any harm and she knows it. So she gets vocal back.

I don't like going into my crate but I do sleep there at night. They say it gives me time to relax. She has to throw a cookie in there before I go to bed. Then I shoot in there as fast as I can. She always shuts the door behind me but I don't mind because I am so focused on the treat. When I am out of the crate and not playing I like to watch out for my family to make sure they are safe. I will follow them around and make sure they know if someone is near the house.

I know I am not the perfect dog from the start but if someone would take time and just stick it through. I am sure I could show them how great I really am like I have shown my foster family. Bye for now! Buddy

________

5/8/20: Hi everyone! My name is Buddy and I have been with CBR a few weeks now. Foster mom says I am settling in nicely. She has taken it really slow with me and I love that. You see before when I first came here I was really scared and didn't want to go out side at all. I would pull my hardest to get back inside. Each trip into the back yard I started to realize that nothing is going to hurt me and it is ok to play. Right now I don't do very well on walks because I am worried I would make it back to the house so I don't want to leave. At least in the back yard I know I cant get lost and will always be near the house.

I love to chase the ball now and they laugh because I almost bring it back to them. You see I figure if they make me exercise they need to do a little also and come get the ball part way. I have been playing every minute I can with my fur sister. We are about the same age so she has energy that keeps up with me. We both take these mini naps and then its game on again. My foster parents say its like a obstacle course in the house. I like to relocate the toys all over the place so no matter where I go there is a toy to play with.

My foster parents are the greatest at letting me relax and come to them when I am ready. Its been a few weeks here and each day I feel more comfortable with them. They give me lots of treats and nice words all the time. Well last night I decided that it would be nice to lay near them on the couch. I got so many rubs on my head and belly. It was great!

_____________________________________________________________________________

Come visit carolinaboxerrescue.org to learn more about me and see more pictures. Learn about our adoption process too!

animal.description:
Manny needs space and a fairly predictable environment. Dog savvy people, no kids. FOSTER REPORT: Manny is a very happy and sweet dog - not a mean bone in his body. He has a lot of energy and needs someone that can give him lots of exercise and give him structure. I have got a trainer that I am working with - happy to try and make some progress with him while he is staying with me. Someone who has experience with dogs is probably best. He is leash reactive and has some "stranger danger" with men. Cats are totally fine. He gets along really well with my dog, they cuddle and play so another dog would be great for him. He is a lovely dog, with the best smile and cutest bat ears. He will make a great companion. He needs someone that will have some patience with him and give him lots of love. 

Thank you for considering adoption of a Milo Foundation Sanctuary dog. Our Sanctuary is where our rescued dogs who have had difficulty in a home in the past, have behavioral issues, or too much energy, or for some, aggression issues with other dogs, or intense stranger danger that make them more difficult to safely and happily live in urban environments. These are not beginner dogs or for the most part nor are they for families with children. IF you are looking for an easy dog to add to your family, we suggest looking at the dogs at our Adoption Center, Milo Pt Richmond. BUT, if you can offer a safe and nurturing home to a dog with some behavioral "quirks" please do send an application today. Thank you.

animal.description:
Looks like: Chihuahua
Female, 12 years old, 8 pounds
Dim Sum's name is almost as cute as her giant ears. This little lady has an adventurous heart. She is pretty fearless and loves to explore every nook and cranny she can find but is surprisingly not big on walking. She really enjoys being held, though. She has some arthritis, which makes it challenging to go up or down stairs or furniture. She needs help better understanding the leash and is likely the culprit of why walks are not her priority. She is polite with other dogs who mind her space. She will greet them but has no interest in mingling with them, she would rather be in your lap. She enjoys meeting new people. 

Dim Sum is great in the home and being left alone, but will cry if crated. She has never lived with indoor cats but is friendly with the outdoor cats she met. She is also great meeting children. Dim Sum does have diminished hearing and vision. Her last dental had all of her teeth removed, but it does not slow her eating and a maze bowl is often used to help her eat appropriately. She has no off button when it comes to eating and she needs to be regulated by her future person. She is a mellow dog that is not interested in playing. 

Dim Sum craves people. She is a wonderful friend and wants to lie down and be near her people. She occasionally whines if left behind in the car but is otherwise great for rides. A calm home with lots of snuggle time will be ideal for her. She does protect her food and water and we hope this diminishes and can be corrected. 

Dim Sum came to us because her guardian has a family member with autism and the disruption to his normal schedule has been really challenging for him. They think Dim Sum would be safer and happier in a new home.

animal.description:
After months of waiting, Pansy is ready to start searching for her forever home!

Pansy is only around 2.5 years old and 45 pounds, aStaffordshire terrier/lab mix. She is a beautiful dawn coloring and the perfect size. 
Pansy was found in the woods with two of her babies, who she’d hidden in a rotting tree trunk. She was covered with demodex mange which made her appear years older. Her sweet, timid temperament wants NOTHING but to love you and shows more that she likely did not have a pleasant past. 

Pansy will likely suffer from skin issues the rest of her life. She requires two baths a week currently with an anti-dandruff shampoo and is working one-on-one with a homeopathic vet to find a solution to best counteract her skin ailments. 
Despite it all and the pain she was likely in, Pansy NEVER stopped wagging her tail. She loves all people she meets and any dogs. She is extremely patient, tolerant, quiet and loving. She loves to give kisses and is very low energy and laid back. She has a sweet, beautiful personality that makes anyone who meets her fall in love. 

Pansy has patiently awaited her adoption debut for months in her foster home as she recovered and got to a healthier version of herself. 
She is up to date, microchipped and scheduled to be spayed. Pansy is heartworm positive and has been undergoing a slow treatment, which will be covered by the rescue. 

Despite her health conditions she hopes someone can look past everything and see her for the amazing companion she is. She needs a little more passion and care, but she will give it all in return in kisses and appreciation. She is so very thankful to be where she is today and shows it tirelessly. 

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our dogs are healthy, spayed/neutered, vaccinated and on heartworm preventative. They live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. Many have basic obedience skills and all have been temperament tested. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, please visit our website to complete an application: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt
(please note: app cannot be done on a mobile device)

For additional information see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq
