animal.description:
Pyrenees are like potato chips, you can never have just one. This Great Pyrenees bonded pair was rescued from a small Texas animal shelter. We don't know the circumstances as to how they ended up in the shelter but by their condition they must have been trying to survive for some time. Since being rescued, this bonded pair has gained weight, confidence and has learned valuable life skills for their forever home.

Patti is an affectionate 3 year old, 75 lb. sweetheart. She enjoys meeting people, going on car rides and will happily keep you company running errands. This perfect companion will surely impress all your friends and those that meet her. Patti sits calmly for treats and melts at the prospect of belly rubs. She is okay with cats and walks well on leash She is the smaller of the two, but she is clearly the alpha dog.

Witt is a handsome, friendly 3 year old, 90 lb. gentleman. He is dog and people friendly and is eager to please those he meets. He is an intelligent dog and catches on fast especially when a treat is the reward. He's not exactly happy with cats, but with really slow introductions he may be alright with them. Like his companion Patti, he also likes car rides and will quickly oblige a belly rub or two from you.

Both dogs are house trained, have had some basic training and some socialization. They are active young dogs with Pyr traits and will require a family without children and who is familiar with this breed. Both need daily walks and a secure fenced yard for exercise. They will need continued training with confident leaders that can provide firm but loving boundaries. With consistent, proper training this bonded pair has the potential of becoming loving, well-mannered, devoted family companions. They have a strong innate instinct to protect their family and home. If you have room in your heart for two wonderful dogs and can provide a loving forever home, please submit your application today.

All dogs and puppies require VISIBLE fencing

Adoption Fee: $500 for the pair ((Adoption fee includes spay/neuter, heartworm test, rabies, distemper, parvo and health certificate for travel). Adoption applications can be found on our website at https://www.greatpyreneesrescuesociety.org. Northwest adopters pay the cost of transport to independent transport service ($225).

ADOPTION, FOSTERING, AND DONATIONS are just some of the ways you can help a rescued dog. We have worked hard to cultivate a large network of volunteers to save this majestic breed. While monetary donations are always much appreciated, you can also help by donating your time as a GPRS foster or volunteer!

No cats for this boy, but he does a wonderful job as a mouser.

Hi! I'm Avery. I'm a smart, sweet pittie girl who is almost 5 years old. I've been at Partner for Pets for almost 2 years, and I'm still waiting very patiently for my forever family. I don't know why I've been here for so long, and the staff and volunteers don't get it either. You see, I need to be an only pet. That's all I ask. I guess some people think its too much to ask, but I know the right family is out there who is going to want me for me and I'll be all they need! A little more about me, since I'm sure you're dying to know! I LOVE tennis balls. I could play fetch all. day. and never get tired! I love going on walks with my favorite volunteers. I keep a relatively clean kennel because I like to wait to do my business on walks. I could use a little bit of training, but I'm eager to please and willing to learn!

animal.description:
Came in w/ 3 pups04/28/18: Hi! My name is Miley, and I am about five (8) years old pit bull terrier mix. I have been at Partners for Pets for 6 years. I like the staff but I would love to have my own family. I am hesitant with new people, so I don't show my personality very well upon first meeting. I usually warm up faster with women; it takes a little longer with men. Children are not recommended. I really need a quiet home to feel safe. Once I get to know someone I am very affectionate, especially if someone will give me a belly rub. I am selective about which male dogs I will accept, and don't really get along with female dogs. I love to take long walks. Since I can sometimes be nervous about strangers out in public, my person must take care to avoid strangers coming up to me and trying to give me unsolicited attention. My adoption fee is $185. Would you like to meet me and see how I would fit into your family?

Hi I'm Miley.
I do not have a tragic tale of unfortunate beginnings like some of my kennel mates do. I was just stray. Well not just a stray, I was a mom dog with my three precious babies, sitting in the pound. A lady from Partners came and saved my babies and took me too. Oh how grateful I was that my babies were going to live. I was even more grateful to hear that all three were adopted into loving homes. I was so hopefully that soon it would be my turn to find a forever home where I be loved and cherished too....but here I sit. You see, I have what you'd call "stranger danger" issues. New people can be kind of scary for me. I do much better with women and warm up faster to them, but men take me a little longer. I have gotten much better over the years, but the issue is sometimes still there. I do just great with the male care givers at the shelter that I've grown to love and trust. I love to roll over for tummy rubs and play with other male dogs. There is a volunteer that comes a few times a week to walk me and it took me 5 minutes to fall in love with her. I wish there was someone out there who would take a chance on me and be willing to help me work through my fear. I'm really a fun loving girl who loves play, snuggle and give lots of kisses. I am
spayed, current on vaccinations, has her annual rabies vaccination, dewormed and micro-chipped. Her adoption fee is $185.00 IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING, GO TO OUR HOME PAGE AT www.partnersforpetsil.org and fill out an application.

Adoptions are held at the O'Fallon, IL PetSmart every Saturday of the month from 11am-3:30pm and at the Glen Carbon, IL PetSmart every Sunday 11am-3:30pm. We are also at Petco in Edwardsville Crossing every Sunday from 11:30-3:30 pm. The cats are only at Glen Carbon. Please let us know if you are interested in a pet and we can arrange to have them meet you at one of the adoption events.

animal.description:
Oh, Berlin. How do we even describe such a sweet, soulful pup? His eyes tell a myriad of stories with just one look, and all he asks is for you to listen and understand. He's a senior boy at almost 9 years old, but he's still got a spring in his step and a life worth living! Berlin loves long walks to the refrigerator for any and all snacks you want to share with him! He keeps a very clean kennel and loves to snuggle into the biggest, fluffiest blanket he can find. Berlin walks great on a leash, but can be a little strong when he's excited.

No cats for this boy please, but Berlin has done very well with submissive female dogs! Male dogs tend to not like him because he can get on a bit of a mounting spree, and he doesn't like to be corrected.

He's at the point in life where he wants to be respected and not pushed and pulled where he doesn't want to go. Because Berlin can get a little cranky when that happens, we recommend a home with no small children who may not know when he's had enough.

Berlin's adoption fee is $195, and he is neutered, microchipped and is current on all vaccines!

If you are interested in adopting please go to our website at www.partnersforpetsil.org and fill out an online application.

animal.description:
"I'm just a dog, standing in front of a family, asking them to love me." -Brewer, (if he could talk)

Brew is almost a 13 year old Boxer mix who has been with Partners for Pets since 2015. He was originally pulled from St. Clair County Animal Control in 2015, and was adopted shortly after.

When his adopter started going blind, he realized he could no longer care for Brewer, so he came back to us last summer. Brewer was so loved by his previous owner, and it shows through his sweet, tender disposition.

Four years have come and gone as a Partners for Pets dog, and Brewer has gotten silver in the muzzle, but he still has a heart of gold he is ready to give to someone who is looking for a senior pet.

In the Game of Life, Brewer is so humble that he would probably choose to retire at Countryside Acres. Though we're pretty certain he wouldn't mind Millionaire Estates either..

Brewer needs to be the only pet in a home. Just him, and his people. What more could you need?

He's ready to retire to his Countryside Acres. Do you think your home fits the bill? Apply to adopt Brewer today! We'll be more than happy to schedule a meet and greet with you and your future best friend.

His adoption fee is $195.00 He is neutered, current on vaccinations, heartworm neg, has his annual rabies vaccination, dewormed and micro-chipped. If you are interested in adopting please go to www.partnersforpetsil.org and fill out an online application. We hold adoptions at the O'Fallon IL Petsmart every Saturday and the Glen Carbon Petsmart the first Saturday of the month and every Sunday. Both days from 11:00 - 3:30.

animal.description:
Raddest Rover - Patty BSmokey is a 9 year old American Bulldog mix. When Smokey first came to Partners for Pets in 2012, he was rescued from a local animal control when his time was up. He was an owner surrender. Sadly, they loved him dearly, but were forced into public housing and couldn't take Smokey. He was adopted and loved for 8 long years until returning back to our shelter when his adopter sadly passed. We do not recommend children younger than 12 years old for Smokey. Now, he's looking for someone to love him in his golden years. He has so much life and love to give his forever family! Despite a silver muzzle, Smokey is a fun loving, playful and energetic boy. He gives THE BEST kisses and is such a joy to care for. He walks well on a leash and obeys simple commands. He loves people and other dogs. He is housebroken and would be a great fit in any family. Smokey is neutered, up to date on vaccinations, dewormed, heartworm negative and microchipped. Contact Partners to make Smokey part of your Furever Family today!

The adoption fee is $195.00. If you are interested, please fill out an online application at www.partnersforpetsil.org/applications.

Please visit our adoptable pets at PetSmart in O'Fallon, IL every Saturday of the month and at the PetSmart in Glen Carbon, IL every Sunday of the month. Our pets will be at PetSmart from 11:00 a.m. to 3:30 p.m.. If there is a dog in particular you would like to meet at PetSmart, be sure to email and inquire whether that dog will be at that particular PetSmart that day. Make your home a fur-ever home! 2/2/21 3:20 PM

animal.description:
Aster (whose real name is Pup Pup) is a sweet 5-year old female Pit Bull Terrier mix who arrived at the HSOV on August 4, 2020 after she was picked up on State Route 339 (Veto Road) by the Washington County Ohio Dog Warden. Aster was not wearing a collar, and she was not microchipped.

Aster has a shiny dark brown/brindle short smooth coat with a patch of white on her chest, a few white toes on her paws, a long tail, and a beautiful face with hopeful trusting eyes, a black button nose, and large semi-erect ears. Aster has a gentle, easygoing personality. She appeared to have an affectionate disposition when we took preliminary photos in her kennel not long after her arrival shortly before closing time. Aster was quick to come to the gate of her kennel and also quite the lady as she waited patiently for attention. 

Aster weighs 49.6 lbs.

We look forward to taking more flattering photos of Aster outdoors but hope that someone recognizes her and comes to take her home first :)

In compliance with the Ohio Revised Code, Aster will be held for three days so that her family will have an opportunity to reclaim her with proof of ownership.

NOTE:  Since Aster was not reclaimed, she went home with a foster family on August 8, 2020 who plans to adopt her after she is spayed.  

UPDATE: Aster (now called Bella Rose) was returned by her tearful foster family on January 29, 2021 because she wasn't doing well with a young child in their household.

animal.description:
Nicholas is a handsome and friendly German shepherd mix - given the reddish hue to his coat, he could have some chow chow. He acts like a shepherd. He holds his head high, prances a little when he walks and the curled tail stays curled when he is happy -  he is usually happy. When Nicholas first arrived he had very little hair on his body from severe flea allergies. His luxurious coat came in except on his tail. He rubbed his curly tail on the dog door just from using it, and because it was hairless, the hair didn't come back as well on his tail. Because he came to us later in life, he was neutered later (upon arrival.) Therefore, it is best that he be placed with a female dog friend if there are other dogs in the home. He is non reactive to cats. 

We are guessing that Nicholas could be 4 years old. He is very friendly with new people and likes to have a big fenced yard to explore and run around in. He is curious and is very people oriented. He is very smart and really wants to have a friend. He will bark at strangers but more as an alert "Hey, there is a stranger here. Do you see that they are here?" 

He is a good snuggler, sleeps with people and likes to give kisses. He is okay on a leash - and we are walking him more to give him practice.  Nicholas was a former stray. He has had a rough life in a short period of time and yet, carries no ill will from it. He has been at the sanctuary for more than a year and keeps getting overlooked. He is a great dog. We are looking for a quality person/family to match with Nicholas.  

If you are interested in Nicholas, please fill out a pre adoption application that can be found on our website www.dogwoodfarmsanctuary.com or on our information page with Petfinders. From there we can start the conversation.

animal.description:
Duke is  2 year old Great Pyrenees in search of a new home through no fault of his own.  His owners jobs require them to be gone for long periods of time and they felt Duke deserved a home where he could get more attention.  He is a fun loving boy, who likes playing with other dogs.  He is good with all humans, however he is protective of his food bowl, so adopters must be prepared for a food protective dog.  He does like to chase cats, although he has never hurt one.  He rides well in a vehicle, and enjoys car rides.  He knows some basic commands, sit, shake and down, and walks well on a leash.  He prefers sleeping on a cool floor, and does not much care for dog beds, however, he does enjoy sofas, and likes to lay on his back with all his legs in the air.   Duke would like a home with another dog. We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 6 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Duke will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Adoption fee is $350

Huckleberry, Male, 8 months, Catahoula/Pit mix, Adoption fee $250 
Huckleberry had a rough start in life and came into the rescue. He has a very loving disposition but was the dominant male with his siblings. He will do best as an only pet, unless you are an experienced dog owner. Huckleberry loves playing outside in the yard chasing tennis balls and finding sticks to chew but is always ready to come in for some couch time.His foster  Adoption requirements include a house with a fenced yard. Please check any Bully Breed Specific ordinances in your community before applying. 
THIS DOG NEEDS TO BE THE ONLY PET IN THE HOUSE AND REQUIRES A FENCED YARD. 
WANT TO MEET THIS DOG?  CLICK ON  "More About Us' and choose APPLICATION LINK. 
Current on all vaccinations, heartworm negative on monthly preventative, microchipped 

Huckleberry is in the Paws in Prison program where dogs receive obedience training. This dog is expected to graduate from Paws in Prison on 9/25. The dogs in this program are trained under the AKC Canine Good Citizen standards and are specifically selected to be family and companion dogs. They spend 24 hours a day with their trainers. For that reason, they will do best in homes where they are primarily inside dogs and spend lots of time with their families. The adoptive family will receive their training journal. This journal documents everything from entering the facility, daily training progress, and interactions with trainers.

***Questions about Carson should be sent to sirescue47165@gmail.com. Email is checked 1-2 times per week.***

This is Carson. We have no idea what his mix is but he looks like a long legged boxer mix. We are also guessing his age around 2 years old. 

We don’t know much about Carson because he was found dumped in the local state forest with a bag of dog food. He wouldn’t come to anyone but he stayed in sight and barked at people trying to help him. He was waiting for his “person” to return for him but that wasn’t going to happen. Luckily, he was easy to trap in about an hour. Once out of the trap, Carson was friendly with his rescuers. It is clear that Carson hasn’t had a good life. His neck is stained gray from a metal chain being wrapped around it and his ears have been eaten by flies. 

We are still getting to know Carson and will update this listing as we get to know him better. He deserves to be put first for a change. 

Carson was neutered 8/4 and is current on vaccines and heartworm prevention since his test was negative. He is also on flea and tick prevention. 

UPDATE 9/5: Carson has not done well with male dogs but has done ok when tested with a female dog. We have not yet tried small dogs or cats. We suspect he spent a very large portion of his life chained alone and wasn’t properly socialized. He will be a work in progress in that aspect. He mainly needs practice! A meet and greet with a female dog will be required. 

UPDATE 9/25: Carson continues to show his love for people and how happy he is to be taken care of! He is still doing ok with only bigger female dogs.

If you would like to donate toward his care our PayPal address is hswcin@blueriver.net. We are 501c3 and provide tax receipts upon request.

animal.description:
Sanctuary Update : Bozworth has been a very sweet and loving guy with the entire staff. He is a big sweet goof that loves attention. He and our big alpha girl Nikki get along extremely well and can fully be trusted to be alone with each other, although we do feed them separately to be safe. Bosworth has been trained to jump into his crate at meal time and can stay in the crate for some time after without putting up any fuss. He had some issues with house training in a foster home, but now being able to use the crate as a training tool will certainly come in handy! When walking by the other dog yards he does get worked up and attempt to fence fight with them if allowed, so it would be ideal for his person to be strong and training minded especially if you live in an area where he could encounter them on walks etc. but the ideal home for Bosworth would be in a country setting with dog savvy folks, either as an only dog or with one other female dog that he has proven to get along well with during a meet and greet here at the sanctuary. Big, loving and handsome guy! 

Bio before sanctuary transfer: Handsome, big white Shepherd. He is easy going, and a good walking partner. Though he pulls initially, he calms down. Gentle and sweet with children, loves rides in the car. A loving and loyal addition for a family or couple with time to share with their dog. Bozworth lives with a BIG GIRL Nikki and does great, though in a home he likely will be better solo, he can have some attitude towards other dogs - if he is to be mixed, he needs a strong, dog savvy person with ability to do proper introductions, and read his body language - first he needs to know he is not in charge. Bozworth has a totally charming side to him - but he is not for the new initiate or the faint of heart! A big love with people, if you have a property and want a large presence who is also a sweetheart he's a great candidate!

 *Foster Return* 11/15/15 "Bozworth loves to travel in vehicles and go on car rides. Needs more socializing with other dogs. Loves to chew on toys." If interested in this sweet guy please email an application to sanctuary@milofoundation.org

Thank you for considering adoption of a Milo Foundation Sanctuary dog. Our Sanctuary is where our rescued dogs who have had difficulty in a home in the past, have behavioral issues, or too much energy, or for some, aggression issues with other dogs, or intense stranger danger that make them more difficult to safely and happily live in urban environments. These are not beginner dogs or for the most part nor are they for families with children. IF you are looking for an easy dog to add to your family, we suggest looking at the dogs at our Adoption Center, Milo Pt Richmond. BUT, if you can offer a safe and nurturing home to a dog with some behavioral "quirks" please do send an application today. Thank you.

animal.description: Catana has been through so much in her short life. We don't know the details, but we see the effects. She shakes and paces when a new person enters her space. Our trainers and volunteers, as well as, the veterinarian staff continue to work with her and she's making progress slowly. However, we see a very different Catana when she's around another dog. She LOVES dogs! Catana's true personality comes out. She's playful and gives them kisses. It's amazing and wonderful to see her be a dog. This is why we feel it is so important for her to have a canine sibling. Catana will need a very special foster/adopter. animal.description:
Goliath is his name, but, if we're going to be honest, that applies more to the love he has to give, since he's actually a medium-sized dog. He's only 2 years-old, and he's a very handsome Border Collie / Rottweiler mix that absolutely adores his people. He loves to play and explore, and hopes to have a backyard of his very own where he can run zoomies to his heart's content. Which makes the fact that he's spent more than 6 months here at HSHC even harder, because, as our fosters have told us, he instantly relaxes and his stress melts away as soon as he gets into a home environment.

He's exquisitely housebroken, and will let you know when he needs to go outside for a potty break. He's also been professionally trained, and knows commands that he will be so proud to show you when you meet him. BUT WAIT, THERE'S MORE! Goliath's adoption comes with a FREE bonus from our friends and Annual Corporate Sponsors at Paws & Play which includes five (5) days of in-home training OR training on site at Paws & Play in addition to seven (7) days of lodging, so you'll have the chance to teach him even more great tricks and commands with the help of professionals from Paws & Play, all for FREE. 

His ideal home would have any children be at least 10 years-old so they can help him practice all his tricks and commands, and he would prefer to be the only pet in his home, as he wants to be the main squeeze for all his people.

We're asking for your help in finding this good boy the home he deserves. If you are working from home and would like a companion to join you and liven up your days and give you a reason to take a nice walk outside, why not come meet him? Or, if you know a family that has been looking for a dog that might be a good fit for Goliath, please share his profile with them.

We know that his people are out there, and that they'll be so happy to have him, they just don't know it yet. Help us help him find his family.

animal.description:
Date of birth: 7/2015

12/17/2020: Hercules is a beautiful Husky/Collie mix! He’s 5 years old and weighs 60 lbs. Hercules is a diamond in the ruff! He’s exhibited behavior that makes us believe the poor guy had been left outdoors without a lot of human companionship. But he’s made tons of progress over the past few months we’ve worked with him! He's become playful and animated now that he's settled in. He’s bright and funny.  We’re seeing a dog who will be an amazing companion with some guidance and a loving home. 

• Hercules will need a home with someone who has dog experience and is dog savvy with dogs who are under socialized. He can be fearful with strangers, especially men, so needs work in that area to become more trusting. He would not be a good match if you are looking for your first dog as an adult.

• He likes most other dogs and enjoys playing in the yard with other dogs.  If you have a dog you could bring your dog to meet Hercules to see if they could be buddies.

• He needs a home without kids or cats.

• He doesn’t like to be restrained and he's sensitive about excessive touching. He will let you brush him once he trusts you. He's made a lot of progress in this area, however, and we expect that with some patience he'll greatly improve once he's in a home.

• He is crate trained and he kennels up well.

• He loves to smell things when he goes on walks.

• He can be a barker, so needs a house vs an apartment or condo, etc.

• Hercules will require some patience and training to make up for whatever he’d experienced during his first 5 years. But he’s a smart, sweet, playful guy with a lot of personality and he’ll blossom in the right home! He's really a lot of fun!

• He’s been neutered, vaccinated and microchipped. He tested positive for heartworms, but has finished treatment and has no restrictions.

MORE ON ADOPTING OUR DOGS... 

> COVID-19 UPDATE:  PLEASE SUBMIT AN ONLINE ADOPTION APPLICATION AND A MEMBER OF OUR ADOPTIONS TEAM WILL REACH OUT TO YOU.  Please visit our web site at HSGKC.ORG for an adoption application, our current COVID-19 adoption protocol, and other adoption info.  

> If you decide you'd like to adopt one of the pets you meet, we reserve the pet for you but we generally don't send the pet home with you that day. We’ll instead schedule a pick up date and time that’s convenient for you.   

> Our goal is to send you home with a healthy pet and any information and support you may need to help your new pet adjust to his or her new home.  All of our dogs & puppies have been spayed or neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, treated for fleas & ticks, tested for heartworms (7 mo. and over), and are on monthly heartworm preventative. Puppies who are too young to receive all the necessary puppy boosters and/or first rabies shot may be brought back to us for those vaccines at no extra charge. You will also receive a leash, collar, coupons for pet supplies and services, toys, and educational materials. And we'll give your dog a bath before he or she goes home! 

> Please note that we prefer and may require a fenced yard for many of our dogs.  Exceptions are made on an individual basis depending on the dog's needs, the person's dog experience, the dog's and person's activity levels, home environment and other factors. 

Thank you for searching for a shelter pet!

Phone: 913.521.2339

animal.description:
PATCH IS AT THE ADOPTION CENTER OF FAMILY DOG RESCUE. Email adopt@ilovefamilydog.org to inquire!

Mostly, Patch is just a handsome, chill, big sweetheart who wants attention, to play fetch or to sleep near his people. He is clearly well trained and responds very well to hand signals (come, sit, down, stay, no, and even shake). He was crate-trained, so settled happily into the crate as his space. He figured out the dog door in a day or 2 and he's been a perfect house guest. He is at my side everywhere I go and at my feet when I'm sitting. He does get on the couch when he thinks no one is looking, and will sleep by the front door when we're gone, so careful opening the door (deaf dogs are deep sleepers!) He's had a couple nights where he randomly barks in his sleep, but quiets down if we touch him. He had a bath, which he did not enjoy but was very tolerant of and he lets me brush him, but he'd rather be playing ball. He's good in the car and in the yard, totally housebroken (no issues at all) and not at all destructive, no interest in chewing even rawhides. Aside from some growling at strangers, he's been great on walks and with the kids. He and Scout had to work out some boundaries over food and contact with me, but it never escalated beyond warning growls/barks and now they actually play together, which is fun to watch. I think he's fine with another dog (once they work out territory/dominance) and my guess is he would mostly ignore a cat, but he would def chase down a squirrel if given the chance! 

 He's been good with our older (pre-teen) kids, but I'd be a little cautious with small children bc he does bark/growl when startled (he's deaf, so that happens) and that can be scary for a little one. Overall, he would be a perfect dog for anyone who can give him a little time and patience up front as he settles in. He is a lover and a cuddler and clearly wants to please. Active and interested in everything he sees, social and outgoing, an Australian Cattledog with a full tail. Patch is bright and smart, however, he is also deaf. He has learned the hand signals for many commands, and responds to certain touches. Best for a home without or at least with older children (teens) - he is not great with cats - though with a commitment to training and consistency - he could learn . . . bright, precocious, agile and eager to get on with life and learning! Patch will need a lot of outdoor activity, playing fetch and other games. Also right now he needs toys and things to chew on and carry around . . . also, he loves other dogs! Former sanctuary caretaker's bio: "Oh my, what can I say? The greatest dog I have ever slept with. He goes down like a stone at bed time, and being deaf, he does not hear a thing, and is a big time snuggler. He goes into his crate on command. He is a handsome devil to be sure, really a good looking dog. He is an obsessive ball chaser. Patch jumps up and nips... your sleeve, your pant leg. He is full of energy. He is vocal and high strung. Patch is one of my favorite dogs at the sanctuary, and lucky would be the person who becomes his friend. He is not easy, and he is not for everyone, but he is a fine dog. Patch is a commitment, not just a dog, but as with most commitments, there is work involved, and rewards. " 

Former foster home: "He currently knows a few basic hand signals such as sit, down, stay, no, come, and we're currently working on watch. For sit, we have been using the palm up signal. Start with you palm low and facing the sky, then raise your palm to the level of your chin. For Down, start with your palm face down at the level of your face and lower your hand to the level of your waist. For come, we kneel down and hold out both of our hands and wiggled our wriste back and forth quickly. Even when we call over Patch when he is being bad, we never punish him if he comes over when he is being called. For no, we hold our the pointing finger facing the sky and quickly move the wriste back and forth once in front of his face (which sometimes shocks him). Patch likes to jump so when he does we turn around and don't pay attention to him. For stay, I put my palm face down in front of his face and and hold it there for 2 seconds (I do this from a sit position). I do this when I put a treat in front of him. Then when I tap the ground right next to the treat with my pointing finger twice (quickly), that's when he knows that he can get the treat. We have also been working on watch. This is where I put Patch in a sit position, take a treat and hold it in front of his nose, then slowly bring the treat up to between my eyes so that he ends up looking at me. Patch also really likes to chase cars. His collar should always be tight on him when he gets walked. We currently use a harness because he likes to chase cars so much. When he sees cars, he sometimes starts to back up a lot, which can cause him to break out of a regular collar. He also really likes to chew so he will need a LOT of toys to play with. For feeding, we're currently giving him 1.5 cups in the morning and 1 cup a night. We found out if he eats more than a cup for dinner he will have to poop in the middle of the night. Patch also loves to get his ears rubbed and sometimes likes being held. " 

Thank you for considering adoption of a Milo Foundation Sanctuary dog. Our Sanctuary is where our rescued dogs who have had difficulty in a home in the past, have behavioral issues, or too much energy, or for some, aggression issues with other dogs, or intense stranger danger that make them more difficult to safely and happily live in urban environments. These are not beginner dogs or for the most part nor are they for families with children. IF you are looking for an easy dog to add to your family, we suggest looking at the dogs at our Adoption Center, Milo Pt Richmond. BUT, if you can offer a safe and nurturing home to a dog with some behavioural "quirks" please do send an application today. Thank you.

animal.description: Zoey joined the rescue a little over a week ago and we are getting to know her. She got all checked over at the vet clinic then moved to her Illinois foster home where she is working on getting comfortable with all of the new sights, smells and activity. She is a super sweet girl who is very loving to all humans that she meets. Due to her age and deafness. we will require that Zoey go to a family with older/dog savvy children. She has also not done well when meeting other four-legged friends, so a home with no other pets will likely be her happy place. 9/5 UPDATED FROM ZOEY'S FOSTER MOM: Zoey is the epitome of sweet. She's loving and loyal, cuddly, gentle and utterly adorable. She is not aggressive or angry whatsoever; she's assertive. We've handled her while she's eating, sleeping, playing, and relaxing, and she's nonplussed. We've touched her paws, face and 2 small growths and she doesn't flinch. We've brushed her teeth, snuck Benedryl into cheese without her spitting anything out (for a reaction to CBH oil), and she even handled a bee sting on her paw with grace. She's not obsessed with her dog food but she eats her 2 meals when she's ready; watch out if you have hard boiled eggs, chicken and CHEESE. She has playful moments, and those usually consist of her zooming around for a couple of minutes a day or grabbing a toy to have thrown and chase down. She does fine with baths and car rides. What she loves more than anything are her humans: her family. She has slept in bed with her adult humans for her entire life, so she would have it no other way in her foster home (she is stubborn and her human fosters need sleep). She does make for a great snooze buddy, though, and has manners: she is neither a bed-hog NOR a snorer. She's potty trained and will sit by the door when she needs to go out, however, she has a schedule and typically doesn't ask for extra trips outside of that. She will always poop on her walks, sometimes 2-3 full loads, so have bags on hand! She does have a little extra pull on the leash, but it seems like correcting with food (human treats, not dog treats) will get her to a slack lead. Zoey does have some quirks, and nearly all of them are most likely a result of her being deaf. She reacts with barking and running towards people approaching the house (and sometimes a large truck driving past), probably because she overcompensates for not hearing and assumes these people need a warning from her. She will trot happily into her crate and even naps with the door open at times, but only when one of her humans are in the room. She'll even lie down and sleep with the door closed sometimes, as long as someone is near. If she's left in her crate and there is nobody in her sights, she panics and escapes, sometimes getting hurt in the process. She probably needs to have her humans near so she feels safe and panics when they are not near. She needs to be crated when humans are not home because the panic drives her to be destructive and potentially hurt herself also. She would not do well in a house with kids younger than teenagers, and she'd be the best dog family member to a home without other pets, as she has a strong prey drive (squirrels, cats, pet birds, pet guinea pig) and becomes defensive around other dogs. Ideally she'd be a long-distance truck driver's ultimate companion or in a family when at least one person is always home. Future homes will need to continue to work with Zoey on feeling safe in her crate when her people are gone and redirecting her focus from what she's barking at to themselves for reassurance. What Zoey isn't great with are outweighed by the positives ten-fold.Zoey Boxer: Silly (she needs to have a toy or something in her mouth when she greets you, so she'll search for something while bent in half, or kidney beaning). Sweet (she is a cuddly, snuggly, gentle love who also LOVES giving kisses, even to the air if you hold her back--file that under silly, too). Smart. (She knows the signs for sit, stay, come, no, and good girl. She goes right into a sit when a treat is pulled out. She learned our routines in our house immediately and adapted quickly). Sassy. (she has fun with bursts of fetch and zoomies and will nudge you a bit with her face to get you to play if she's ready and you're not). Sleepy. (She loves to snooze and cuddle for naps and also sleeps through the night...yes, I'm a mom to a human, too, so this still means a lot to me). Stylish. (she has sweaters for the winter AND she has a heart-shaped spot on her nose .

animal.description:
IN FOSTER THRU FAMILY DOG RESCUE. Email adopt@ilovefamilydog.org to inquire!

What a beautiful, active and happy girl! Nakita is all smiles and absolutely loves people. She has lived with other dogs - notably our deaf Heeler mix boy Patchy, but typically she can be a handful around other dogs. Super dominant, and not good around them on leash, possibly pairing with a submissive, playful male could work in a large space. She is a loving girl looking for a breed-savvy adopter. She gets along nicely with all people and some friendly male dogs, but no females or dog parks for this pretty girl. She does NOT do well when meeting dogs through a barrier or on leash, but with proper direction this could possibly improve. Her ideal adopter would either have experience with leash reactive dogs or would be prepared to work with trainers to help her react more appropriately when seeing other dogs on leash. She believes all the food in the world is hers and while she doesn't act aggressively with people or dogs regarding food, she has no problem taking food that doesn't belong to her and will happily knock them over to make this a reality. For this reason she does need to be separated from other dogs during feeding time and should never be "free fed". Nakita's previous owners mentioned she could be quite the escape artist as she is very good at jumping fences, because of this she is in need of a home that has very good fencing and owners with the ability to get her the mental stimulation, and physical activity a smart energetic girl like her needs. However, she has not tried or been able to escape from our six foot fences here at the Sanctuary. It is very easy to fall in love with her beautiful face and completely charming personality, but before applying please do stop to think if you would be able to give her the exercise and training that she would need in order to reach her full potential. She needs someone who is comfortable with taking the lead. Someone who will love her and always treat her compassionately, but will set very clear and consistent rules, which they are willing to stick to when she decides to test and challenge them. We are looking for a home for her with someone who understands that although they are fluffy and adorable, Husky's are a unique kind of dog and can be a challenge if not trained properly. If you feel that you can offer this girl the loving home that she so deserves, please send your application to sanctuary@milofoundation.org

animal.description:
Meet CAJUN!
If you can see this dog, they are AVAILABLE. We delete their posting once adopted.

Say hello to Cajun, a very excitable and fun boy! When Cajun came to us, it was clear he had no previous introduction to toys or fun. Now all Cajun wants to do is play!! He is a very fun guy looking for someone willing to teach him how to be a dog, as he has little to no guidance previously. Cajun could also benefit from someone willing to teach him basic commands and how to walk on leash. He is  shy at first and can be a bit reactive to strangers but will warm up with slow introductions, especially when play is involved. He loves water and will chase a water hose all day long! Cajun has not been tested with kids or cats but seems to do well with other playful dogs. 


ADOPTION FEE AND HEALTH INFORMATION

Upon adoption, they will have received: age appropriate vaccines (DA2PP vaccine), (Bordetella vaccine), (Rabies vaccine), up to date on flea/tick prevention, spay or neuter of pet, deworming, and microchip.


APPLY

Aren't they sweet? Wondering what's next?

You MUST fill out an application to adopt. Please copy and paste the URL to start adoption application.

https://form.jotform.com/200145864739157


Once you have submitted an application, we do our best to work efficiently to process them. We will call you with any questions we have. In the meantime, you can come by and meet the dog you're interested in.



FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS

Q: Where are you located?
A: We are located just on the Arkansas - Missouri border at 32 Bella Vista Way, Bella Vista Arkansas.


Q: I would like to set up a meet and greet!
A: Please fill out an application! This is the first step to see if the dog you chose is a great fit for your home.


Q: I have more questions!! Who do I contact?
A: Please call 479-855-6020 or email bvas@sbcglobal.net


Q: I am under 18, will you adopt to me?
A: Unfortunately, we do not adopt to anyone under the age of 18.


Q: I would like to surprise my family with a dog! Can I do this?
A: Unfortunately, no. If there is more than one decision-maker in the home, all of them should be in agreement.


Thank you for your understanding and consideration and for helping the dogs and puppies in need!

animal.description:
We recently welcomed back a former PLP momma, Nellie. She first joined us in December 2016 and gave birth two babies in our care (Clark and Ellen). The puppies found wonderful families and Nellie went to an awesome foster home to work on becoming the carefree girl she was meant to be. She was a timid girl who had known little kindness before coming to us, and it showed. With her foster family, Nellie’s confidence grew, and she blossomed into a silly, playful, fun-loving girl. She went on lots of adventures, learned that the world wasn’t such a scary place, and that cuddling with her human friends and playing with her canine pals were pretty much the best things ever.

The following Spring, Nellie found what we thought was her forever home, but not everything goes as planned. For unknown reasons, Nellie became terrified of her human dad. She shook out of fear when he was present and started to lose weight from the stress. Sadly, we’ll never know why Nellie became so fearful of a person she lived with for over 2 years, but we are glad she’s back with us. She deserves to live a life full of fun, not fear. She rejoined her foster family from three years ago and is back to the silly, playful girl we know. 

Nellie is ready to find her forever family and needs someone who will be patient and understanding of her timid nature. Once she’s your friend, she’s a totally different, goofy, playful, crazy girl. She does best with a confident canine pal, so another large dog in the home is a must. This girl likes to play hard! She also loves to cuddle with her family, both two and four legged. As for kitties, we’re not sure, so a feline free home would be best for her.

To meet Nellie, please visit our website, www.pittieslovepeace.com, to submit an adoption application. Nellie is spayed, microchipped and vaccinated. Her adoption fee is $250.00 and includes doggie kisses and a lifetime of LOVE. 

The Petfinder.com system requires that we choose a predominant breed or breed mix for our dogs. Visual breed identification in dogs is unreliable, so for most of the dogs we are only guessing a predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each dog as an individual and will do our best to describe each of our dogs based on personality, not by breed label.

animal.description:
ADOPTION INFORMATION.................

Forrest was rescued as a stray in one of our NWA communities. Forrest’s finder brought him to RRR when they could not find his owner and did not readily have a foster to house him.  A big shout out to For Pet’s Sake for helping with Forrest’s initial vetting!!!  Forrest is a young loving boy, who wants to please, but is still learning his manners around people and other dogs. He is approximately one year old and is a Black and Tan German Shepherd.

Forrest  has been neutered and tested for heartworms and intestinal parasites.  He is current on his vaccinations, deworming, heartworm prevention and Flea and Tick Prevention.  We are still working on getting Forrest’s weight up as he was quite thin and had parasites when he came to us.   

Forrest will need an active home where he could go walking, running or hiking with his new family.  Forrest’s new family will need to be committed to taking him through training courses.  We would like to see Forrest go to a home with a large privacy fenced yard to play and run in.  As Forrest still has a lot of ‘puppy’ in him, to keep him out of trouble while you are away, he will need to be crated or kenneled. Forrest may do fine with older dog savvy children, but he may accidentally knock over younger children. We are working with Forrest with other dogs. He may not do well with all dogs, but we are working on learning more about the personality of dogs that may work as a playmate for Forrest!

Forrest is available for foster to adopt or immediate adoption. Forrest’s adoption fee is $400 and includes a microchip.  Come meet his handsome boy today!

To request an Adoption Application, email rescue@southwesthospital.com. 

Recycled Rovers Rescue reserves the right to deny any application that is deemed unsuitable for the animal. 

Please be aware that our animal adoptions are NOT on a first come-first serve basis. Our sole purpose is to find the best possible home for the animals that fall under our care. 

Priority will be given to local applicants and previous adopters.

animal.description:
Hello, I'm Beau and I am a 3 year old Shepherd mix! I am about 93 lbs.
 
My friends at Pawmetto Lifeline would describe me as big and beautiful. I LOVE to play fetch and can do it all day - every day. I love treats and will do whatever trick in the book it takes for you to give me one. I even take treats gently - what other 93 lb dog will do that!

I was adopted out from Pawmetto Lifeline as an 8 week old puppy and was returned three years later. My adopters told Pawmetto Lifeline that when they adopted me, they had picked the perfect dog. Pawmetto Lifeline does not know what happened in those three years but since then, I am a little insecure. I need comfort and security knowing that my toys are mine, so if you're willing to buy toys that are just for me and no one else - I would greatly appreciate it. I am basically a teenager in dog years.. what teenager doesn't want to keep his things to himself? 

I would feel most comfortable in a home without children under 18 as I am not too fond of commotion in the home. It would be best to have a fenced in back yard. I would love to have an experienced dog owner who is confident and can handle a dog as smart as I am. I would like to be the star of your life and of your home - being an only child is alright with me. I would do best in the home with someone who is willing to work with me and show me that the world isn't scary, that I am safe, and that I am loved. Patience is everything - please allow me to take my time warming up to you, even if that means no belly scratches or any sort of touch until I feel comfortable. I need someone that is okay with that transition taking longer than a week - I need time to develop my bond with you but I promise my love will be worth it. 
 
My adoption fee of $200 includes my up-to-date vaccinations, microchip, deworming, and I come home spayed/neutered. I even started on my monthly flea and heartworm preventatives - what more could you ask for? 

My adoption is considered "Best Match". This means that I am looking for a specific type of home or certain qualities in my new family. I am not first come-first serve for any approved applicant. Pawmetto Lifeline's adoption advocates and my case managers would love to review your application to see if we are a BEST MATCH! I appreciate your patience as the Adoption team discusses your application with my case managers!
 
If you'd like to meet me, please fill out an application on our website, PawmettoLifeline.org, and an adoption advocate will be with you shortly. Thank you!

animal.description:
Tallie

Located in Sidney NE
American Bully mix
Good with other dogs with slow intros and doesn't really like to share her toys
Mixed read on cats so siding with no cats 
ADORES children 
Doing well with house training
Crate trained but isn't destructive thus she's not crated, she does know a couple commands also
Insanely sweet & happy 
LOVES TOYS & CHEWS and will need to work on sharing 
Has had all vaccines but will need to be spayed at the end of the month
Approx 50lbs 

This insanely happy lil hippo princess came to us as a pregnant "pit mix" and we named Tallie. She was SO excited to be rescued from a kill shelter in west Texas and knows that she's on to bigger and better things! She's been used and abused for breeding purposes, her ears were butchered via an at home crop job and it's obvious the world she knows hasn't been kind. The kindest thing her "owners" ever did for her was surrender her to the shelter. However to meet her you would never know! She LOVES all humans and dogs she's met and is literally one of the most grateful and unconditionally loving dogs EVER. Dogs are amazing and Tallie proves that with every booty shake! Tallie has now learned the ways of the indoor house dog and has 100% embraced couch life. She also LOVES toys, she's not so good on sharing, as she's never had any to share so that is going to take a little work. She adores food and her "zoomies" are an experience that cannot be properly explained. She's so insanely happy and grateful we cannot wait to meet her special FURever family because they are going to be fantastic! 

 $200.00 Adoption Fee 
(Which is considered a non refundable donation and being we are a 501c3 organization it is tax deductible. The fee itself is not negotiable, our vets don't negotiate and thus neither do we.)

Gloria is shy when first meeting somebody new. She is so sweet and can be won over with a game of fetch. She would love a home where she is the center of attention, no other pets, and no children under the age of 12. She will chase lightning bugs all night. Loves to snuggle once she lays down, does very well in her crate. She walks on a leash well, however, she does lunge after animals nearby. She loves toys and isn't possessive of them. Gloria is an active dog and needs a place to run, she will not do well being in her crate for long periods of time. When she is out of her crate she follows you around and is your shadow for most of the day. She is potty trained for the most part, only has accidents in the house every once in awhile. She seems to be very trainable, eager to please. 4-5 years young. Heartworm positive, as well as a torn ACL.

Our adoption fee is $260 for dogs over 5 months of age and includes all vaccinations, spay/neuter, micro chip implantation and registration/transfer, heartworm test and much more. Puppies up to 5 months of age are $275 and this includes all sets of puppy vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip implantation and registration and more. To adopt, go to www.fosterpetoutreach.org to complete an application.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Henry (TX) is a 60-pound male English Coonhound mix rescued in Texas, where he was attacked by his kennel mates at the shelter, sustaining a serious wound to his neck. Our veterinary partner estimates that Henry was 3 years old at the time of intake in February 2020. After treatment with our vet partner, Henry is all healed up, packed up and ready to go to his forever home. Oh wait, this poor boy doesn't yet have a forever home! Can you help us out with that? Henry is
a sweet, funny lapdog.

understandably timid but is coming out of his shell in his foster home. He is fearful of men, so he needs a kind, gentle forever mom who lives in a quiet suburb without a lot of street traffic, and who is home most of the time as Henry doesn't like to be alone. If there are children, they should be on the older side so they understand that Henry is easily spooked. Henry is housetrained, loves to cuddle and snuggle and will bond with his person. Please apply online to adopt Henry at www.rescuedogsrocknyc.org.

East TN Pit Bull Rescue is a Tennessee Non-profit corporation with 501(c)(3) status. Your donations to sponsor pets are tax deductible. animal.description:
If you are looking for an energetic buddy to keep up with your active lifestyle, Brix may be the pyrfect boy for you! In his former home, Brix was a livestock guardian dog, but he would rather hang out with his people than with livestock all day, and is looking for a change in lifestyle. Since coming into rescue, Brix has settled in nicely with his foster family. He proves to be a playful companion to his foster siblings, especially those similar in size to him. He loves being around people, and he shows his affection by leaning all his weight on you until you give in and shower him with head scratches and ear rubs :) Brix is eager to make new friends - he is always among the "welcome committee" whenever friends and neighbors come to visit. These days, Brix is busy enjoying life as a companion dog, learning house manners, and romping around with his foster siblings. Brix is looking for an active family who will take the time to train him in house manners and the necessary skills to be a companion dog, and one who can engage him in an appropriate amount of activities to allow him to channel his energy in a positive manner. With patience and love, Brix will thrive and mature into your loyal buddy who will not leave your side!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Kayne and Ryla are two of the sweetest dogs that have been through such an ordeal together. Now they need a great home where they'll get all the love and attention they deserve, and can stay together forever. Kayne, a 2 1/2 year old boxer mix, and his mom, Ryla, a 5 year old pit mix, were abandoned in a trailer by their puppy mill owner. He took Ryla's 2 week old puppies from her and left the pair with no food or water for weeks. Thankfully they were rescued, and they are so incredibly happy now. These two love everyone they meet and love each other too. They're both attention-hogs, they very affectionate, playful, well-behaved, and housebroken. They need a home with no other pets. They'll bring so much happiness to the good family that welcomes them home! File#29690/91 7/24/20 Call 609-693-1900 or email: office@ahsppz.org for an appointment to meet Kayne and Ryla.

If interested please visit our Forked River Shelter. We are open Mon. - Fri. from 12:00 P. M. - 6:00 P. M.; and Sat. & Sun. 12:00 P. M. - 5:00 P. M. for directions call 609-693-1900. There is an adoption donation required. The society cannot accept personal checks but we do accept Visa, MC, AE, Discover and cash. As part of our adoption process, we must have proof of residency. Homeowners must show proof of ownership; landlord approval is required for renters before an adoption can be approved.And as always we thank you for your kindness in opening your heart & home to a Society orphan.

animal.description: Adopting an older dog is one of the greatest acts of love and kindness you could ever express. This precious girl is Angel. In January of 2015, Angel thought she had found her forever home. A single guy and she was his only girl. Things were great and Angel was happy. Then came the girlfriend and her life forever changed. It wasn't a jealous girlfriend issue like most thought. Angel loved the new person in the house. So much that she began to prefer her attention over his. You might say it was a jealous man issue. Soon his jealousy turned to anger and that scared Angel even more. He had enough! He packed up Angel and took her back to the rescue from which he adopted her. Angels beloved new friend came along and it was a tearful goodbye. It is so hard to understand. He was the adult, the human, the supposed Pack Leader. But a jealous heart turned against Angel all because Angel chose to love another. But this is not the end of the story. In the 5 years that Angel was with her owner, never once was she taken to the vet. No check ups, no vaccines, no preventions. Once Angel was back in the care of her former rescue, she was immediately taken to the vet. Luck would have it that Angel had her own Angel watching over her. She got a great check up, all her vaccines and was heart worm negative. Now Angel waits. Is there a real forever home for this precious girl? Angel is now 8.5 years old. She weighs around 60 lb and is considered a Staffordshire mix. Angel has not been around another dog in over 5 years and doesn't know how to interact. It would be best it she found a home where she was the one and only. She deserves all the attention to make up for the years she has lost.

animal.description:
Dorayaki is a 6 year old female Japanese Chin and Maltese Mix rescued as an owner surrender.
Sadly, Dora’s owner passed away so she came into our rescue. She is still a little depressed and missing her mom but she’s slowly getting better. So far, Dora likes to lay on her bed most of the day and will come around for a few head scratches occasionally. She does like to sit in laps but not for long. She does have some food aggression issues so we feed her by herself. She is also a climber. She is very resourceful and will use whatever she can to climb up high. She can be grumpy towards other dogs at times but I think once she gets more comfortable that will change. She does fine with cats and will even let them eat out of her food bowl. Dora is a very sweet girl with a broken heart. Once she starts to feel safe we think she will make a fun, sweet and loyal companion. Dora also needs a home with no children as they startle her and she doesn’t like that.

If you think you would be interested, please complete our no obligation application and we can start the process at www.luv4k9s.org. Select Available Dogs then scroll down to application, complete and submit. 

A physical secure fence attached to the residence is a requirement to adopt a dog from our rescue. Invisible fence doesn't meet this requirement. No exceptions.

Our adoption area is primarily OHIO. We will consider KENTUCKY, AND INDIANA AND CERTAIN AREAS OF MICHIGAN, WEST VIRGINIA, AND PENNSYLVANIA. 

WE DO NOT SHIP NOR ARRANGE TRANSPORTS.

THE APPLICATION MUST BE COMPLETED AND SUBMITTED BEFORE WE CAN START THE PROCESS. 

IT CAN TAKE AT LEAST 2 WEEKS TO PROCESS AN APPLICATION SOMETIMES LONGER DEPENDING ON VOLUNTEER AVAILABILITY AND NUMBER OF APPLICATIONS RECEIVED SO PLEASE BE PATIENT. 

NOTE TO EMAILERS FROM PETFINDER: WE DO NOT RESPOND TO EMAIL INQUIRIES WITHOUT AN APPLICATION. WE REGRET WE CANNOT RESPOND TO EVERY EMAIL, BUT UNLESS YOU FILL OUT AN APPLICATION, WE DO NOT KNOW YOU EXIST. 

All known information about an individual dog is provided in its listing. We do our best to provide accurate information, but adopters must understand that each home is different, and the dog may behave differently in a new home. Dogs are creatures of their environment and you help make the dog what it will be. 
Homes considering adopting a puppy must be prepared for:
1.) Flexible schedules for potty training. Puppies can only hold it for one hour per month of age (ex. a 4 month old puppy can only go 4 hours without a potty break) 
2.) Crate training until the puppy is at least one year old, to prevent chewing on inappropriate things when you can't supervise.
3.) Socialization: The more positive and varying experiences as a puppy the better, both in and out of your home.
4.) Puppy behavior and life stages are equivalent to a human toddler. It takes at least a full year to have a calmer, well-adjusted dog. Patience is required and when your dog's behavior is a positive experience for you and those around you, your patience will be rewarded tenfold, for years to come.
Please do not consider adopting a puppy if you have not thoroughly thought through the pros and cons of having one. So many people end up returning them after 3-5 months because they didn't realize the amount of work involved in raising a puppy. Patience, appropriate toys, socialization, and obedience training are all musts. All are time consuming and can be expensive. All Dogs Require supervision with children and obedience training. Adopters that want to have good dogs must be prepared to put the time and effort into training a dog. Any dog requires work and effort, but a well-trained, well socialized dog is more than worth the effort put in to get them there. 

Our adoption fee includes spay/neuter, routine shots, rabies, worming, microchipped, heartworm testing and they are on monthly preventative. Visit our website www.luv4k9s.org for more information and to complete an application.

animal.description:
Pâté is a shy 5yo in search of a paw-some family! He was found in critical condition after being attacked by other animals, so he is easily scared by loud noises/quick movements and would do best in a quiet home with no small children. Pâté will need a patient adopter who is dedicated to helping him overcome his fears and anxieties. Rest assured, when he is given the time and space to come out of his shell and connect and build trust, he will quickly let his playful and sweet personality shine! 

Once he creates a bond with someone and feels safe, he is a total velcro dog and will even guard you while you're on the toilet. He is most energetic in the mornings and will demand alllllll of the booty rubs upon waking. Pâté is house trained, walks wonderfully on a leash, LOVES napping in small corners of the house after long walks/car rides, and absolutely cannot resist a good swim in the lake. 

Pâté also has epilepsy, which is easily managed with anti-seizure medication and blood work every six months for the rest of his life. 

While he may have scars and trauma, Pâté is fiercely loyal and would be the perfect dog for the right situation. We are confident this gentle boy will thrive with stability and lots of love. Please contact Mazie's Mission today if you think this big bear would be the perfect match for you

animal.description:
Phoenix is waiting and longing for a second chance at finding his forever home. Phoenix was adopted as a puppy and lived happily with his family for four years until, through no fault of his own, he was surrendered by his owner because they decided to move into an apartment that does not allow dogs, so Phoenix found himself back at 11th Hour once again. He would love to live in a home with a person or family for him to love again.

Phoenix is a beautiful, loyal, obedient and loving six year-old dog who bonds easily with people. He is good with all adults, housetrained and is fine when crated. He loves to go for car rides, walks in the park, play with toys or a nice game of "Fetch". He loves to receive affection and to have his tummy rubbed. He is eager to please and even knows a few commands like "paw" and "sit". Phoenix does well on pack walks and when around other dogs. He grew up as the only dog in the house but may do well with another dog or dogs after a proper introduction. If you are looking for a loyal, affectionate companion please consider completing an application for him and be sure to ask for Phoenix!

Phoenix is non-reactive to other dogs and may do will with another dog after a proper introduction, good with adults, loves the car, crate-trained, loves to go for walks in the park and for dips in the pond, obedient, loyal, affectionate, eager to please and very intelligent.

Although he does well with meeting children, he should not be homed with them as he requires consistent structure in his home. He needs a STRONG leader who is willing to provide and maintain boundaries for him in your house :)

animal.description:
PLEASE, PLEASE READ  carefully.  Most of your questions will be answered in this biography.

*Housetrained
*Doing Well on Leash
*Kid Tested 
*Will be Happiest as an Only Dog
*Good Option as a Family Dog
*Crate Trained

HERSCHEL  is a  lovable hunk! 

He’s house trained and walks great on a leash! He’s a pretty low energy dog, but enjoys an evening walk and a roll in the grass. He loves snoozing, snuggles, and kisses! 

Herschel is dog selective.  He is also sometimes protective over his resources (food/toys).  We are recommending Herschel as an only dog, and honestly, he would love to be the solo beneficiary of all the snuggles and affection.  He ADORES his humans!  Herschel is great with all people, including children! Herschel will make a great pet for anyone looking to love on this hunk!

When Herschel was rescued, we noticed that he had stiffness in his left hind leg/hip.  We wanted to make sure that there wasn't an underlying condition that was creating pain, and took him in for an evaluation.  X-rays disclosed a previous injury that was not properly addressed resulting in chronic osteoarthritis.  In order for Herschel to live a pain-free life, the recommendation was for a surgical procedure known as Femoral Head Ostectomy (FHO) to provide permanent relief.  Herschel is now in post-surgical recovering  and doing well.  His Foster Mom is providing daily physical therapy exercises to make sure the hip remains flexible and at optimum functionality.  Herschel also had laser therapy to expedite the healing.  If you adopt HERSCHEL before completion of his 12-weeks of in home physical therapy, we will show you how to perform these easy exercises which will also help in your bonding process with your new companion.

Herschel, although a young guy,  was in need of a dental cleaning (should be done regularly for all adult dogs to maintain health), and he received that service too! All in all, he  is feeling so much better now!  Just look at his happy photos.

We believe HERSCHEL to be an American Staffordshire mix. His estimated DOB is 04/08/2016, and he weighs 745.6 pounds as of 7/16/20.

For more information on our adoption process, please visit our website at www.youluckydogrescue.org and read our Adoption FAQ's and Before You Adopt documents. You can complete an online adoption application from our website. You can also email info@youluckydogrescue.org for additional details that are not included in this biography.

PRIVATE MEET & GREETS: Submitting an adoption application is required before a private meet & greet will be scheduled. We will complete a pre-screening first to make sure that the dog you are interested in is a good fit for you. That way, we don't unnecessarily waste your time or the foster's time. 

Our adoption fee is $300 and includes all age appropriate vaccines, spay or neuter and microchipping. All of our rescue dogs are heart worm tested annually beginning at 9 months of age, and they are kept on monthly heart worm and flea preventatives.

The breed and age included in this listing is based upon the opinion of a vet that has examined the dog. We cannot confirm the age of the dog unless the dog was born in the care of the rescue. 

We are located in the metro Atlanta area. We currently do not allow out of state adoptions as a home check is required as part of the adoption process.

animal.description: BDRR rescued Skywalker with his bonded friend Chewbacca from a Florida animal shelter. They would be best being adopted together. They were originally found together as stray puppies and adopted together. Skywalker does have some anxiety when alone and he is very sensitive to changes and new surroundings . He was very very skinny coming from his last home and did not eat for several days. He is finally at a pretty good weight but still needing a few more pounds. They came from a home where there were young children that tormented them. So definitely no young children. Teenagers are fine. They are very active and love to run, wrestle and play together so a big fenced yard would be ideal. They like to play in water too. They are not good with livestock and no small animals too due to prey drive. They are crate trained. They will probably do best in a home together without other dogs. For more info about me, contact my foster, judy_christiansen@yahoo.com.

animal.description:
Maverick is one of seven Great Pyrenees mix puppies that were surrendered by an owner who could not find good homes for them in her area of Missouri. 

Hi my name is Maverick and I'm going to be a big boy! I am very active and love people so I think I need a family who will enjoy exercising with me every day. I walk really well on a leash and love to explore new places. I love to play with the dogs in my foster home. We have a big ball that I like to chase and lots of toys to keep me busy. We also have a pond and I love to go swimming. I used to sleep in a crate, but I really like the couch much better so my foster mom moved the crate to the garage and I don't have to sleep in it anymore. I am working on staying down, but I really love to give hugs and I get so excited to see people I just can't help it. My foster mom tells me I'm not a human, but I think maybe I should've been. I learned to sit and I love treats. I usually come when called but I am independent and I might miss something! My foster parents say I'm special because I give the people I love a kiss just so they know I love them! I will come to you neutered, microchipped, up to date on vaccinations, and up to date on flea/tick preventatives. 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved, you must also pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Children in my home need to be at least 8 years old as I could knock little ones down with my playfulness. And I am pretty agile so I require a 6 ft fence. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, Minnesota, and Wisconsin. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a furever home, please fill out an application on my rescue's website. 

Being fostered in Ruthven, IA

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Red is an energetic goofball searching for his furever! Red loves all people even kids (older kids he can't knock over with all his goofy energy)! He used to be nervous with men, but he has been doing much better with it in his current foster home. He just needs a minute to sniff you out and with treats and belly rubs, he will warm right up and slobber you with kisses.

Red likes long walks at the park and car rides. He also enjoys having a wide assortment of bones and toys to keep himself entertained.
He also
loves to snuggle with his people and likes having his own blanket to nest within. He loves sleeping in! Honestly, who doesn't?

Red needs a family who is attentive to his diet. He is on a chicken free/grain free diet due to allergies. He has also experienced several rashes caused from environmental allergens, which are now under control by the prescription Apoquel and over the counter Zyrtec which are taken daily. Red also uses Douxo shampoo as needed only.

Red must have another dog companion in his furever home. He is absolutely thriving in his foster home where he has 2 other dogs to hang out with!

Another good thing about Red is that he attended board and train for three weeks, where he brushed up on leash etiquette and learned the commands sit, place, break, come, heel, and stay. Red is housebroken and will notify when he needs to go outside. He is crate trained during the day when no one is home. He LOVES to sleep in bed with his people at night.

Please fill out an application to make this handsome boy yours!

**We do not adopt to Canada due to breed specific legislation and border restrictions**Adoption donation includes Spay/Neuter, UTD on Vaccinations, deworming, and flea treatment.

Hi!I'm Alfie! I'm an adult beagle mix and as beagles do - I LOVE food. The three best adjectives to describe me are: loyal, protective, and loving. I will request for pets and scratches by using my snout on your hand. I enjoy playing with toys and unlike a puppy, I treat my things very nicely! Since food excites me, I might try to sneak a bite here or there :) I'm a medium boy with medium energy, happy to relax, but when the leash comes out I do a little dance. I also like looking out the window to see what's happening out there. I share my foster home with a resident beagle and we coexist pretty well together. I walk well on a leash, know the command for sit, and tolerate my crate okay (though I can be trusted to be left uncrated because I'm a full grown doggo!). I hope we can meet soon so I can show you my little happy dog dance: I wiggle my butt and pitter patter my little paws.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Personality:

None of our foster dogs are tested with cats because we have no way of testing them with cats. Siberians are notorious for their high prey drive and typically kill cats, rabbits, chickens, birds, squirrels, opossums, etc., so we we don't have much success adopting them out to homes with cats. Most of our foster dogs are with us for killing cats, chickens and goats to begin with so our assumption is they are not good with cats and other small things that move.

Siberians are typically good with children of all ages and the only reason we would not list them as not good with kids is because they may be too energetic and bouncy and knock over a toddler.

Southern Siberian Rescue is a volunteer based 501(c)3 organization based out of Raleigh, NC, so we do not have a physical facility with operating hours that you can visit to meet our dogs. All of our foster dogs are in our personal homes. You need to fill out our adoption application (http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption) and get approved to adopt and then we will set a time for you to meet our foster dogs. As a volunteer based group, we all have jobs, family, personal dogs and other commitments but we try to acknowledge and process applications as quickly as we can. That being said, we try to keep our available foster dogs as current as we can also but it is time consuming to get pics and information on new dogs so not all of our dogs are listed at all times. Please fill out our application and then we can discuss dogs that will work for you and your situation. We average 40-45 Siberians in our program so we are certain we have one that will work for you. Please know that we are not obligated to answer inquiries on dogs as we will focus on approved applicants. Again, there is ample time to discuss all of our foster dogs AFTER we have an approved application on file. We do adopt out of state as long as we can get a home check done. We ask that you, your family and existing pets make the trip to NC to meet and adopt our foster dogs.

SSR can not and will not hold dogs for anyone. If we do, that means another Siberian will die in a shelter because a shelter dogs time is very limited, as is our foster space. We do our best to process applications in the order received and first application gets first interest in our foster dog(s). We understand that there will be scheduling conflicts with home checks and meet and greets but we will try to accommodate for that if a potential adopter has interest in a particular foster dog in our program.

All Southern Siberian Rescue foster dogs are microchipped, up to date on shots, spay/neutered, on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative. For additional information on Southern Siberian Rescue and Siberian Huskies, please visit www.SouthernSiberian.com. To fill out an application, please visit

http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption
.
