Most of our foster dogs are with us for killing cats, chickens and goats to begin with so our assumption is they are not good with cats and other small things that move.

Siberians are typically good with children of all ages and the only reason we would not list them as not good with kids is because they may be too energetic and bouncy and knock over a toddler.

Southern Siberian Rescue is a volunteer based 501(c)3 organization based out of Raleigh, NC, so we do not have a physical facility with operating hours that you can visit to meet our dogs. All of our foster dogs are in our personal homes. You need to fill out our adoption application (http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption) and get approved to adopt and then we will set a time for you to meet our foster dogs. As a volunteer based group, we all have jobs, family, personal dogs and other commitments but we try to acknowledge and process applications as quickly as we can. That being said, we try to keep our available foster dogs as current as we can also but it is time consuming to get pics and information on new dogs so not all of our dogs are listed at all times. Please fill out our application and then we can discuss dogs that will work for you and your situation. We average 40-45 Siberians in our program so we are certain we have one that will work for you. Please know that we are not obligated to answer inquiries on dogs as we will focus on approved applicants. Again, there is ample time to discuss all of our foster dogs AFTER we have an approved application on file. We do adopt out of state as long as we can get a home check done. We ask that you, your family and existing pets make the trip to NC to meet and adopt our foster dogs.

SSR can not and will not hold dogs for anyone. If we do, that means another Siberian will die in a shelter because a shelter dogs time is very limited, as is our foster space. We do our best to process applications in the order received and first application gets first interest in our foster dog(s). We understand that there will be scheduling conflicts with home checks and meet and greets but we will try to accommodate for that if a potential adopter has interest in a particular foster dog in our program.

All Southern Siberian Rescue foster dogs are microchipped, up to date on shots, spay/neutered, on monthly heartworm preventative and flea and tick preventative. For additional information on Southern Siberian Rescue and Siberian Huskies, please visit www.SouthernSiberian.com. To fill out an application, please visit

http://www.southernsiberian.com/info/adoption
.

animal.description: Lexi is a 10 year old terrier mix was rescued from West Virginia. Her "family" shaved all her hair off in December, left her outside, and drove to Florida on vacation. Lexi is not being mean, we think it's the way she was treated. She takes food and runs. We don't want any little ones getting their fingers nibbled. Lexi is pretty good with other dogs but can sometimes be a jerk. A one dog household would be best. She is very playful and acts a lot younger than 10.

animal.description:
Shenzi is about 3 years old and 11 to 12 lbs. Handsome black & tan boy who is a bit shy - he is coming around with attention, good food, and friendship. He gets along great with the other small dogs in his area and plays with the puppies.
His group came from Central Cal - rescued from orchards where they were living. We have a socialization program that has really helped them to heal.
Please find our applications and valuable information under 'Adopt a dog'* on our website: *www.beaglesandbuddies.com* and email your application to beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Let us know your preference of appointment day/time and which dogs you are interested in and we will do our best to accommodate and email you the closest appointment available. Please allow us up to a week to get back to you. Most appointments will be Friday-Sunday, 10 am - 2 pm, for an hour.
*Note bring any other dog/s and the entire family to your meet and greet at B&B.* A complimentary training manual is included with each adoption, authored by terristeuben.com. Check out her website - she is fabulous!
B&B is glad to be open during the pandemic. We know the value and comfort of a loving pet companion and are doing our best to help the dogs and folks who need them. We update our website daily and are always rescuing, vetting, rehabilitating, socializing.
* We are accepting applications for volunteers to spend time with our dogs, hang out, sing/read to the shy ones, walk/toss ball with those who go to the playgrounds; cleaning, office work, gardening, and building/repair projects! *
Are you my furrever family?

For further info on the adoption process, please visit our home page and check out the "Adopt a Dog" section, which has thorough instructions. All our dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped, and

fully vaccinated before adoption; they have been wormed, bathed, socialized, walked daily and much loved; each adoptee leaves with a leash, collar, and all medical records.

Our prices are higher than the shelters' because we nurse the dogs through their illnesses and get them needed surgeries and dentals. We also spend time socializing. Furthermore, unlike shelters, rescues do not get financial aid from the government and must rely on donations, grants, and adoption fees. Our fees for adults start at $150 and go up to $750. The higher end is for our most in demand dogs, such as young beagles and other purebred dogs. The lower end is for dogs who have been here a while. For puppies, we may go beyond this and charge $1000. The good news is that, because rescues fall under the "charity" category, the fees for our dogs are officially donations and are therefore tax deductible. You can think of it as donating to a worthy cause and getting a dog in return!

Sponsor Me

Beagles & Buddies must find ways to raise money so we can continue saving dogs. Your tax-deductible donation keeps our rescue kennel operating!

Hours

Friday: 10 am to 3 pm

Saturday: 10 am to 3 pm

Sunday: 10 am to 3 pm

Monday: CLOSED

Tuesday: CLOSED

Wednesday: CLOSED

Thursday: CLOSED



Weekday appointments may be available. We are a small staff and do our best to accommodate your needs. **Note that during COVID, we are not holding open houses on any day. Please email us for an appointment and include your application (found on our website, beaglesandbuddies.com, under "Forms"). Most appointments will be Friday through Sunday, though other days may also be available. We usually schedule one appointment per hour. Allow 1-2 hours for your appointment. Please look at our website and make a list of one or more dogs that you would like to see.

Contacting Us

If you have a question about adopting, giving up a dog, boarding, or volunteering, please visit the appropriate tabs on our
home page.

For more specific questions, call 626-444-9664 (please leave a voicemail if no answer) or email at beaglesandbuddies@gmail.com. Note that
Emailing
is always preferred!

Thanks!

Please note: If you are viewing this profile anywhere other than Beagles & Buddies own website, you are not receiving full info. Visit info on pet here.

animal.description:
This girl is the best dog. Just about perfect. Is there room for this pretty girl in your life? Carolina is looking for that special someone!

She and her brother Sonny have come a LONG way. She's gone from hating attention to almost craving it and walks incredibly well on a leash (versus biting/freezing). She is very treat motivated and was easy to teach to sit and several other commands.

She does good with dogs, especially low energy dogs as she won't fetch or wrestle. And while she'll willingly jump on your lap for pets, she really isn't a cuddler or will lay down on your lap. She's independent that way and doesn't need to be crated either.

She needs to keep moving forward and deserves a home!

New to the story of Sonny & Carolina... here's a video from North Texas Giving Day:

https://vimeo.com/358414206

Carolina is a beautiful red pit mix, dainty in size. Over the last 6 months she has made huge strides in her confidence and willingness to forget her past. She has become so social and will even jump on the bed for pets. She is dog friendly and loves to be in your lap for car rides. She would make a great family pet, just needs some time to warm up and get used to her new surroundings. She is healthy, sweet, weighs about 30 pounds and is 3 years old.

Carolina was found with her brother and based on their demeanor when we found them it is assumed they had little human interaction. Over the past 6 months, they have opened up and their trust has increased. 

So Sonny, the poor pup shivering in the shelter afraid of anything that comes near him, has a sister... meet Carolina. Like her brother, she is equally as shy, so hopefully together they can build some confidence! We look forward to seeing the change in these two now that they are in a loving foster home.

All Dallas DogRRR adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon finalizing adoption. The standard minimum donation for puppies is $325 + 8.25% tax = $351.81, for dogs over 12 months the adoption fee is $225 + 8.25% tax = $243.66 and for our senior dogs 8 years and up is $100 + 8.25% tax = $108.25; this increase includes sales tax recently required by the State of Texas to collect. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. 

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process. Thank you for your interest in adopting a Dallas DogRRR.

Reese is a little girl that came to us with her sister Twix after the elderly owner she had recently passed away. In his declining years, he did the best he could to care for his dogs but due to age and health related issues, Reese and her sister did not receive the socialization that they needed to be truly well-rounded dogs. 

As such, Reese does not know what it means to actually live in a home environment and is learning things like how to walk on a leash, and how to be approached by people regularly. Reese needs a home with a confident dog who she can take her cues from and learn how to be part of a family with. She also needs a secure fence.

animal.description:
Meet Piper
Rescued and safe… Calling all senior dog lovers! Piper needs you. We rescued Piper (and her friend, Bear) from Cobb County Animal Control when their owner wasn’t able to care for them due to health reasons. Bear being younger had rescue, but Piper was in danger of being euthanized. Bear and Piper have lived together for a while, including in foster care most recently, before they came to our shelter. When their futures became uncertain we wanted to make sure they were able to stay together and find soft places to land. They arrived at our shelter on July 26, 2020.  Bear has since been adopted.
Piper is a beautiful purebred German shepherd. She’s a senior girl at 10 years old. She is blind. Piper gets around very well though and relies on voices or presence to know where her person is or doggie friend is. Piper was in danger of being euthanized. In our opinion no dog deserves to die just because she’s old and blind. That’s when they need us the most! Her personality is terrific. She’s easy-going, just a love of a dog. She’s in good health, but does need daily enzyme powder on her food to ensure that she’s able to process it, but it’s easy to manage. 
She’s very calm and gentle. She walks well on a leash and she rides well in a car. She has beautiful manners. She enjoys sunning herself in the yard and quietly taking in the sounds around her. Piper longs to live in a quiet, calm place where she can feel safe. The unknown and unexpected noises of the shelter are tough on her, but she bravely deals with her new circumstances.  She loves sleeping and she eats well. She likes her walks in the forest and will gingerly and slowly feel her way forward. Piper gets along well with Bear and it would be great if these two could be adopted together, but it’s not necessary. Piper seems to like calm male dogs versus females and cats don’t seem to be an issue. 
Piper is a remarkable girl, who’s had a tough go in life. Our greatest hope is to find this girl a place where she can live out the rest of her days in gentle kindness and quiet. If she can go with her bestie, Bear, so much the better. He helps to guide her and she knows when he is around. If you’re able to open your heart and home to Piper please get your application in. This exceptional dog deserves a chance at a loving home.

Adopters MUST come to the shelter to transport their new family member home. We do not ship nor do we transport them to their new homes. Charles Smithgall Humane Society (CSHS) is a No kill shelter. Animals in our care remain safe with us until adopted. Resident animals are primarily owner relinquished and also accepted from local Animal Control. The facility usually is operating at capacity with a list of animals waiting for space to open.
Adoptions and meet and greets are being scheduled by appointment only. Please call our office, email us or complete an application and someone will be in touch just as soon as they can.

animal.description:
In late April we ran across a post of a dog that had been kicked out of her house and out of her yard to her neighbors yard. She sat there, staring at the property that she had once called home. The post said

"Her owners ran her off their property and she is currently at their neighbor's place. They have bred her over and over for her pitiful puppies and now that she MAY have got pregnant by another stray dog they threw her OUT!!! She keeps looking over to the property where she used to live at. She's very hot, sad, confused and helpless."

We sprung into action and found a foster and immediately got her out of there. After her 1st vet visit it became clear the dire health situation which she was in. She was HW positive and had a tick disease, in addition to in fact being pregnant. We had to make a decision, did we spay, and risk that she very well may bleed out, or do we allow her to deliver and understand she could also bleed out that way. After speaking with numerous vets we made the decision to allow her to whelp her pups as the risk there seemed less than opening her up. She gave birth to 8 pups, one wasn't properly formed and one died a couple days later. Unfortunately over the first 24 hours Lark began to have life threatening issues. She was hospitalized, recieved fluids and a bevy of meds in addition to a blood transfusion. Over the next week we all held our breath praying that her red blood count would stabilize and that she would begin to eat on her own. Eventually she did and we were elated when she could eventually leave to head back to her fosters home. Unfortunately this meant that she could not only not nurse her pups, she couldn't even hear them. The foster wanted to keep the pups and momma under the same roof anyway and she was devoted to bottle feeding and socializing the pups. Lark recovered and her pups are now ready to find homes of their own, as is Lark. 
 

Lark is dog friendly, she lived with other dogs in her original home and her first foster had multiple other dogs which she had no issues with. However since the first foster the next 2 fosters she wasn't impressed with their dogs. Not sure if it was the way she was introduced or if she just has decided she would rather not deal with other dogs haha. I truly believe that she would be ok depending on the individual dog. 

Lark is on slow kill Heartworm treatment as that is the only treatment that is safe for her at this time. We will test her again in 6 months and see where she is at, then go from there. 

Lark has had a horrid start to life. She was devoted and loved people who obviously aren't fit to own a rock. Further her ears were butchered, she wasn't even slightly cared for and she has had litter after litter. Her life has changed now however and she knows it! She knows that she's now an inside family member, cherished and loved. She is feeling better and has the sweetest personality. This little lady deserves the most amazing home and we are absolutely devoted to finding it for her! 

If you think it's you, please contact us ASAP!

animal.description:
Breed:  Formosan Mountain Dog mix
Age:  1 yr.
Weight:  30 lbs.
Good with dogs:  yes, no large dogs
Good with cats:  yes
Good with kids:  10 yrs. and older
Energy level:  medium
Good with men/strangers:  fearful, prefers women
Hypoallergenic:  no

Special home requirements or medical:  needs a playful dog; yard preferred

Additional info:

Alex has really started to open up and is gaining more confidence. He now walks on leash very well and will even pass by strangers on walks, he will still try to avoid larger groups of people, but I’m hopeful this will improve as well. He is also cat friendly and has learned to not chase the resident cat any longer, instead he will sometimes just follow her around nicely. If Alex is moved into a home with cats it may take a few days to get him acclimated and his adopter will need to be prepared to work on that with him. He’s still playful with other dogs and doesn’t have a preference for any size. He loves playing catch, but is still learning the concept of “fetch”. He has not been around any children at all so we can’t be sure if he will do well with them, so it’s best that the children in the home be at least 10 years old and be able to understand that he may need some space at first.

Since Alex loves to play so much the dog in his home has to be just as playful as he is, he does not require a yard but it would be amazing if he did find a home that has a secure yard that he can run and play in.

If you are not ready to adopt just yet and would like to help in other ways, please consider clicking on the green “Sponsor Me” button above to help this dog receive the best care we can give. We rely on the generosity of others to make rescuing dogs possible.

IF YOU ARE INTERESTED IN ADOPTING THIS DOG, PLEASE MAKE SURE YOU HAVE READ THE DOG'S INFORMATION CAREFULLY.  ONCE YOU HAVE DONE SO, PLEASE DO THE FOLLOWING:
1.       Visit www.dogswithoutborders.org
2.      Then fill out an online ADOPTION APPLICATION -  http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-application/
3.       Please wait to hear from our representative in approximately 48 hours on weekdays.
4.       To learn more about our adoption process, please look up our Adoption FAQ’s. - http://dogswithoutborders.org/adopt-a-dog/adoption-faq/

animal.description:
Minnie is a 2 yr old very loving and intelligent terrier mix, house and pee pad trained. She has boundless energy and enjoys playing outside with her foster doggie siblings. When she first moved in, she lunged and barked at everyone in the house because she was afraid. After several weeks, she warmed up to her foster mother and now comes for kisses and snuggles. Be aware that she is likely to bark and lunge at strangers and would probably benefit from some behavioral training. She is looking for a patient, loving home with no children and low traffic that will provide plenty of snuggles and exercise while helping her build confidence. A fenced yard would be a bonus, as she can be temperamental on a leash. Adoption fee is $300.

All UnderDogs are spayed/neutered, heartworm checked, microchipped, up to date on vaccines and heartworm/flea/tick preventatives.  For consideration for one or more dogs, we require that an on-line application is filled out.  

TO ADOPT THIS DOG PLEASE FILL OUT AN APPLICATION AT https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/. 

Sorry, we do not adopt outside of Florida.  Applicants are subject to a home visit, and veterinary references will be checked. Please include a vet reference (including phone number) when applying online.

Our application process:
FIRST, an application must be approved for adoption from our rescue.
SECOND, we determine whether the dog that has been applied for is a "good match" for the household that wants to adopt him/her.  We take into consideration the dog's activity level, compatibility with other members of the household (human and other pets), etc.
If your application has been approved, but the dog you applied for is no longer available, please take the time and look over our adoptable dogs again.  We will make every effort to find the right dog for an approved applicant.

We hope you agree and understand that our goal to find the best forever home is our #1 priority! Please fill out an Adoption Application at https://underdogrescueofflorida.com/

animal.description:
Roscoe  is a 5 year old, 17 pound neutered male. He is very people friendly and fine with most dogs once he knows them. His new owner should be prepared for some high energy! He is currently recovering from flea dermatitis and his hair is slowly growing back. His new home should have a securely fenced yard and be willing to work with him on basic manners. 

If you wish to be considered for this animal, please download an application at http://fallstonanimalrescue.org/adopt/ or email fallstonrescue@aol.com to request one. It can take up to 2 weeks to process an application; we suggest following up by email on the status if you have not received a reply within 3-5 days. We are an all-volunteer based rescue and we ask for your patience if we are slow to respond. 

Please understand that we fit the dog with the home we feel is best suited and will accept multiple applications for one dog. We have strict requirements for families with children under 10 since many of our dogs are grumpy and may not do well with children. Some dogs will have fence requirements, while others may not. It is preferred you are within a 2 hour drive from our Rescue Center in Fallston, MD.

A pet is a lifetime commitment and it is our duty to do our very best to place them correctly the first time around. We do not take the adoption process lightly. Thank you for choosing to adopt not shop!

animal.description:
Hello My name is Jasmine. I am smart, loving and very playful. I am a lab mix about 2 years old, weigh about 45 pounds, I love kids.

My wonderful rescue helped me when i was a stray and Mrs. Joyce became my foster. Mrs. Joyce is a dog trainer so that was a big bonus for me. I have been at her house for 6 months and I have made a lot of friends there, animal and human.

Some of the things I like to do are: play with balls, stuffed animals and play under the water sprinkler. Since I am smart I learn commands quickly especially if treats are available. For instance, I can sit, come when called and do puppy push ups. I really would be a great running partner, I love to run.

When I am out in public I love meeting people and am always friendly. I can meet and greet really good. However sometimes I forget and jump up on people and my foster reminds me this is a no,no. I can be a calm girl when my foster family watches t.v. I will even sit with them nicely. My favorite thing to do is play with the dogs. Our favorite sport is to run up and down the fence when the kids come by on their bikes. I also love to go walking and say hello to other dogs and people. I do like my bed and treats. I am house trained and definitely do not chew items up. Mrs Joyce has rabbits and I am good with them too. They are cute!

I would be best as an only dog as I play rough and have waited so long for my own home that I want all the attention and lovings.

Over all I am healthy and looking forward to my own home and family. Being a dog trainer, Mrs. Joyce has taught me to have good manners and since I am smart I can remember manners really good!Interested in adopting a companion dog or cat from Texas Animal Society?
Please email info@texasanimalsociety.com and complete online adoption application at texasanimalsociety.org
Come visit our Facebook page https://www.facebook.com/www.texasanimalsociety.org/

animal.description:
Do you want an easy walking partner to help with your New Year Resolution to be more active? Goose walks nicely on a leash; our Junior volunteers love walking Goose, too. He rarely pulls and if you even jog a little he stays right beside you. Daily walks you and Goose would take together would be an easy way to stay on track!

 

On the flip side; Goose is at that perfect age where lounging around is a great activity. If lots of activity isn't the kind of dog you are looking for Goose is a great fit. Hes an easy going boy!! He knows SIT, PAW and learning DOWN. He is a pretty quick learner and happy to please his people! Goose is food motivated so learning new tricks would likely be fairly easy.

He'd be happy to travel in the car with you as well. He has riden with many of our volunteers and is a great co-pilot. He won't "bark" directions or corrections while you drive :)!

Even though he will play a bit of tug-o-war or fetch a ball with you; he'd be just as happy relaxing next to you; high energy he is NOT! He is a 5-yr old GENTLEman; 60lb male Boxer mix. He loves everyone he meets and is a quick to give you a little kiss! He has been good with older children and very polite with excellent manners. Goose does need to be the only dog.

As part of Goose's $250 adoption fee, he is neutered, microchipped, up to date on vaccines, and current on his monthly flea/tick and heartworm preventatives. If you have questions about this sweet boy, email Dogteam@pawsforlifenc.org. If you wish to adopt Goose, you can fill in an online application for him under the Adopt a Pet Tab on our website: www.pawsforlifenc.org

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Please review our Adoption Process before filling out an application. If you would like to try a Foster to Adopt trial, please fill out an Adoption Application.

If you are only interested in temporarily Fostering one of our rescues, please fill out a Foster Application.

Lola is an adorable small GSD mix who was rescued in September 2019 from the streets of Tijuana, while tied to a post. Lola was fearful when she first arrived in a dog kennel for transport and was very scared. She didn't hesitate to try to bite, so we did what we always do when we have a dog who is scared and can be a fear biter. We gave her space and she came out on her own to explore, and after a few minutes slowly adjusted and trusted a couple of selected volunteers. Lola was fostered in Mexico with her original rescuer for a long time until she was able to find a foster family who took her in on a foster-to-adopt trial. They knew this girl would need dog training because of her uncertainty with some people and dogs. The couple that took her were first time dog owners in a condo setting, who would need to walk her daily. They did sign her up to dog training classes, but as time progressed Lola became protective of them and they were not the right family for her. They were not able to control her on leash walks or when people would come to their home to visit. As a result, they only fostered her for 4-6 weeks. It has been about 6 months since that foster experience and for the past 4-6 months, she has been fostered in a home with a yard, one handler/foster, and several other cats and dogs. We can say this about Lola:1) Ideally she needs an experienced dog owner, who understands how to be the leader of the pack. Lola is a pretty great, easy dog, but NOT if she senses no leadership. 2) She is a young, healthy, and up-to-date on medical. She is almost 2 years of age and about 40 pounds.3) She is crate trained, house trained, and rides well in the car. 4) DOG interaction: Lola does well with all puppies and all male dogs. She does well with female dogs, BUT if they are females like her with a potential dominant/alpha personality, there could be issues. In that case it may be a rough or slow introduction, instead of a "let's all be friends and play" type of interaction. It could be more of a 'I will ignore you, but if you start something with me, I will also continue something." In that case, there will be just a few dogs that she will not get along with, but for the most part she does very well with most dogs. If Lola is being naughty or planning on starting to be naughty, her handler/foster/owner will need to be observant during introductions so they can quickly stop things from escalating by verbally correcting her. When she is corrected and told to stop, she will immediately listen and will go do something else. This will only be for the first few hours of meeting another dog with a strong personality. After a day or two of being around that type of dog, she will ignore/forget the personality differences they had with each other. HOWEVER, when it comes to recourses like toys/treats, she can share when she is in the mood. But she will sometimes refuse to share with any dog personality/age/breed when it comes to toys/treats, so she needs to be supervised and corrected before anything gets started. 5) Lola loves cats and cats seem to love her! We mean INDOOR CATS, because she can have "prey drive" with birds, squirrels and cats in the yard. This is not severe, but she can chase them, which can turn into something else. A home with indoor/outdoor cats would NOT be well matched for this girl. Lola has many indoor feline friends from ARWOB, from kittens to senior cats. If the cats ignore her she ignores them, if the kittens try to play with her she loves it. 6) Lola is not a big barker and stays home alone very well, although it's best if she is not aware that you have left the house, so her not hearing the car coming and going would be best. On a vocalization level, we would put Lola at 3 (with 10 being the highest). She can whine when left home alone, if she sees you leaving her. But if she is in her crate in the bedroom when you leave or in the yard for a short period of time, she could care less and does just fine. She is not a barker when in the yard or inside the home, UNLESS someone she is not "feeling" approaches. Sometimes people will walk their dogs near the front yard and she could care less about them. Sometimes the UPS driver will make a delivery and she will ignore this. But other times she will BARK and protect her property like any other BIG dog (i.e. German Shepherd protection). She can be easily corrected if you are there to call her back, but this could mean she could be a liability if left unsupervised in an area where different people come and go. Some people trigger her instinct to "protect her home."7) Lola does well on leash walks for the most part, with minimal pulling and dog reactivity. But on occasion, she will sometimes get on high alert and start pulling more than usual. She is easily corrected when she starts pulling and/or barking. This is where a knowledgeable adopter comes in and as long as they take the leader role and correct her when this happens, it can be corrected quickly. Her handler will need to be aware of their surroundings when taking her on walks to make sure nothing is out of control, so she can be immediately corrected.8) Lola does not live with children now, but she did live with kids when she was in Baja, Mexico. She does see kids and has no problem with them. 9) Lola is an excellent exercise partner and a napping partner. She can do both like a pro! 10) An adopter for Lola will need to ENROLL her in dog training with a behaviorist for evaluation on DAY ONE before taking her home. They will need to make sure she does not revert to her old behavior from when she lived with her foster family in Mexico (i.e. over protective and spoiled). Behaviorists stress the importance of DAY ONE evaluation to get the family started on the right path. If an adopter has a behaviorist/trainer that they have worked with or have experience, that is great. However, we must stress that this needs to be BEHAVIOR training, not just general training commands like sit/stay/down. We are in no rush to move Lola since she is EASY PEASY for her current foster mom and does not demand anything, nor get into trouble in her foster home. Her foster mom finds she is an easy partner to have at home.11) We are ideally looking for a foster-to-adopt trial for Lola of approximately 2-4weeks, before we finalize her adoption. We are happy to lend a crate, leash, etc. to get her started, but we will not cover the fees for dog training during the foster-to-adopt trial. The only thing we could approve is a weekend stay with Lola, so her potential adopter can get to know her a bit. Then the potential adopter would be able to decide if the foster-to-adopt trial would be feasible and if paying for training services is something they are willing to do. You can email us at animalrescuers@sbcglobal.net with any additional questions about Lola. Thanks!If you think Lola would be a good match for you and you would like to foster her or possibly adopt her, please submit an application online. Don't wait!If you would like to meet one of our animals, PLEASE fill out an adoption application.

animal.description:
Miss Ramsey Ray~
If you’re looking for a fun loving babe that turns heads where ever she goes, look no further.  Ramsey, is a 3 year old boxer pitty mix and happiest on an adventure (water included is a plus) and with women. She has perfect leash manners, sensitive to commands, and aims to please. Ramsey, is still learning how to be a dog in our big scary world so patience and dedication are the key ingredients. New places, people, and noises can leave her unsure but she will look to her handler for leadership. Ramsey, likes slow intros with dogs and men, these two categories should not be forced and she needs a strong advocate to keep everyone comfortable and safe. She will be the first one to jump in the car for a road trip or bound happily next to your bike, but she does require proper cool down like all squish faces. Ramsey enjoys affection but is also fine to rest alone.
•
If you would like to schedule a chance to meet Ramsey please fill out our adoption application on our website at www.californiabullyrescue.org/adopt

Placement limited to within an hour's drive of Albany, NY.  Please take a moment to read the pet’s ENTIRE description which should answer many of your questions.

Rhett Butler, very handsome, 18 month old, 65# Redbone Coonhound.  Gets along great with other dogs; plays too rough for cats.  He has a hound bay, so not an apt/condo/duplex dog.  A very sweet boy who likes to play but enjoys snuggling too.  Rhett has a cataract in one eye that dimishes his sight.  His other eye is fine.  He is on daily eye drops for life - $15-$20 a month.  Too exuberant for children under 8.  A secure 4"+ fenced yard is preferred.  Application available at www.capp-petplacement.org. Approved applicants can meet Rhett by appointment.  Contact - 518-292-0555.

Some of our general policies:  1) Pets can be seen at pet adoption clinics or BY APPOINTMENT TO APPROVED APPLICANTS ONLY.  Application and general adoption fee schedule (exceptions noted in pet's description) at www.capp-petplacement.org .  For our weekly pet adoption clinic schedule, like us on Facebook.  2) For the safety of the dog and children, we generally DO NOT place senior dogs or dogs under 35 pounds in households where children under 8 years old either reside or visit frequently.  3) Note that, unless we have prior records on a rescued pet, ages, grown weight for puppies, etc. are estimates only.  4) If you are interested in a CAPP pet, read CAPP's Program page on our web site which fully explains our adoption process or talk to us at a pet adoption clinic.

animal.description:
*Meet n' greets for this pup, will be taking place on Saturday, 12/5. Please consider this before applying, as we will not be able to accommodate personal scheduling requests.* 

Obi-Wan Kenobi (DOB: 4/10/20) is a handsome, Husky mix that was surrendered to the rescue when his family could no longer care for him. At the time of his surrender, it was clear that Obi-Wan lacked structure, boundaries, and limits in his previous home. However, since coming into the rescue, all of that has changed. Obi-Wan's foster has established herself as the pack leader and has created an environment in which he is thriving. 

Characteristic of his breed description, Obi-Wan is energetic and alert. He enjoys romping around in the yard and tossing around his toys. Obi-Wan has been well-socialized with other dogs and would benefit from continued training. Obi-Wan would do best in an active adult-only home with working dog experience. 

In order to be considered as a potential adopter, we will need you to complete our online application at www.arrus.org. Should we choose to move forward with your family, you will be notified via email within the week. Due to the large volume of applications received, we are no longer able to respond to each and every applicant. We apologize in advance for the inconvenience and appreciate your understanding. 

Additional information and/or medical records for this rescue pet are available and will be reviewed in person should we choose to move forward in scheduling a meet n’ greet. In the meantime, please feel free to follow us on follow us on Instagram (animal_rescue_r_us) and visit our Facebook page at www.facebook.com/arrusadopt for more pictures and posts from his/her foster family. 

HELP US, HELP THEM! Animal Rescue R Us is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization. We do not receive county, state or federal funding and rely solely on donations. These donations help offset the cost of routine veterinary care, medical expenses, and other necessities while the rescue animal is in our  care. To make a secure donation, please visit www.arrus.org/donate . Alternatively, you may visit our Amazon Wishlist (http://www.amazon.com/registry/wishlist/C36VRV500R85) for a current list of needed supplies! All donations are tax-deductible and all are greatly appreciated. Thank you for your support!

The adoption counselors will be able to show you many that would be a good fit for your family. Animal House Shelter can not guarantee breed or breed mix of our adoptable animals. The animals are posted on the website as a breed or breed mix based on their physical characteristics they most resemble. We also can not guarantee the ages of our adoptable animals.

animal.description:
Hi I'm Charlie! I am a high energy dog that loves to play. Children and new dogs are my absolute favorite. The best part about my foster home is that we have guests over often and I think they are all coming to see me! I really enjoy laying on the couch with my foster family and love touching them with my paw or laying my head on their laps. I love my crate and know how to potty outside. I take my squirrel hunting very seriously but I've never been quick enough to catch one! I'd love a home with a big yard to run around in and a family who will embrace my sweet nature.

All of our pets start their journey in Memphis Tennessee where they remain in loving foster families until they are adopted.

In order to qualify for ALIVE Rescue Memphis's program all of the following steps must be met:

• You must be at least 21 years of age and be able to provide ALIVE with proof of age.

• Any current pets must be up to date on vaccinations, and be spayed/neutered. Exceptions to this will only be considered if proof of a medical explanation is provided.

• If you currently rent, you must provide a landlord’s phone number and a copy of your executed lease.

• All members of the family living in the home where the animal will be placed must be interviewed.

• Applicant must live within 50 miles of Memphis if interested in adopting and within 30 miles of Memphis if interested in fostering. 

•Allow an ALIVE Rescue Memphis representative into your home for a visit to insure that your home is safe for the potential new dog or cat.

•You must allow an ALIVE Rescue Memphis representative into your home for a visit to ensure that your home is safe for the potential new pet.

•You must be able and willing to spend the time and money necessary to provide training, medical treatment, and proper care for a pet.

•Currently, adoptions fees in Memphis are $275 for a dog over 4 months of age, $300 for a dog under 4 months of age.

•We require an additional $75 training deposit at the time of adoption. You will be required to enroll and complete a training class with your new companion at one of our approved training facilities. Once ALIVE Rescue Memphis receives proof of the completed class, this $75 deposit will be refunded.


Our adoption application can be found at http://www.aliverescuememphis.org/memphis-nashville-adoptions

Due to the extremely high volume of inquiries we receive, we ask that you submit an application immediately to start the adoption process. We try very hard to include all pertinent information in our bios. We are excited to help you find your new family member. However, ALIVE Rescue Memphis is operated 100% by volunteers. We want to spend our time saving dogs and assisting those adopters who have taken the time to complete an application. Thank you for understanding.

Breed selection is done in conjunction with two local vets and is not to be considered a guarantee but rather a well-educated decision from well qualified staff.

LIKE ALIVE Rescue Memphis on Facebook & Instagram!
Thanks for choosing rescue!!

animal.description:
Meet magnificent Max- This handsome pittie mix is looking for his forever person. At first glance, he might seem ferocious, but you'll soon find out that he's just ferociously goofy! Max can be a bit reserved when he meets new people, but once he warms up it's all about the belly scratches, ear rubs and snuggles. Max loves his person/pack and does not welcome strangers into the home or yard until he gets the ok from his people. Max responds well to a strong but loving leader and he is extremely food motivated. He is a very smart boy although it's sometimes overshadowed by his stubborness. Max is also potty-trained, crate-trained (yummy treat motivation needed since he's not a fan of the crate) and knows how to use a dog door. He will even sit and wait for his food until his person gives him the okay to eat. Max would love someone dedicated to continue teaching him leash skills and basic obedience training.

 This big boy has been living in his foster home for several months with a sassy 10 lb. terrier mix and they are good buddies- he even lets the little one boss him around. That being said, Max needs slow and proper introductions to other dogs and might do best as the only dog in the home so he can enjoy all your time and love for himself.

 Older children in the household would be preferred since Max isn't quite aware of his own strength and clumsiness in his tendency for rough play. Due to a very strong prey-drive, Max should not live in a home with cats. 

 Some of his favorite activities? Going for car rides, patrolling the yard and chasing away all the bunnies and squirrels that dare to invade his territory and lounging in the sunshine. Indoors, he's a very mellow boy who enjoys snoozing on the couch, looking out the window to watch for critters that need to be chased, chewing on his bones and destroying soft, fluffy toys.

 If you think you might be the person he has been eagerly waiting for, please submit an application to meet magnificent Max today!

*Homeownership required!

Adoption fee includes the following:


	Spay/Neuter
	Rabies Vaccination
	Distemper / Parvo Vaccines (includes series of 3 for puppies)

animal.description:
Hello
My name is Sadie. I am an Akita/German Shepherd mix gal that is about 6 months old and I weigh between 30 and 35lbs. I was part of an unwanted litter and rescue was contacted to go to a rural area to trap us. We had never known the kindness of humans and were very afraid. We now know how wonderful it is to be loved and never have to be hungry again. We have learned that we really...really enjoy being loved. We have lots of tail wags for our humans now. We are such good girls that need homes of our own now, to have the happy ending the nice rescue people promised us. Can you be the wonderful life we dream of?

animal.description:
I am trying to keep it cool, but you are making it hard, I am wishing your arms were wrapping me up tight… I wanna spend forever with you!  My name is Bellarini.  I am a 2 year old, 65 lbs, female, German Shepherd mix. I am a smart girl who is working on mastering all of that house and crate training business.  I am determined to get this stuff down and will be a professional in no time at all.  At first meet, I may be a little timid, but once I warm up we will be the best of friends.  I am a friend to other dogs and will need older children in my forever home. I would be fine living with a cat too.   I would also like to ask that I live in a house with a fence, so no apartment or big rig life for this big, active and sweet girl, please.  I need a home full of structure and routine. I thrive with it! My dream is to find an active family that will allow me join in on their adventures.  And if you wanna know if I wanna be your girl forever, just fill out that application for me, Bellarini.

My adoption fee is $150 and includes my spay/neuter, vaccinations, wellness exam, heartworm test, and microchip! If you're interested in meeting/adopting me, please visit www.rescueonespringfield.com/our-adoption-process/adoption-application/ and fill out the form! We do adopt out of state with vet references and video home check. *Adopter is responsible for coming to get the dog and returning the dog if the adoption does not work out* 

Don't forget to LIKE us on Facebook!-www.facebook.com/rescueonespringfield

*Remember, dogs are pack animals. Because of this, Rescue One does not adopt to outdoor-only homes. Pets are family and are not disposable.  Please make sure that you are 100% committed to a pet before considering adding one to your home.

animal.description: Dakota is a 6 year old spayed female black German Shepherd. She is a very energetic and driven dog. Loves to go on hikes and walks and she absolutely loves swimming. Her favorite toy is a ball and a log. She loves to chase small animals so no cats but especially loves to chase birds and airplanes. She walks great with other dogs and plays well with other dogs (outside of the home). Dakota is overly dominant and territorial in home when other dogs are present and does not get along with cats at all. She is friendly towards strangers and is great with children . She is fully house trained and crate trained. She has received formal obedience training. Dakota is in great health but does have a slight urinary incontinence which is control by medication Twice a week (DES). She is also very allergic to chicken and cannot have anything containing chicken products . Dakota is a very good dog and well trained however, she is very territorial in her own home (yard, house) and needs to be the only dog in the home.

animal.description: Roux is a 6 year old, American Staffordshire Terrier mix. Roux is very loving with her human and bonds strongly, so would be a very loyal companion. She's good with cats but not other big dogs. She might do okay with little dogs. Roux is potty trained, crate trained and does well on leash. Roux is heartworm positive but undergoing treatment, which is covered by the rescue until she is negative. If you are interested in meeting Roux, please apply at www.hhfrescue.org. The adoption fee includes vaccinations, bordetella, deworming, rabies, spay/neuter, microchip, a lifetime registration of the microchip, and sales tax. If adopting a puppy, the rabies and spay/neuter will be done at the same time by our vet once they are 4 months old and billed to us. It is against the law in the State of Texas for a rescue not to be sterilized so we have to make sure it gets completed and that we have record of it.

animal.description:
Good With Kids:  Not at this time
Good With Other Dogs:  Yes
Good With Cats: No
Housetrained: Yes
Crate Trained: Not needed
Walks Nicely On A Leash: working on it
Knows Basic Commands: yes
Energy Level (Couch Potato, Moderate or High):  Moderate
Special Needs: 

Arrival story:  Lucky Clover was pulled from a local shelter just 2 days before giving birth to her Lucky Seven pups!

Approximate age / Weight:  5 yrs/70 lbs

Personality:  Our girl Clover was busy the first 2 months being a mom.  Now that her puppies have found their forever homes, she is blossoming as she becomes comfortable in her foster home.  She likes to play in the yard and go on walks, and then she will settle in nicely to occupy herself with her toys.  She's discovered that it's quite wonderful to be brushed, and she's eager to please and willing to learn.  She's been making great strides when meeting new people and warms up quickly.  It appears Clover may have missed out on some important experiences early in her life as she can be shy and looks to her person for reassurance in new situations, but she is gaining more and more confidence as time goes by.  Clover's biggest accomplishment of late is her interactions with the resident dogs in her foster home.  She lives with small and medium-sized dogs and they are teaching her appropriate canine social rules.  She's been a quick study; however, she still gets a bit carried away during play so a confident dog pal who doesn't mind a little rough-and-tumble play would be a good match for Clover.

Clover is house-trained, doesn't need a crate, but still needs some work on leash. She's a very strong girl!! We think Clover has so much potential and will continue to make great strides in her confidence with more experiences under her belt. If you're a shep lover with an understanding of all things shep, you could be the special person or couple to continue her life's journey.

Forever home: Clover would do best in an adult household with experienced dog owners who will continue to build her confidence.  She'd do fine as an only dog; however, she's recently shown interest in playing with the resident dogs.  So, it would appear she wouldn't say no to a compatible canine playmate.  Sorry kitties, but Clover is not a cat person.   She would not do well in an apartment/condo setting, and no electric fences, please.


If you are interested in meeting a dog, please complete the Adoption Application on our website, www.waggintailsdogrescue.org>Adopt>Adoption Application.
 
ADOPTION INFO:
 
We do not have a facility; all of our dogs are fostered in private homes.   We generally have two adoption events per month.  To meet a dog in person, please see our event calendar on our website for the date and time of the next adoption event. Arrangements can be made to meet a dog outside of Saturday adoption events after an application is submitted and approved.

Our adoption process includes an application and in-home meet-n-greet with the dog.
   
-Adult Dog Adoption Fee - $225
-Small Breed Adoption Fee - $275
-Senior Dog Adoption Fee - $125
-Pup Adoption Fee - $250 plus $50 spay/neuter deposit refunded upon proof of surgery by 6 mos.
 
Thank you for supporting dog rescue and your interest in a rescue dog!

My friends tell me I'd do better in a home with older kids since I have so much energy, and I really want to be your one and only pet so I can have all your love to myself. If you think you and I would make a great match, set up a time to meet me today!

This amount only partially covers the cost of veterinary care, boarding fees, and other miscellaneous expenses involved in the temporary care and adoption of our dogs and is 100%25 tax deductible. Prior to placement, all dogs will be spayed or neutered, receive current vaccinations, and are usually microchipped. If not, arrangements will be made on an individual basis. Special consideration may be given to those willing to adopt older dogs or dogs with physical problems. Our adoption process begins with completing an application on-line. A phone screening will soon follow, and lastly a home visit will be conducted by our volunteers.

Kurt von Kusel is a 2 year old working line German Shepherd.  He is bred to work and needs someone with the skill to be his alpha pack leader.  To be seen as a strong pack leader, his owner should be firm and consistent and also possess an air of self assurance. A confident dog, his owner must have the proper German Shepherd experience with confidence that exceeds his.  An adult only, quiet, calm environment - one without a lot of visitors - would suit him best.  He enjoys both physical and mental stimulation.  With the proper owner, Kurt is a devoted and faithful companion.  He knows several commands, responds well to positive reinforcement and is playful.  He is housebroken, crate trained and meets both female and male dogs well and is sociable.  If you are a calm, assertive, skilled pack leader, Kurt would be an amazing partner and best buddy!

animal.description:
PAWS is currently closed due to COVID-19 and the mandated shutdown of non-essential businesses.  The animals are receiving the same high level of care as always, they'll just be staying with us a little longer.  During this time, we are taking application over the phone.  Until permitted to resume normal operations, we will be taking deposits and doing curb-side adoptions only.  We know it’s difficult to choose a lifetime companion animal from a picture but it’s been working out well for our adopters and most importantly, for the animals in our care. The financial impact is obvious but we're committed to keeping our community and our volunteers as safe as possible and providing the best of care for our animals.  Any donations are greatly appreciated to help PAWS provided that care.  Thank you.

UPDATE: Dean has proved to be too rowdy for a home with little kids and may be best as an only child.  Some dogs he’s ok with. Others not so much. So only pup is best. 
Introducing Dean, an 18 month old sweetie who is looking for a dog savvy adopter who can teach him how to be the best dog ever.   He was very gentle and well behaved while doing his glamour shots.  He’s very smart and seems quite eager to please those around him.  An adopter with experience with power breeds will be the best match for Dean.  We have discovered Dean’s theme song. Ain’t No Mountain High Enough!  This boy can clump darned near anything, especially a chain link fence. Did we mention how smart he is?  Dean will require a cat-free home. Dean is smaller than he looks, weighing in at 53 pounds.  His adoption fee is $175.

All of our animals are provided with age appropriate vaccinations, spayed/neutered and microchipped prior to adoption. 
PAWS has added the H3N2/H3N8 combo flu vaccine to its shot protocol. Every dog is being vaccinated upon intake, however we urge adopters to get a second flu shot for their new family member to ensure as much protection against the flu as possible.
To meet our incredible dogs and offer them the love they deserve, stop by PAWS on Friday, Saturday or Sunday from 10 - 4 PM, call us at 217-243-7297. We do applications in person or over the phone. You can also see pictures on our Facebook page, PAWS Jackson.  With an approved application, a deposit will hold your new best friend for up to 1 week to allow you time to come to PAWS.  This deposit is not refundable nor transferable.

Are you looking for an incredibly intelligent, quick to learn, eager to please  playful companion in your life?  If so Dickens might be the one for you. He would also be an excellent companion and friend for a lonely pet who needs a companion and friend to play with.  

Opt to Adopt! and give me a chance to love you! Copy/paste this link to your browser to fill out an adoption application for me at: www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org (under the adoption application button).

If you are interested in adopting a pet from Ahimsa Rescue Foundation the first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org 

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.

When you "Opt to Adopt" your ADOPTION PACKAGE INCLUDES:
-Pet that has been temperament tested
-Neuter/Spay
-Veterinary General Wellness Exam 
-Vaccinations: Rabies, DHPP, Bordetella
-Blood testing for heartworms, ehrlichiosis, lyme and  A Phagocytophilum disease  
-De-worming for hook, round, whip and tape worms
-Teeth Cleaning if needed 
-New ID Collar, slip leash and ID tags
-Microchip Placement and ID Tag
-Lifetime Registration of your Microchip with Avid microchip company.

There are many wonderful pets who find themselves homeless at no fault of their own.  Thank you considering a rescued companion from all our happy tails and everyone at Ahimsa Rescue Foundation! 

The first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org  To be considered for the adoption of a pet you must submit the on line adoption application.  

We hope to see your application soon.

animal.description:
Are you looking for an incredibly intelligent, quick to learn, eager to please  playful companion in your life?  If so Grantley might be the one for you.  Grantley loves people and gets along well with other dogs.  Grantley is playful , energetic and fun.  He would also be an excellent companion and friend for a lonely pet who needs a companion and friend to play with.  

Opt to Adopt! and give me a chance to love you! Copy/paste this link to your browser to fill out an adoption application for me at: www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org (under the adoption application button).

If you are interested in adopting a pet from Ahimsa Rescue Foundation the first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org 

Ahimsa Rescue Foundation’s adoption donation varies between $150 and $250 for each pet. Ahimsa Rescue Foundation invests on average $200 per dog on medical, microchip and incidental care.

When you "Opt to Adopt" your ADOPTION PACKAGE INCLUDES:
-Pet that has been temperament tested
-Neuter/Spay
-Veterinary General Wellness Exam 
-Vaccinations: Rabies, DHPP, Bordetella
-Blood testing for heartworms, ehrlichiosis, lyme and  A Phagocytophilum disease  
-De-worming for hook, round, whip and tape worms
-Teeth Cleaning if needed 
-New ID Collar, slip leash and ID tags
-Microchip Placement and ID Tag
-Lifetime Registration of your Microchip with Avid microchip company.

There are many wonderful pets who find themselves homeless at no fault of their own.  Thank you considering a rescued companion from all our happy tails and everyone at Ahimsa Rescue Foundation! 

The first step of the adoption process is the on line adoption application at www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org  To be considered for the adoption of a pet you must submit the on line adoption application.  

We hope to see your application soon.
Ahimsa Rescue Foundation
www.ahimsarescuefoundation.org
savingpaws@aol.com

animal.description:
Camben is a 2 year old red tri Aussie/Border Collie Mix with a gorgeous full tail. Camben is always smiling and happy to greet you. He prefers to be where the people are and will follow you from room to room or wait just on the other side of the closed door.  Camben is very good with other dogs of all sizes but is not good with cats, birds or other pocket pets. He warms up quickly to new people and has been introduced to children ages 1 to 16 with no issues. He is friendly with a moderate energy level and medium velcro tendencies. His favorite thing is riding in the car and he walks well on the leash. He is crate and house trained. So far Camben has not wanted to play with toys in his foster home but does like treats.  Camben prefers to eat his meals alone in his kennel. He will growl at his foster siblings if they are too close or nosey during meal time. He has not shown any other characteristics of resource guarding and takes treats softly and politely even in the group. Camben tested positive for heartworms, fortunately treatment is going well and we anticipate he will be healthy and ready to go to his forever home later this fall. Camben is fostered in Cimarron, KS.

Applications for adoption can be submitted at www.ns4ar.org

animal.description:
Everyone say hello to our fighter, Dana! This 5 year old pit bull mix came to us in May severely emaciated, lethargic, with diabetes, and a big will to live. We fueled that fire inside of her with lots of TLC, and today Dana is doing wonderful. She is diabetic and will require special food and insulin for the rest of her life. The cost for these medications are not overly expensive but you do have to have regular vet visits to ensure her levels are where they should be. She is also blind due to the diabetes. Her foster has nothing but wonderful things to say about her and her recovery. 

She is housebroken, and crate trained, and while this girl is newly blind and needs some guidance, she's maneuvering well in her foster home. She likes to carry her toys around and chew on them. Before she went blind she would try to chase the cats but now we don't believe she could find them as easily. She loves being doted on and groomed. Even enjoys her bath time! She is very treat motivated and takes treats gently. She knows sit and wait, and is a patient girl. She is not a fan of thunder, and fireworks, or gunshots, and will need some cuddle time during these events. She rides in the car well and is happy to tag along with you. She really is the sweetest, gentlest, most loving dogs, who just wants to be near her people at all times!
Dana is current on shots, licensed and microchipped. All dogs over 6 months have been heartworm tested, and all dogs are treated monthly for fleas/ticks (Nexgard or Frontline Gold) and are on Heartworm prevention (Heartgard Plus). All pets are spayed/neutered prior to adoption. All our dogs are temperament tested and "should" like dogs, cats, and kids unless noted. WE HAVE MORE PETS IN THE SHELTER THAT ARE NOT ON PETFINDER. Call with the pet's name and ID if you have questions on this pet. Save time, print out and bring our Pre-Adoption Form.

animal.description:
Aaron was a stray who showed up at a lady's house one day. The lady called us about him and we put him on our waiting list. Aaron stayed in her back yard for a few weeks until we had room for him. As you can see by the smile on his face, he is a very happy boy!! He is very sweet and loves everyone, including children and other dogs. Aaron is very active and high energy, so he will need a lot of exercise and play time from his new family, and he will give a lot of love in return! 

Aaron's date of birth is 3/31/2019 and he weighs about 50 pounds. 

We had a DNA test done on Aaron and found out he is 37.5% Boxer, 12.5% Belgian Malinois, 12.5% Standard Bulldog, 12.5% Labrador Retriever, and 25%Breed Groups: Asian, Herding, Sighthound. & Terrier.

You can submit an adoption application for this handsome boy at http://www.fayettefcar.com/applicationform, where you can also review FCAR’s adoption requirements.

All FCAR adoptable dogs have been spayed or neutered, are current on all vaccines, on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, microchipped, and come with a 30-day pet health guarantee. The adoption fee is $95 with an approved application. A fenced yard is required for Aaron.

animal.description:
If you have ANY QUESTIONS or are truly interested in adopting any animal from PAW Animal Shelter Please, fillout an adoption application FIRST! WE are a high intake No Kill Shelter ran by a staff of 4 and do not always have time to answer every question asked by so many. If you are a good fit for the animal you are interested in -we will call to speak with you, If we feel you are not a good fit , we will contact you about other pets that may be a good fit for your home. Many people are losing the opportunity to adopt the animal they want because they fail to put in an application and the pet was adopted before we could answer your email. .If you have applied for an animal in our facility and have not received a response within 7 days, PLEASE call or contact us again. Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

319-372-2274

animal.description: Hiccup, Hica for short, is a very sweet Shih Tzu Mix boy who's looking for a new forever home with his dad Gizmo! Their family has fallen on hard times and has to move in with relatives who already have dogs. They made the tough choice to ask rescue to help re-home Hiccup and Gizmo. Gizmo is a purebred Shih Tzu and Hiccup is his 5 yr old mixed son. Hiccup weighs just under 10 lbs, while Gizmo weighs about 12 lbs. They are both healthy, friendly little dogs.  We will have them neutered, vaccinated and chipped. Hiccup and Gizmo are good with other dogs and people them meet. They are playful without being hyper and generally well behaved. Hiccup and Gizmo don't have any behavioral issues or baggage. Hica has a happy small and will bring a lot of joy into any home. We will only adopt them out as a bonded pair. If you'd like to meet Gizmo and Hiccup and live in the Los Angeles area, please complete our adoption application found on dexterfoundation.com

animal.description:
Baron is an 80-90lb big hunk of love, male Pit Bull. He is super strong, energetic and goofy. 

Baron loves to go for walks, run around and play in his kiddie pool with water. Baron is LARGE and very strong and will require a family that is very experienced with bullies and or large breeds. 

Baron is a bit of a wild child and will need a family that will work on basic obedience training with him. He is working on not pulling on a leash and not jumping when he is excited. 

Baron is not good with other dogs and since he is so strong and large, will need a family that will keep him safe and be diligent about keeping him away from other dogs. We recommend kids over 16 in the home or an adult only home. No cats. Baron will need a fenced yard since he is energetic and loves to run around.

Baron is UTD on shots, microchipped and neutered. His adoption fee is $400.

animal.description:
Luke is a super playful five year old who decided to hang onto his puppy-ness! He loves to play and loves attention from his human family. He wants an active home where someone will play with him and let him be a lap dog. He has a stunning smile and is happy to meet everyone. He thinks he is a lap pet too and will gladly go for a car ride and sit on your lap if you let him. He seems to have an issue with other male dogs since he was neutered so late in life but has been great around females. We expect his issues with males to not last for long as his hormones can drive his brain for up to 6 months after neuter surgery. We want him to have a female fursister in the home because he really wants to have a fursister in his life. Sadly, Luke has flea-allergy dermatitis and will need to be faithfully given flea preventatives to prevent hot spots and sores from forming on his body. He also has heartworm disease, but the rescue will provide medication for slow kill treatment until he tests negative. Because we are foster based, we require an approved application before a meet and greet is scheduled. We think that is fair for our fosters so every meet & greet has the potential to result in an immediate adoption. The application is available on the rescue website and can be completed online. We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but we hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. Average adoption fees in our area are $175-$450 depending on the pet and the organization.

We work with many rescues and strive to find every rescued dog in our care a great home. Sometimes that means transferring that pet to another location where adoption may be more likely. We currently have partners in New York, Pennsylvania, and Vermont.

If you are interesting in meeting any of our pets, the process is to complete an application. It can be downloaded as a pdf document from our website and submitted by email to WindyRidgeRescue@gmail.com as a scanned document or as photos OR can be completed entirely online. Both links are in the header of our website.

Because we are foster based, we require an approved application to schedule a meet and greet. We feel that is fair to our fosters and rescues so every meet and greet can result in an adoption.

We do not have set adoption fees for dogs, but hope adopters will donate generously so we can rescue more. The medical care for every dog can easily exceed the adoption donation. Average adoption fees for dogs in the area range from $175 up to $450.

We ask for a minimum adoption donation of $50 for cats regardless of age. Each cat is up to date on vaccinations, dewormer, and microchipped. Larger donations are always welcome so we can rescue more. Medical care for each cat easily exceeds the minimum donation.

As with every rescue, our resources are limited and the need for rescue help is unlimited. Your generosity helps us to rescue more.

Adopting or fostering for a rescue frees up a space where a new rescue can reside.

If you can't adopt or foster, than please consider donating.

animal.description:
Danny Boy is a handsome 6-year old male Pit Bull Terrier mix who was brought to the HSOV on July 29, 2020 after he was picked up on Williamson Avenue in New Matamoras Ohio by the Washington County Dog Warden. Danny Boy was not wearing a collar so there was neither an id tag nor a dog tag to enable us to locate his owner .. And he was not microchipped.

Danny Boy has a dark brown/brindle short smooth coat with a large white bib on his chest, white paws, a long tail, and a sweet face with expressive brown eyes, a dusting of white on his muzzle, and short semi-erect ears. This good-looking guy has a happy outgoing disposition and a lovable affectionate personality. Danny Boy wiggles all over and wags his tail in anticipation of attention. He was in love with HSOV kennel tech Morgan Parsons and rewarded her with some great 'puppy kisses' after his photo session :)

Danny Boy weighs 52.2 lbs. 

In compliance with the Ohio Revised Code, Danny Boy was held for three days so that his owner would have an opportunity to reclaim him.  Sadly nobody came looking for him :(

This sweet boy seems to have a look of sadness in his eyes, and we look forward to the day when he is adopted by a fabulous individual or family and ‘his Irish eyes are smiling’ again.  

Danny Boy will be neutered in the near future (tentatively on October 28, 2020) and will be ready to find the home of his dreams.

UPDATE: Danny Boy was neutered on October 28, 2020 and was also given rabies vaccine.

Arf! I’m BLUEWATER-- I'm a husky/shepherd mix (born 3/31/2020) on an Indian Reservation in Arizona. I got a one way ticket onto The Rescue Train and came to Los Angeles with my 11 siblings and my momma when I was just 6 weeks old. I’m now a big boy that’s ready to leave the nest and am looking to be your new best friend! I am one of the "edgier" littermates so my adopter needs to be very experienced with my breed.

Being that I'm just a young adult, I am still learning how to be the best dog I can be. The Rescue Train has been working with a certified professional dog trainer and has invested a lot into my future! I'd love an adopter who is committed to continuing my training so I can grow to be an awesome adult dog.

I’m off to a great start learning crate training. My favorite activities include (but are not limited to) learning, playing with my toys, meal time, chewing on my nylabone, and belly rubs and being told I’m a good boy.

If you are looking for a smart active companion to do fun stuff with I hope you will come meet me!

animal.description:
Meet Patches -- she is a very sweet 4 year old Jack Russell Terrier. Patches was surrendered when she could not stand with her rear legs. It turned out that Patches had a disk issue and was in a tremendous amount of pain. After crate rest and physical therapy, she is much better now, and no longer seems to be hindered by pain. 

Patches did have a weight problem, but since she is now able to get exercise she has trimmed down nicely. She remains on a special diet, and her snacks are limited to mini training treats, celery, green beans and carrots, all of which she loves. 

Patches also loves long walks, car rides, play time, and will snuggle up when she is ready for a rest. She is a very funny dog, and keeps her foster mom laughing with her antics. She LOVES to cuddle up under a blanket, and will burrow under one till she gets it just the way she wants it. She is crate trained, and goes into it and gets completely under her blanket when she is ready to go to bed. In the morning, she patiently waits in her crate till it's time to get her day started. She is potty trained and will let you know when she needs to go out. She's a smart pup, is learning to sit and stay, and seems to enjoy training sessions. 

She loves meeting new people, and after enthusiastically greeting them, lays down on her back for a belly rub. Because of her excitability she would do best in a home without young children or other dogs. She has lots of energy and needs plenty of exercise.

We would love to see our wonderful Patches unite with her forever family!


If you are interested in Patches, click 'Apply for Adoption'!

If you're on Adopt-A-Pet or PetFinder, please visit 'https://www.hopeanimals.org/' to apply!


** Please note that due to COVID-19 and stay at home orders, we are not having our usual adoption events. The first step in the process is to submit an online application. Virtual meet and greets over the phone/computer will be set up before selecting the best fit for adoption. Thank you!

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue: 6/16/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Found as stray by a caregiver
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? none
Weight: 38.60 lbs
Height: 20 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? Yes

What kind of home would be best for me? Ringo would enjoy any home that is full of hustle and bustle. He wants to be active and the center of his family's life. Ringo will be best as an only dog. He would love a home where someone is home during the day - he has some separation anxiety and needs to learn that people do come back. Ringo would enjoy an active, outdoor lifestyle. He would do well with children over 12. Ringo's high energy is ready for adventure.

What is my personality like? Ringo is a young, happy dog who enjoys life. He is full of sunshine and all things wonderful about a dog. Ringo will be a close companion and prefers to check in for physical touch to make sure everything is OK. He may nuzzle a leg, sit closely or walk right next to you. When Ringo is playing with his friends, he is full steam ahead. When playtime is over, he will seek you out for snuggles and rest.

Ringo does not enjoy life in a crate. He has shown some separation anxiety when crated away from his pals and caregivers. He is overjoyed when he is reunited with his pals and our caregivers. Ringo is working on leash manners. He doesn't know any basic commands yet, but is very eager to please and would benefit from dedicated training to help him learn. Ringo will need training to understand his people will always return and time apart is normal.

How do I act when I first meet new people? Ringo thinks everyone is his new forever friend. He will greet you with wiggles and wags.

Other tips and tidbits: Ringo's estimated birthday is 6/16/2019

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.
