animal.description:
**SPECIAL NEEDS, PLEASE READ FULL BIO**

Eclipse came into rescue when her previous owner realized that she had unknown medical needs that she could not afford to get diagnosed or treated.  She knew she needed help, and selflessly surrendered her so that she could get the medical care that she needed.  

After a month in foster care we started the journey of finding out exactly what was causing this young girl to stumble, buckle her front and back legs and fall over. 

After x-rays and an MRI it was determined that Eclipse had wobblers disease (a genetic compression of the spine) and a secondary issue of a spinal cyst.  This is a lot for a 16 month old, to have going on.  

The good news was that Eclipse was young, had a zest for life and was otherwise a healthy Dane.  The decision was made that we needed to do what we could to give this amazing girl the life that she deserves. She had surgery in mid September to decompress her spinal cord (wobblers correction) and remove a cyst that had formed on her spine near the compression.  This was a difficult surgery, with a very long recovery time, and the expectation was that Eclipse may not walk or stand for more than 2 weeks, and could need assistance to walk for MONTHS.  But we were up for the challenge.  

Did I mention that Eclipse was a fire cracker? Well, she took the fast track, and walked out of the vets office on her own with just a bit of assistance with a harness.  Just a few days after being back in foster care she was becoming difficult to keep down and resting, she started to take her caregivers for walks, rather than them assisting her, she wanted  to chase the chickens and ducks at her foster home. She has defied all odds in her recovery, this due to her happy, vivacious personality.

It's been three months post surgery now, and she still walks a bit wonky. At her recheck the specialist discovered that her wobbler's compression has been completely corrected but that her spinal cyst had come back. This means she could require additional surgery at a later date. 

What to know about Eclipse; she is a 1.5 year old pup with the stamina of the Energizer Bunny, she has 2 speeds - full out play and sleeping.  She loves other dogs and has done well with every dog she has met, large,small, male or female. She would likely do fine with cats if properly introduced, but she does play rough, so it would need to be a dog savvy cat.  

Eclipse requires a house with no stairwells or lots of steps. She really needs to have a playmate in the house, when bored she tends to get into mischief, chewing on things, taking things off the counter etc. she is a counter surfer, and she has no shame, she will take what she wants right in front of you.  Eclipse is crate trained, and needs to be crated when left in the house alone, she will chew moldings and furniture if left free roam for too long in the house.  Eclipse needs some work on leash manners, and due to her spinal surgery will need to use a harness rather than a collar and leash.   She will run if left loose outside of a fence, she’ll comeback, but not until she is ready, and the chase is a lot of fun for her!  Eclipse has mastered the art of cuddles, she loves to lay on your lap and get some love, and when she wants attention she nudges her way into your space to let you know that she needs your undivided attention.  Eclipse has shown no food aggression, loves toys, but is willing to share, she has no boundaries with other dogs, so she needs to have tolerant, patient dog buddies in her forever home, that are willing to put up with her constant pestering to play.  Eclipse has a cute little habit of giving love nibbles, she does this to both her fur buddies and her humans, she seems to do it when she is happy and content,  foster mom calls them Clipsy love nibbles.  

Are you Eclipses family? If you have the energy, for this girl she will repay you with mountains of love, a ton of laughs at her silly antics and the best cuddles ever!  She was dealt a rough hand physically, but she has proven that nothing will get her down! 

Eclipse's adoption fee is $400 To apply to adopt Eclipse go to www.nwflgdr.com/adopt.

ATTENTION: NWFLGDR does not transport. If you are applying from out of area or out of state, understand that if your application gets approved, you will be expected to pick up the dane in the location that he/she is being fostered. In addition, if the adoption does not work out, it is your responsibility to bring the dane safely back to us.

animal.description:
Do you start your day with a cup of coffee? Two creams and two sugars? We recommend you skip the cup and start all your days AAD style with a tangy mixed blend named Cafe! We were first introduced to Cafe when he was just a young puppy who found himself abandoned at one of our partner shelters Miami-Dade Animal Services. He was very ill and received life-saving emergency medical care for two weeks and just like a great cup of coffee he came back even stronger. Once he received the all-clear our partners transported him up to us so we could assist him on his road to recovery. As a puppy, you couldn't deny the adorableness that was his wobbly legs and floppy ears but as we got to know him we noted Cafe would need a family willing to offer structure and guidance in order to teach & nurture a well-balanced dog. We are unsure what Cafe's past experiences were like, but they were during such an important stage in a puppy’s life. His true nature mixed in with his poor experiences was hindering him in ways we knew he would need careful guidance to overcome.  Cafe was adopted and he loved his new life very much but as he continued to physically grow and mentally mature his family realized their lifestyles just were not the right blend. He found himself back in our care and desperate for a new direction in life. Cafe is an enthusiastic boy that if left to his own devices will cause a bit of trouble but when pointed in the right direction that lively spirit can be used for so much good. He will tackle any agility course equipment with such eagerness just so you can give him a bit of praise. He has flourished with us in our training program and the skills he has learned will help him and his new family enjoy many fun adventures together. He truly does rely on one of his trusted humans to show him that something he might not have ever been exposed to before is safe to touch, explore, and possibly enjoy. He works harder for physical attention than any treat you can offer him but if treats are in play his taste buds truly jump for the world-renowned tiny sized basic milk bone. If you ask any of our staff one of our favorite things about Cafe is no matter the mood you are in his full body wiggle to greet you will fill your cup over with joy!

If you find yourself in need of an instant energy boost this robust blend just might be the pick for you!

To adopt Cafe, please fill out our adoptions questionnaire here: https://forms.gle/5heEH8S6c7zXBneD7

Contact our Adoptions team at adoptions@adoptadog.org or (914) 273-1674 for more information!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Jessie. Big Dog Ranch Rescue saved me and my sister Josie from a Georgia animal shelter as part of the 4th of July Freedom Bus. Albert is a 5 year old, male dachshund. He weighs about 17.5 pounds. 

Check out what Albert’s foster mom says about him. 

Albert is doing well. He is crate trained.  He surprised me by going out doggie door.  
He is eating well and pottying outdoors MOST of the time (pooped inside once). 
He doesn’t ask to go out, I just take him every hour or two.  
He barks when I’m fixing his dish.  Loves to cuddle.  Demands it actually. 
I think he’d do well in any home as long as the other dogs don’t run him over and the home has no more than one step— even to go out.  
Because he tries to do them.  What a lovely boy!
Albert does have weakness in his backend from mild IVDD.

His adoption fee will be $375.00 which includes neuter, full vax, microchip, HW & parasite negative, dental (if needed) and any other medical issues treated.

Albert is currently being fostered in Decatur, Al. 

Because of volume, we do not answer questions on this page.

House Trained: Most of the time
Crate Trained: Yes
Kid Friendly: Unknown at this time
Cat Friendly: Unknown at this time

You may apply to adopt at www.tndachshundrescue.com

A little about how the adoption process works:
We are an all volunteer rescue so please be patient with us.
We usually have pre-approved adopters waiting for the right dog so it is best to get your application approved beforehand so you can contact us immediately when you are interested in meeting a potential pet.

You will be contacted once the app is processed for a home visit.

animal.description:
Rooster is sooo sweet and loving. He was a very good boy for his intake and just let us do whatever we needed to do. He would take his paw and tap you for more pets?? He’s very affectionate, calm and laid back. 
He had 2 spots of hair loss. On the right side of his face and on his back. It looked like the hair was starting to grow back so I’m not sure what it was. He also had 2 small lumps/masses. One on his front right leg and one on the right side of his face. Both didn’t seem to be painful and they were soft.  Treated for HW's.   boxer mix; male; stray; 7/27; 4-5 yrs old; 56lbs.  Adopted mid October and returned early December as he kept getting out of underground fence.

Mr Doting!  My new volunteer friends called me Mr Doting, Mr Chill Master and Mr Attentive!  All labels suit me just fine and make me smile.   I'm a bigger boy with a big, blocky head all primed and ready to nicely sit by your side and keep you company.  I had a nice time running and exploring in one of the enclosed areas and when the pretty caramel colored female dog, Caramel came to say "Hi," well she really completed my fun excursion.   We respectfully greeted each other and in no time were relaxing side by side and the whispering secrets below the long cement bench!   My human friends noted that I'm a smart fellow who enjoys giving paw and nicely sitting when asked.   Sweet and loving,  slightly older kids would be a good match for me and a more submissive doggy companion (preferably female) would nicely compliment my bigger personality.    Ask for me, Rooster today!  And cock-a-doodle-do!

Hey! We're now best friends! My name is Otto and if you like big, fuzzy goofballs, I'm your pup! I love new friends both two and four-legged. I love a good grooming sesh so much that I can doze off while having a paw-dicure. My foster mom says I'm "a little extra" but I'm sure she means extra soft and extra handsome!

My doctors (who are also my best friends) say I've got Neuronal Degeneration, which means when I run I do a great impression of a kangaroo! It also means I might know you really made that breakfast for me but I don't have the balance to pull it off the counter, knock over trash cans, or jump on your furniture. I'll be livin' my best life if there aren't any stairs to my yard and carpet or rugs inside for traction.

The house I live in now has stairs but I don't pay them any attention. Don't feel sad if I don't follow you up, I'm just a single story kinda dog. I'm perfectly happy sleeping downstairs and catching some me time. I'll doze on your lap if you sit with me but sometimes I prefer napping outside connecting with my inner pyr!

Otto is looking for a for a long term medical foster home. Is that you?

All our dogs require secure VISIBLE fencing. All current pets in adoptive home must be spayed/neutered and up to date on vaccinations.

Looking for a smart, energetic dog buddy to be your activity companion? Ghost loves to go for long walks and jogs, especially if he can get away from the busy city streets. He also enjoys his playtime...he LOVES to roll in the grass and running full speed in the yard and tumbling head over heels like a gymnast :) He's very smart and picks up most new commands in minutes. With just a few days training he can add to his new trick arsenal - his focus is razor sharp! Ghost is a very cuddly dog and showing his affection to his family is important to him. Even at nap times this sweet boy would like to have one paw on a human. Ghost loves other dogs and loves to play with them. He would benefit in a home with a more experienced dog that can guide him and help him learn the boundaries and rules of his new home. Cats are fine and he often ignores them, though he would prefer if one played or cuddled with him :) He'd also do fine as the only dog, providing he gets plenty of attention and activity stimulation. We don't know much about Ghost's past but he is missing part of his ear and back toe so he may have been attacked when he was younger. His quirky ear perfectly captures his curiosity and goofball nature, and he doesn't seem to mind his toe which certainly hasn't slowed him down (all foot xrays are clear). He also has an issue with one of his hips which is managed with glucosamine, and again, does not slow him down one bit. Ghost will need an experienced Pyr owner to continue his training and bring out the best in this boy!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/rescue-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can call 877-739-3582 or email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

Josie is a 2 yr old, 53 lb Australian shepherd/lab mix. J


Josie’s sweet spirit is a testament to her resilience after a difficult start in life. Though always loved, Josie spent her first months in a confined environment, without much socialization or exercise—a tough combination for her breed. But she has come such a long way! She is the sweetest, most playful dog, with a lot of energy; she craves attention and activity, and she will reward your efforts with boundless joy and affection. Her favorite activities are stealing socks, barking at people out the window, and fetch (which she often takes up a notch by demanding to be chased). Although she absolutely loves meeting other dogs, she probably is best suited for a single-pet household. She adores kids and would make a wonderful family companion! She loves lots of attention, will benefit from lots of exercise, and loves to play fetch with a trusty tennis ball. Josie would love a fully fenced yard, if possible.

animal.description:
Meet Trey!  He was born approximately November 2017.  Trey started coming to one of our volunteer's homes and was chasing her outdoor kitties.  She chased him away multiple times but he kept coming back.  After doing this many times, she took him to the vet and had him checked for a microchip but he had none.  She posted notices but no one came forward to claim him.  Trey is very loving and super smart.  Unfortunately, he chases cats when they run but doesn't hurt them.   A home with cats would not be a good fit.   He is a great watchdog.  Nothing gets by him and he barks to alert that someone is coming.  During the time he's been fostered, we have noticed he likes children.  We believe his original owners had children.  Do you think you’re a match for Trey?  Trey an indoor only dog, except for potty breaks and requires a secure fenced yard. 

Trey is neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, deflead and available for adoption through Second Chance Kitty, a local non-profit 501(c)(3) organization dedicated to assisting cats, kittens and an occasional dog, escape a life of abandonment, abuse and neglect. Interested parties may contact us via email at 2chancekittys@gmail.com.  An application may be submitted at www.secondchancekitty.org.  A home visit is required.

animal.description:
We have a few quirkier little ones we have been working with and are looking for particularly understanding dog-savvy homes...

First up, introducing Suki!

This 5 year old chi only weighs 6lbs but he thinks he is much bigger and puts on quite the tough guy act with strangers!  Deep down he is just very insecure and tries to act fierce to make up for it, but when he bonds and picks his person he is just as fierce in his devotion and loyalty.  He has an independent streak as well and likes his space at times.  Suki does well with other small dogs in his foster home and we think he might feel more secure living as part of a “pack”.  He does tend to bond and protect one person so is looking for an adult home preferably with just one person he can devote himself to, and someone that understands the chihuahua breed and their quirks and issues.  

Please email njwoof@cs.com to meet him by appointment and submit an application from our website www.secondchance.petfinder.com


Due to COVID-19, we will not be holding our Sunday adoption events until further notice, but we can schedule socially distant appointments with a specific dog outdoors at our vet’s office:
VCA Morris Plains Animal Hospital 
3009 Rt 10 East 
Morris Plains (Denville on GPS) NJ 07950
Now is the perfect time to open your home to a needy dog!  Submit an application from our website www.secondchance.petfinder.com to speed up the adoption process

I love all dogs and really enjoy hanging out in my crate with the door open. I’m a good girl and haven’t chewed up anything in the home but I do enjoy relocating shoes so my humans can’t find them. Leashes still really scare me. I live with 4 kids but my foster mom thinks I would do better in a calmer house with no kids. It will take me time to warm up to my new family but with treats and time I will come along. I do not like cuddling but I will lay in bed with you just not too close please. I was born in July 2016.

Included with adoption: Age-appropriate vaccinations, up to date heart-worm preventative, heart-worm test if over 6 months, insurance for 30 days, microchip with registration, and spayed or neutered- if not already, a voucher is provided.

animal.description:
Ivy is looking for a special family. Not just any family- a VERY special family that will understand she’s had a difficult and scary life. Ivy was rescued from a puppy mill. She arrived at NGPR very unfamiliar with human interaction and scared of almost everything. Despite her fears, she is a very sweet girl. She is making progress but has a long way to go. Ivy prefers to be indoors in her crate, where she knows she is safe. She will venture out, once she is comfortable, to lay with her humans for short periods of time, but her new family will need to be very patient and give her lots of time to adjust. As a result of Ivy’s fears, house training has been a work in progress. Her new family will need to help her understand that she is safe going to the bathroom outside. She is currently being taken out every couple of hours to avoid accidents in the house. Ivy seems more comfortable going outside at night than during the day. She is good on a leash but is too nervous to go out for walks in the neighborhood. Ivy doesn’t have any basic obedience training. Due to her anxiety, bad behavior hasn’t really been an issue as she doesn’t venture anywhere she could get in trouble. Ivy’s perfect home is a quiet home, perhaps out in the country, as loud neighborhood noises make her very scared. Ivy would benefit from another confident dog to help her feel more secure and show her the world is not so scary. She's looking for a family that doesn’t need immediate love and affection from their dog, but Ivy will thank you for your endless patience in different ways. Watching her very slowly come out of her shell will be the best reward for her new people. We understand that a dog like Ivy is not for everyone, this special girl requires a special place to live. We know the perfect family is out there for her. If you have a quiet home filled with patient, understanding and loving humans--well then maybe it’s the pyrfect retreat for sweet Ivy.

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Hello my name is Hazel and I am a female Jack Russell mix around 10 years old young and I weigh 14 lbs. I am an unbelievably sweet girl from North Carolina that picked up and care for temporarily until my stray hold as the shelter had many calls about me wandering around and people were being mean and throwing rocks at me to get me off their property and someone even drove me several miles away to get rid of me but found my way back. I was very thin and the heat was getting to me so the shelter there asked this nice rescue to take me in, thank God! Now I am so happy to be in a loving cool home and I am am enjoying good food too! I have been to the Vet since arriving and it seems that I am almost blind so it is a miracle that I was not killed when the folks in NC were being so nasty to me and  not helping me at all. I am pretty malnourished now and diabetic from all the neglect but I am still nothing but sugar and spice and everything nice. I love attention and relish any love given to me and boy do I love a good belly rub! I am good with other dogs and slightly curious about the cat but I would never hurt a thing. I am crate trained but I do not like the crate very much and you do need to be able to let me out and keep me on a schedule. If you would like to adopt me, please fill out an application on the rescue's website www.floprva.org that is always the first step to be considered to adopt from this rescue who saved my life, just for you! 

Love, Hazel xo

animal.description:
Marla is a sweet and loveable girl!! She loves her people and bonds quickly with whoever showers her with love!!! At around 55 lbs, she is on the larger side of medium, but her short legs make her appear more demure! We would call her a medium energy dog as she will run and play as long as she wants, she would prefer a fenced in yard!! She loves to rest her head on your shoulders and get hugs. Marla looks at each toy as a deconstruction challenge. She will show you exactly what its made of so you know for next time :). She does well with dogs one on one, mostly boys, with slow introductions. She must be in a cat-free home due to the hound in her. She also would do best in a home with older kids due to her lack of boundaries. She is house trained, does NOT love her crate but tolerates it, and does not show any food aggression at all (with dogs or humans)! She is very smart and is doing well learning her commands. She really would love a home where she could get hugs and kisses all day, walks and a nice fenced back yard! 

Marla is a four year old, 55lb, female Hound mix. As part of her $250 adoption fee, she is spayed, microchipped, and up-to-date on vaccines, and monthly flea/tick and heart worm preventatives. If you have questions about Marla, you can email Dogteam@pawsforlifenc.org. If you wish to adopt Marla, you can fill in an online application for her here: http://pawsforlifenc.org/pet-adoptions/apply-for-adoption/.

Note: Dogs are pack animals and do not do well away from other members of their pack. The adopter is the alpha member of the pack, and the dog or puppy needs as much one-on-one contact with the alpha as possible. For this reason, all Route 66 Rescue Inc. dogs are adopted to inside homes only. They must be on leash, or inside a secure fence when outside, and not left outside alone when no one is home. Invisible fencing does not qualify as protection since other animals and strangers have access to the dog. The dogs must be returned to Route 66 Rescue, Inc. if ever given up by the adopter. Thank you for understanding we want only the best for the dogs you give a forever home.
 
Please complete and return the adoption application to meet any of our adoptable dogs.

animal.description:
Duke is available for adoption through Colorado Canine Rescue, a nonprofit rescue in the Denver area. He came from a crowded shelter in New Mexico where he was turned found as a stray. Since we have little history on him, we are estimating his age to be around 1-2 years old and think he might be a Cattle Dog/Husky mix due to his working drive and gorgeous eyes..

Duke is a playful guy who loves people. He is a high energy dog who needs mental and physical exercise and would do great in an active household or as an exercise buddy. He is a smart dog and knows some basic commands but would benefit from continued basic obedience and leash skill building. Duke is working on his manners with other dogs, and would be best suited living with a tolerant dog his size or as an only dog. Duke doesn't do well with cats or small dogs and would do best living in a home (no apartments or condos) with children 12 or older.

If you are interested in adopting Duke, please submit an adoption application located on our website, coloradocaninerescue.org. We are asking for a $200 adoption donation. Duke is neutered, housebroken, up to date on vaccinations and microchipped.

CCR cannot hold dogs, arrange meet and greets or adopt out any dogs without a completed adoption application.

CCR cannot guarantee the breed composition or ages of our dogs as we usually have no history prior to them entering the shelter.

Dogs listed as potty trained may experience an adjustment period as they learn the routines in their new home.

animal.description:
Hello everyone! My name is Lucy and they tell me I am a nine-month-old all American breed- whatever that means!? I am currently hanging out with what they call a foster family. I have a foster mom, three four-legged foster brothers and an old crotchety foster sister! I like other dogs and want to play more, but these guys are pretty low key! 

I spend my free time chewing on bones and toys-I could do it for hours. My foster mom gives me LOADS of stuff to chew on so I do not go and find stuff I am not allowed to chew!  I was not introduced to many new people in my first home, so I bark at people and can be very shy when I meet new folks. My foster mom has been taking me to new places and I am meeting new people! Once I am comfortable, I LOVE to cuddle and be beside you. I just need a little time to trust you. I like going on small walks and enjoy that time with humans! I prefer the big two legged as the little ones make so many crazy noises and run  around and that scares the tar out of me and I will bark and growl to try to keep those little terror machines away!  I have been working on my confidence building skills and I am learning to love trying new things! 

My rescue family has taken me to a training class and they reward me for trying new things- those rewards are great- they call them treats!!! I  LOVE treats! I do not think I have tried one that I did not find delicious! My foster mom says I will be taking another class and I can not wait! Maybe my forever family will take me too!! 

I am learning this world has many great things to offer and may not be as scary as I originally thought. I am currently recovering from surgery because I kept having what the vet called UTIs. I had to potty all the time! It was awful. Because of this, I am not what my foster mom calls house-trained. She says this surgery should really help me not have to potty so much and we can start working on that soon! 

Well, I gotta go- lots of bones to chew!! Hope to meet you soon!

Our adoption process starts with our application. Once the application is approved, a member of Legacy will contact you to set up a home visit. The home visit usually last 1-1 1/2 hours and is to make sure our dog and any current dogs/cats are getting along, as well as both of us agreeing it's a fit. At this time the adoption fee is due, and begins the 2 week trial. We will check in during the 2 week trial. If it's not working, our dog is returned to the foster home and all except $100.00 {$75 if Senior} of the adoption fee is returned. At the end of the 2 week trial, you decide if you will finalize the adoption - if finalized, the Adoption Contract is signed and all medical records are turned over to you. If at any time you need to rehome the dog it contractually needs to be returned to Legacy Dog Rescue.

ADOPTION FEE's:
Puppies under 6 months:  $199.00
Adults:  $150.00
Seniors (over 7 yrs):  $99.00

If you are interested in one of our dogs please fill out an application: 
https://form.jotform.com/193425528783165

animal.description:
Helen came to us from a owner who had to move and could not take her along. This is heartbreaking since Helen is a special dog, she cannot see or hear. Could you imagine loosing your home, your owners and not being able to navigate this world? Well, Happy Hearts came to the rescue.

Helen is a 2 year old Belgium Mal and is thriving in her foster home. She is now showing signs of affection, love and confidence. Plus, she gets along well with the other small pup in the home!

Helen is incredibly smart and will need a strong, dedicated owner who can give her a daily job or activite to help her feel fulfilled. She can socialize with other dogs, large and small, but should be supervised.

Since she e is lacking hearing and sight and requires proper guidance. She is completely dependent on her nose, taste, vibrations, and her owners guidance.

It has taken a lot of time, training and resources to see her come this far.

Are you interested in meeting Helen or donating to her cause? If so, please let us know!

Interested in learning more, let us know! https://happyheartsgsr.org/

animal.description:
Meet Benz! Benz holds a special place in a lot of people's hearts. He's one that we will be very picky who he goes to, so please read through the entire description before applying for him. Benz was picked up on the streets of Lockhart with his brother at just 8 months old. Benz has been doing great on his leash walking and has picked up so many good behaviors and tricks.... Benz gets along with lots of dogs and is very trainable. 

Benz is still young and is going through a fear period right now. New things make him put on the breaks, but if you are patient with him, he comes around. He spent some time at the trainers house where he really likes laying around outside or in the different dog beds. He is NOT the kind of dog you can adopt today and bring to the dog park tomorrow. Benz will need someone who is patient and willing to let him do certain things on his own.

Benz was fostered by a wonderful family who desperately wanted him after the first day home. He fit in great with their other dog and LOVED the laid back, quite lifestyle they were providing. Unfortunately Benz is still working through his fear period and he is reactive right now to small children. Other than that the fosters said he was perfect in every way. So smart and so kind. He is the trainer's house currently working through his child issues and is doing quite well (videos posted soon) but he is not completely comfortable around kids. Therefore we will not be adopting Benz to anyone who has small children at this time. Nor anyone who lives in a apartment or in a neighborhood with lots of kids around so that Benz can continue his wonderful progress. 

Benz is NOT looking for a super active outdoor lifestyle. He is VERY content laying around the house or the back yard. He doesn't need long walks and would prefer at this stage to not venture out to dog parks or other outings. But he definitely has energy playing and run with a person or another dog. After all, he's still a big puppy! In my opinion, This boy would be PERFECT for someone who lives a little more isolated, doesn't have kids around (for now), and is looking for a "hang out with you" companion. Someone who is patient and will let Benz decide things at his own pace. For example, he's been at the trainer's house for a week now and doesn't feel like coming inside. He's very happy to sleep in the climate controlled dog room... so that's where he hangs. For 2 days he wouldn't go in his new crate, so he didn't have to. After a few feedings with the door open, he goes in happily and stays in for hours when needed. He's SUPER smart...SUPER willing to shape new behaviors...and SUPER chilled. He does, however, mimic the dogs around him... so if your current dog is a fence fighter or reactive, Benz is NOT the dog for you because he will gladly do the same...all 60 lbs of him! 

If you think you can provide the safe, loving home Benz so desperately deserves, We want to hear from you!!! You can apply for Benz TODAY! Please visit our website, YouTube Channel, or Facebook page for more information. www.pawsinprison.com @pawsinprison Paws In Prison-Lockhart, TX

animal.description:
Lilly has a heart of gold and is eager to please her humans. She is a 7 year old pit terrier mix with the cutest floppy ears, who has been through a lot in her day - including surviving heart worm. She loves treats and is a quiet girl. She will need a home with patient humans who can show her that love and consistency exist. Once she forms a bond with her human(s), she is very loyal and loving.



She must have graduated at the top of her manners class. She is fully house trained, does not jump on furniture or people, she doesn’t bark at guests or distractions outside. She has a thing for shoes, but rather than chewing them she cuddles with them. She is crate trained and behaves well enough to be left loose in the house.



She is the perfect mix of athletic and calm. She is content cuddling in her bed most of the day, but can run for miles. She is great in the car and loves to go for rides with you. She finds long walks and new places stressful, taking comfort in slow, peaceful introductions to new things. With patience, positive reinforcement, and baby steps she may warm up to being an adventure dog, but for now she likes to sniff in yards or open parks (not dog parks). 



She needs a home with no other pets as she has a history of dog and cat aggression and prefers a fenced back yard that she can sniff and play in.

Chrissy is a sweet senior girl who loves her treats, taking naps, and going anywhere with her foster mom. She greets visitors with a friendly demeanor.

Crissy is potty trained and knows basics direction like sit, move, and go. She is completely housebroken and crate trained. She would love to chase the cat, but she’s easily distracted by food.

In general, Chrissy is a calm, quiet lady who loves to be sung to. She will make a wonderful companion for someone who lives quietly and wants a serene Boxer girl to love.

***For more information about this dog and information on how to apply to adopt, please visit www.ncbr.org***

Adoption Process At a Glance:

- Step 1 – Fill out the Adoption Application
- Step 2 – Preliminary Screening by Application Team which includes a Landlord check (if applicable) and vet Check
- Step 3 – Meeting with appropriate boxer(s)
- Step 4 – Home Visit
- Step 5 – Adoption Day


Adoption Requirements At a Glance.

    * You must be 21 years of age
    * You must have a fenced in yard (exceptions can be made for certain dogs)
    * All current pets in the household MUST be spayed/neutered and current on shots (yes, we do call and verify this information)
    * Applicants with young children will be required to answer additional questions
    * Applicants that rent must provide Landlord contact info. NCBR requires verbal landlord approval for all renters.
    * We no not do adopt female boxers into homes with other large breed female dogs
    * We do not adopt out dogs as gifts
    * All pets must be INDOOR companions!
    * NCBR does not adopt outside of the Northern California or Reno/Tahoe area.

animal.description:
Kiiro was born to a stray mama in the rescuer's neighborhood.  He was taken in after weaning and she has worked with him extensively.  

With a guesstimated birthday in Dec. 2019, Kiiro is still mostly puppy.  His mama is American Staffordshire mix and dad is husky with either Carolina Dog or shepherd genes.

Kiiro is a sweet boy, but will bark initially at strangers and views them with suspicion.  He prefers other polite dogs.

Kiiro gets along with cats and ignores the ones in his foster home.   He'll chew, so should be offered plenty of authorized things to chew on.  He's house-trained and leash-trained with very gentle manners under most circumstances.  

Barking is typical in a new home environment for Kiiro.  He's expressing his discomfort, but will settle in within a few days.  We recommend his new family crate him when he can't be supervised as he's been known to jump on his foster's kitchen table.  He's most comfortable in a 42" crate so he can sprawl if he chooses.  An old (but clean) blanket to lay on is preferred so he isn't laying on a hard surface.

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
Cool Hand Luke, 2, greets us each morning with a double-eared salute and a Mona Lisa smile on his face. He's one of those dogs who NEEDS his own Instagram account, mostly because we can't bear to be without seeing his sweet face every day.
It's hard to tell what he's thinking - but he's always got his head tilted, and that crooked little smile beaming up at us. This boy has swagger and sweetness. Luke is a gentle, curious guy with a kind of dreamy personality. He always looks like he's lost in thought, floating somewhere, a million miles away from the hustle of shelter life.
On leash, Luke is more focused and has begun checking in with us on walks, growing more attentive the more he relaxes.
Luke came to us from Albany Humane Society, where he had a reputation for being and easy guy who is good with other dogs. He would love to end up with someone who is playful and fun, and a more active home would be ideal for him.
If you're interested in a friendly, gentle, independent guy, he is so worth a look. Please fill our an application and email it to us. We'll set up a time for you to come out and spend some time with him. We are pretty surge you're going to love him.

animal.description:
Cheese has the best grin in America. Left behind at our gate one night, when this petite wigglebottom unicorn first smiled up at us, something inside us shifted a little. Because, look! Look at those tiny, crooked little picket fence toofers! With a couple missing up front! When Cheese smiles, 2020 doesn't seem so bad after all. Pandemic? Who cares? You've got Cheese! What else do you need? Okay, a bottle of wine. You need a bottle of wine. But, still; you're halfway there! Cheese is crazy about people and is unapologetically flirtatious with everyone who crosses her path. This girl has no shame, and we adore her for it. She's the kind of dog who will break out into a happy dance when you walk back inside from getting the mail. YES! You're back! That was the loneliest 36 seconds ever! Welcome home - now rub the belly!
We don't know her backstory, but Cheese will need to be an only dog in her new home. People are her thing - other dogs? Not so much. If you're looking for a joyful, wiggly, affectionate companion, please fill out an application for Cheesy-Cheese. Email it to info@pawsatlanta.org and we'll get you set up to come out and meet our girl. She's the bomb, y'all.

animal.description:
Ice Cube was rescued after living most of his life on a chain and surviving on table scraps. He had severe heartworm when he was rescued and wasn't expected to survive. 

With lots of love and TLC, he is now heartworm negative and loves living the good life of an inside dog. He gets along with his doggy and kitty foster siblings and loves snacking on whatever veggies his mom drops while cooking dinner. 

Ice is a senior dog who's content to nap away most of the day. He loves walks but goes slow and his favorite thing to do is play with his ball. 

Location: Houston, TX

IN-STATE ADOPTION ONLY 

If you’re interested in completing an adoption application, go to https://loveandrescue.com/adopt/ and click on the adoption tab

Please ONLY call the number listed on our page if you HAVE filled out an adoption application. 

-----------------------------------------------------------------------------

Love And Rescue Adoption Requirements:

All interested adopters must have/understand ALL of the following before being considered as a potential adopter. We take placing an animal's life in your hands very seriously and want to ensure we are doing the best thing for both the animal and for you.

- Valid Drivers License
- Be over the age of 23
- Renters must show proof or provide information to verify that the pet is allowed at the residence
- Be willing to have an in-person interview to go over expectations for both you and the animal
- Be willing to have a Love And Rescue volunteer do a home visit
- Dog Adoption Fee: $150 / Cat Adoption Fee: $75
- MUST FILL OUT THE LOVE AND RESCUE ADOPTION APPLICATION (Link above)
